{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines", "text_new": "{{pp-protected|reason=Persistent addition of [[WP:INTREF|unsourced or poorly sourced content]]|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in the Philippines}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Philippine English|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines\n| map1            = COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in the Philippines.svg\n| legend1         = {{center|Map of provinces (including Metro Manila) with confirmed (red) COVID-19 cases (as of April 5){{refn|group=note|name=PHmapnote|Breakdown of confirmed cases is according to the [https://ncovtracker.doh.gov.ph/ COVID-19 Case Tracker] of the Department of Health. Take note that the map may not reflect all affected localities and is primarily based on the recorded place of residence of confirmed cases. Patients with confirmed COVID-19 infection may be referred to a health facility than their recorded place of residence. See [[#Affected regions|Affected regions]] section below for a more comprehensive list of affected localities.}}}}\n{{legend|#3a0000|500+ confirmed}}\n{{legend|#510000|100\u2013499 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#900000|71\u201399 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#c80200|51\u201370 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#ee7070|21\u201350 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#ffC0C0|1\u201320 confirmed}}\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = Philippines\n| first_case      = [[Manila]]\n| arrival_date    = January 30, 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=30|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China\n| active_cases    = \n| confirmed_cases = 3,246\n| suspected_cases = \n| severe_cases    = \n| recovery_cases  = 64\n| deaths          = 152\n| territories     = [[Regions of the Philippines|16 out of 17 regions]] affected\n| website         = {{ubl|{{URL|http://www.covid19.gov.ph}}|{{URL|https://www.doh.gov.ph/2019-nCoV}}}}\n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have spread to the [[Philippines]] on January 30, 2020, when the first case of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) was confirmed in [[Metro Manila]]. It involved a 38-year-old Chinese woman who was confined in the [[San Lazaro Hospital, Manila|San Lazaro Hospital]] in [[Manila]]. The second case was confirmed on February 2, that of a 44-year-old Chinese man who died a day earlier, which was also the first confirmed death from the disease outside mainland China.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ramzy|first=Austin|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/02/world/asia/philippines-coronavirus-china.html|title=Philippines Reports First Coronavirus Death Outside China|date=February 2, 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live|last2=May|first2=Tiffany}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/250815-coronavirus-what-we-know-about-first-death-outside-china|title=Coronavirus: What we know about first death outside China|date=February 2, 2020|work=Rappler|access-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live|agency=Agence France-Presse}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/02/02/20/coronavirus-what-we-know-about-first-death-outside-china|title=Coronavirus: What we know about first death outside China|date=February 2, 2020|work=ABS-CBN News|access-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live|agency=Agence France-Presse}}</ref> The first case of someone without travel history abroad was confirmed on March 5, a 62-year-old male who frequented a Muslim prayer hall in [[San Juan, Metro Manila|San Juan]], [[Metro Manila]], raising suspicions that a community transmission of COVID-19 is already underway in the Philippines. The man's wife was confirmed to have contracted COVID-19 on March 7, which was also the first local transmission to be confirmed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/6/san-juan-muslim-prayer-hall-coronavirus.html|title=San Juan prayer hall frequented by coronavirus patient temporarily closed|publisher=CNN Philippines|website=cnnphilippines.com|date=March 6, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/business/03/06/20/greenhills-mall-implements-precautionary-measures-vs-coronavirus|title=Greenhills Mall implements 'precautionary measures' vs coronavirus|publisher=ABS-CBN News|website=news.abs-cbn.com|date=March 6, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n<!-- When changing the updated number of confirmed cases, add a source for the number. -->\nAs of April 5, 2020,<!-- Manually ppdate this at the end of the Phil working day, as the DOH gives updates around 4pm local time--> there have been 3,246<!-- The DOH gives updates near the end of the Phil working day, about 4pm--> confirmed cases of the disease in the country. Out of these cases, 152 deaths and 64 recoveries were recorded. Some 16,368 have been tested so far. <ref name=\"COVID-19 tracker\">{{cite web|url=https://ncovtracker.doh.gov.ph/|title=COVID-19 Case Tracker|website=doh.gov.ph|publisher=[[Department of Health (Philippines)|Department of Health]]|url-status=live|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://endcov.ph/dashboard/|title=COVID-19|last=|first=|date=March 27, 2020|website=COVID-19|publisher=University of the Philippines 2020|url-status=live|access-date=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/multimedia/infographic/03/17/20/tracking-covid-19-cases-in-the-philippines|title=Tracking COVID-19 cases in the Philippines|date=|work=ABS-CBN News|accessdate=March 24, 2020|url-status=live|publisher=ABS-CBN Investigative and Research Group}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/specials/content/137/covid-19-dashboard/|title=COVID-19 Dashboard: Summary of Confirmed Coronavirus Disease 2019 Cases in the Philippines|date=|work=GMA News Online|access-date=March 24, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.inquirer.net/novel-coronavirus-update|title=Novel Coronavirus Update|date=|work=Inquirer|accessdate=March 24, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The largest single-day increase in the number of confirmed cases was on March 31, when 538 new cases were announced.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/732050/philippines-covid-19-cases-now-2-084-deaths-rise-to-88/story/|title=Philippines' COVID-19 cases now 2,084; deaths rise to 88|first=Julia Mari|last=Ornedo|work=GMA News|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> Meanwhile, the smallest single-day increase since the last week of March was on April 4, when only 76 new cases were announced.\n\nThe [[Research Institute for Tropical Medicine]] (RITM) in [[Muntinlupa]], Metro Manila, is the medical facility where suspected cases are being tested for COVID-19 since January 30, 2020. Before that date, confirmatory tests were made abroad. Currently, five sub-national laboratories (in Davao, Cebu, Northern Luzon, Metro Manila, and the Lung Center of the Philippines) are also conducting testings while thirty laboratories are still undergoing proficiency testing before use.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1250910/fwd-doh-more-laboratories-expected-to-be-opened-for-covid-19-testing-within-the-week|title=DOH: More COVID-19 testing labs expected to open|first=Daphne|last=Galvez|publisher=Philippine Daily Inquirer|website=inquirer.net|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1098214|title=Private labs for Covid-19 testing to open this week|first=Ma. Teresa|last=Montemayor|publisher=Philippine News Agency|website=png.gov.ph|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSeveral measures were imposed to mitigate the spread of the disease in the country, including bans on travel to [[mainland China]], [[Hong Kong]], [[Macau]], and [[South Korea]]. On March 7, 2020, the [[Department of Health (Philippines)|Department of Health]] (DOH) raised its \"Code Red Sub-Level 1,\" with a recommendation to the [[President of the Philippines]] to impose a \"public health emergency\" authorizing the DOH to mobilize resources for the procurement of safety gear and the imposition of preventive quarantine measures.<ref name=\"phconfirms\">{{cite news|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/728715/doh-recommends-declaration-of-public-health-emergency-after-covid-19-local-transmission/story/|title=DOH recommends declaration of public health emergency after COVID-19 local transmission|date=March 7, 2020|accessdate=March 7, 2020|url-status=live|publisher=GMA News Online}}</ref> On March 9, President [[Rodrigo Duterte]] issued Proclamation No. 922, declaring the country under a state of public health emergency.<ref name=\"phe\">{{cite news|last=Parrocha|first=Azer|url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1095955|title=State of public health emergency declared in PH|date=March 9, 2020|accessdate=March 9, 2020|url-status=live|publisher=Philippine News Agency}}</ref>  On March 12, President Duterte declared \"Code Red Sub-Level 2,\" issuing a partial lockdown<!-- common term for 'community quarantine' --> on Metro Manila and extending the metropolis' class suspensions up to April 12, to prevent a nationwide spread of COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/729459/code-red-sub-level-2-duterte-announces-tougher-measures-vs-covid-19-threat/story/|title=Code Red Sub-Level 2: Duterte announces 'community quarantine' vs. COVID-19|date=March 12, 2020|publisher=GMA News Online|url-status=live|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/12/COVID-19-Metro-Manila-restrictions-Philippines.html|title=Duterte declares lockdown of Metro Manila for 30 days due to COVID-19|date=March 12, 2020|publisher=[[CNN Philippines]]|url-status=live|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> The class suspensions were later extended up to April 14 through a memorandum circular released by Malaca\u00f1ang on March 14.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/729643/classes-canceled-in-metro-manila-until-april-14-2020-due-to-covid-19-threat/story/|title=Classes canceled in Metro Manila until April 14, 2020 due to COVID-19 threat|date=March 14, 2020|work=|accessdate=March 16, 2020|url-status=live|publisher=GMA News|website=gmanetwork com}}</ref> On March 16, the entirety of [[Luzon]] has been placed under an \"[[2020 Luzon enhanced community quarantine|enhanced community quarantine]].\"<ref name=\"luzon lockdown\">{{cite news|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/729875/duterte-orders-lockdown-of-entire-luzon-due-to-covid-19-threat/story/|title=Duterte orders lockdown of entire Luzon due to COVID-19 threat|first=Virgil|last=Lopez|publisher=GMA News|website=gmanetwork com|date=March 16, 2020|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref> On March 17, President Duterte issued Proclamation No. 929, declaring the Philippines under a [[State of emergency|state of calamity]] for a tentative period of six months.<ref name=\"state of calamity\">{{cite news|last1=Kabiling|first1=Genalyn|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/17/duterte-declares-state-of-calamity-over-ph-for-next-6-months-amid-rise-in-covid-19-cases/|title=Duterte declares state of calamity over PH for next 6 months amid rise in COVID-19 cases|date=March 17, 2020|work=[[Manila Bulletin]]|accessdate=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On March 25, the President signed the [[Bayanihan to Heal as One Act]], which gave him additional powers to handle the outbreak.<ref>{{cite news|last=Tomacruz|first=Sofia|url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/255718-duterte-signs-law-granting-special-powers-coronavirus-outbreak|title=Duterte signs law granting himself special powers to address coronavirus outbreak|date=March 25, 2020|work=Rappler|accessdate=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Duterte signs\">{{cite news|last=Aguilar|first=Krissy|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1247988/duterte-signs-law-granting-him-special-powers-vs-covid-19|title=Duterte signs law on special powers vs COVID-19|date=March 25, 2020|work=Inquirer|access-date=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Philippine government has repatriated some of its citizens across different international locations, all of whom were later quarantined at the [[New Clark City]] in [[Tarlac]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/02/06/new-clark-city-to-serve-as-quarantine-site-for-filipinos-to-be-repatriated-from-hubei/|title=New Clark City to serve as quarantine site for Filipinos to be repatriated from Hubei|first=Analou|last=de Vera|publisher=Manila Bulletin|website=news.mb.com.ph|date=February 10, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n== Timeline ==\n{{main|Timeline of the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Philippines medical cases chart}}\n{{clear}}\n\n== Cases ==\n=== Confirmed cases ===\n[[File:COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in Metro Manila.svg|200px|right|thumb|Confirmed cases in Metro Manila (as of April 3)<br />{{legend|#510000|100+ confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#900000|71\u201399 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#c80200|51\u201370 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#ee7070|21\u201350 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#ffC0C0|1\u201320 confirmed cases}}]]\nThe first case of COVID-19 in the Philippines was confirmed on January 30. The diagnosed patient was a 38-year-old Chinese woman from [[Wuhan]], the origin of the disease, who had arrived in [[Manila]] from Hong Kong on January 21.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite news |title=Philippines confirms first case of new coronavirus |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/01/30/20/philippines-confirms-first-case-of-new-coronavirus |accessdate=January 30, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=January 30, 2020}}</ref> She was admitted to the [[San Lazaro Hospital, Manila|San Lazaro Hospital]] in Manila<ref name=\"companion\">{{cite news |last1=Magsino |first1=Dona |title=Companion of first nCoV patient in Philippines also at San Lazaro \u2014DOH |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/724311/companion-of-first-ncov-patient-in-philippines-also-at-san-lazaro-doh/story/ |accessdate=January 31, 2020 |work=GMA News |date=January 31, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131073955/https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/724311/companion-of-first-ncov-patient-in-philippines-also-at-san-lazaro-doh/story/ |archive-date=January 31, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> on January 25 after she sought a consultation due to a mild cough. At the time of the confirmation announcement, the Chinese woman was already [[asymptomatic]].<ref name=\"phconfirms\"/>\n\nThe second case was confirmed on February 2, a 44-year-old Chinese male who was the companion of the first case. His death on February 1 was the first recorded outside China. He suffered from [[coinfection]] with [[influenza]] and ''[[Streptococcus pneumoniae]]''.<ref name=\":01\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/first-coronavirus-death-outside-china-reported-philippines-n1128371|title=First coronavirus death outside China reported in Philippines\n|date=February 2, 2020|website=NBC News|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=February 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn February 5, the DOH confirmed a third case in a 60-year-old Chinese woman who flew into [[Cebu City]] from Hong Kong on January 20 before she traveled to [[Bohol]] where she consulted a doctor at a private hospital on January 22, due to fever and [[rhinitis]]. Samples taken from the patient on January 24 returned a negative result, but the DOH was notified on February 3 that samples taken from the patient on January 23 tested positive for the virus. The patient upon recovery on January 31 was allowed to go home to China.<ref name=\"doh3rd\">{{cite web|url=https://www.doh.gov.ph/doh-press-release/doh-confirms-3rd-2019-nCoV-ARD-case-in-PH|title=DOH confirms 3rd 2019-nCoV ARD Case iN PH|last=|first=|date=February 5, 2020|website=Department of Health (Philippines)|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205081612/https://www.doh.gov.ph/doh-press-release/doh-confirms-3rd-2019-nCoV-ARD-case-in-PH|archive-date=February 5, 2020|accessdate=February 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter a month without new cases, on March 6, the DOH announced two cases consisting of two Filipinos. One is a 48-year-old man with a travel history to Japan, returning on February 25 and reported symptoms on March 3.<ref name=\"DOHNC\">{{cite news |last1=Punzalan |first1=Jamaine |title=Philippines' new coronavirus cases now at 5, including potential local transmission |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/06/20/new-coronavirus-case-in-philippines-possible-local-transmission |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 6, 2020}}</ref> The other is a 60-year-old man with a history of hypertension and diabetes who experienced symptoms on February 25 and was admitted to a hospital on March 1 when he experienced pneumonia. He had last visited a Muslim prayer hall in [[San Juan, Metro Manila|San Juan]].<ref name=\"DOHNC\"/> The DOH confirmed that the fifth case had no travel history outside the Philippines and is, therefore, the first case of local transmission. A sixth case was later confirmed, that of a 59-year-old woman who is the wife of the fifth case.<ref name=\"codered\">{{cite news |title=CODE RED: Philippines' coronavirus cases rise to 6, DOH confirms local transmission |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/07/20/code-red-philippines-coronavirus-cases-rise-to-6-doh-confirms-local-transmission |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 7, 2020}}</ref> The Department of Health confirmed that the fourth case is a lawyer who works for the multinational firm [[Deloitte]] while the fifth case is a resident of [[Cainta]].<ref>[https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1238159/doh-deloitte-ph-employee-is-4th-coronavirus-case-5th-case-is-from-cainta DOH : Deloitte PH employee is 4th coronavirus case; 5th case is from Cainta | Inquirer News<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> On March 8, it was confirmed that an American, Taiwanese and two Filipinos were being treated for the virus.<ref name=\"CNNNews7\">{{cite news |title=4 new confirmed coronavirus cases recorded in Metro Manila |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/9/Coronavirus-cases-Quezon-City-Philippines.html |accessdate=March 9, 2020 |work=[[CNN Philippines]] |date=March 9, 2020}}</ref> On March 9, the DOH announced 10 more cases of the virus with unnamed patients being isolated at various hospitals.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/253882-new-philippines-novel-coronavirus-cases-march-9-2020 | title=Novel coronavirus cases in Philippines spike to 20}}</ref> That same day, President Duterte announced four more cases from San Juan, [[Quezon City]], and [[Santa Maria, Bulacan]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Duterte: PH has 4 more cases of COVID-19; total reaches 24 |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/09/20/duterte-ph-has-4-more-cases-of-covid-19-total-reaches-24 |accessdate=March 9, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 9, 2020}}</ref> The last-mentioned case was eventually clarified to be from [[San Jose del Monte]], still in the same province.<ref name=\"CNNphCSJDM\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/11/coronavirus-bulacan-philippines.html |title=Bulacan coronavirus patient is from San Jose Del Monte, officials say |last=Santos |first=Eimor |work=[[CNN Philippines]] |date=March 11, 2020 |accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> Since then, the Department of Health recorded a continuous increase in the number of COVID-19 cases in the country.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/731898/philippines-records-1546-covid-19-cases-78-deaths/story/|title=Philippines' COVID-19 death toll rises to 78; cases soar to 1,546|first=Julia Mari|last=Ornedo|publisher=GMA News|website=gmanetwork.com|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe oldest person to have recovered from COVID-19 in the Philippines (as of March 31) is reportedly an 83-year-old woman from [[Santa Rosa, Laguna]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Garcia |first1=Maria Angelica |title=83-yr-old lola is oldest to recover from COVID-19 in Philippines |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/regions/732100/83-yr-old-lola-is-oldest-to-recover-from-covid-19-in-philippines/story/?just_in |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> while the youngest patient to die due to complications from the disease (as of April 3) is a 7-year-old girl from the [[Ilocos Region]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cabico |first1=Gaea Katreena |title=7-year-old girl is Philippines\u2019 youngest COVID-19 fatality |url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/04/03/2005293/7-year-old-girl-philippines-youngest-covid-19-fatality |accessdate=April 5, 2020 |work=The Philippine Star |date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Philippine Medical Association]] reports that, as of March 31, a total of 17 Filipino doctors have died due to complications from COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nicholls |first1=AC |title=Medical group cites protective equipment lack for death of 17 doctors |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/31/17-frontline-COVID-19-doctors-dead-due-to-lack-of-PPE-.html |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n<!-- {{-}}\nHere is the list of the general information about the 1,418 confirmed cases in the Philippines:{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Philippines medical cases summary}}\n{{-}}\n -->\n\n==== Notable cases ====\n<!-- Entries here MUST have Wikipedia pages. Per [[WP:NOTE]]. -->\n\nThree incumbent and two former [[Senate of the Philippines|Senators of the Philippines]] have contracted COVID-19. On March 16, Senate Majority Leader [[Juan Miguel Zubiri]] confirmed that he tested positive for COVID-19, although he claimed he was asymptomatic.<ref name=\"Zubiri\">{{cite news |last1=Lalu |first1=Gabriel Pabico |title=Senator Zubiri tests positive for COVID-19 |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1243160/senator-zubiri-tests-positive-for-covid-19-total-lockdown-covid19ph |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> On March 25, Senator [[Koko Pimentel]] announced that he had also tested positive for COVID-19.<ref name=\"Pimentel\">{{cite news |last1=Cabico |first1=Gaea Katreena |title=Pimentel becomes second senator to test positive for COVID-19 |url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/03/25/2003350/pimentel-becomes-second-senator-test-positive-covid-19 |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=The Philippine Star |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> The following day, Senator [[Sonny Angara]] became the third senator to announce his COVID-19 diagnosis after yielding a positive result.<ref name=\"Angara\">{{cite news |last1=Ramos |first1=Christia Marie |title=BREAKING: Senator Angara positive for COVID-19 |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1248773/breaking-senator-angara-positive-for-covid-19 |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref> On March 31, former Senator [[Bongbong Marcos]] also tested positive for COVID-19 after receiving his March 28 test results from the Research Institute for Tropical Medicine (RITM).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/732076/bongbong-marcos-positive-for-covid-19/story/|title=Bongbong Marcos positive for COVID-19|first=Joahna Lei|last=Casilao|work=GMA News|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> Marcos said that he felt unwell upon returning from a trip to [[Spain]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Relativo |first1=James |title=Kumpirmado: Bongbong Marcos positibo sa COVID-19 |url=https://www.philstar.com/pilipino-star-ngayon/bansa/2020/03/31/2004618/kumpirmado-bongbong-marcos-positibo-sa-covid-19 |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |work=The Philippine Star |date=March 31, 2020 |language=Filipino}}</ref> Another former Senator, [[Heherson Alvarez]], and his wife were reported to be in critical condition after contracting the virus.<ref name=\"Virata, Alvarez\">{{cite news |last1=Tupas |first1=Emmanuel |last2=Felipe |first2=Cecille Suerte |last3=Flores |first3=Helen |last4=Villanueva |first4=Rhodina |last5=Santos |first5=Rudy |title=A\u00f1o, Bongbong, Virata test positive |url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/04/01/2004777/ao-bongbong-virata-test-positive |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |work=The Philippine Star |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn March 17, actor [[Christopher de Leon]] announced that he had contracted the virus, although de Leon claimed he was asymptomatic and was not in contact with any COVID-19 carriers.<ref name=\"de Leon\">{{cite news|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/showbiz/chikaminute/730126/istopher-de-leon-confirms-he-has-covid-19/story/|title=Christopher De Leon confirms he has COVID-19|date=March 17, 2020|work=GMA News Online|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref> He was released from the hospital on March 24.<ref>{{cite news |title=Actor Christopher de Leon discharged from the hospital |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/entertainment/2020/3/25/christopher-de-leon-discharged-covid-19.html?fbclid=IwAR0v650LFw98H8MyOQlTdcnjCn5Z1IXWBiGHNf_R830H4zrwYNkoBTOhq9o |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> Actress [[Iza Calzado]], who was hospitalized for pneumonia on March 25, was later confirmed to be COVID-positive on March 28.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Malig|first=Kaela|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/showbiz/chikaminute/731682/iza-calzado-confirmed-positive-for-covid-19/story/|title=Iza Calzado confirmed positive for COVID-19|date=March 28, 2020|work=GMA News Online|access-date=March 28, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On March 30, Calzado announced that she already tested negative for COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |title=Iza Calzado now tests negative for COVID-19, due for hospital discharge |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/entertainment/03/30/20/iza-calzado-now-tests-negative-for-covid-19-due-for-hospital-discharge |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 30, 2020}}</ref> On March 31, actress [[Sylvia Sanchez]] announced that she and her husband Art Atayde had contracted the virus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/entertainment/03/31/20/sylvia-sanchez-husband-test-positive-for-covid-19|title=Sylvia Sanchez, husband test positive for COVID-19|work=ABS-CBN News|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\nProfessor [[Aileen Baviera]], a former dean of the [[University of the Philippines Asian Center]] and a leading expert on China, died on March 21 at San Lazaro Hospital in Manila due to severe pneumonia caused by COVID-19. She died before seeing the test result that should have confirmed if COVID-19 was the main cause of her death.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Esguerra|first=Christian|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/21/20/leading-ph-expert-on-china-succumbs-to-suspected-covid-19|title=Leading PH expert on China succumbs to suspected COVID-19|date=March 21, 2020|work=ABS-CBN News|accessdate=March 21, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 25, [[Rizal]] Governor [[Rebecca Ynares]] announced that she had contracted the virus.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cinco |first1=Maricar |title=Rizal Governor Ynares tests positive for COVID-19 |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1248492/rizal-governor-ynares-tests-positive-for-covid-19 |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27, Defense Secretary [[Delfin Lorenzana]] confirmed that [[Armed Forces of the Philippines]] [[Chief of Staff of the Armed Forces of the Philippines|Chief of Staff]] Gen. [[Felimon Santos Jr.|Felimon Santos, Jr.]] tested positive for COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sadongdong|first=Martin|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/27/afp-chief-of-staff-tests-positive-for-covid-19/|title=AFP Chief of Staff tests positive for COVID-19|date=March 27, 2020|work=Manila Bulletin|access-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Four days later, Interior Secretary [[Eduardo A\u00f1o]] announced that he had tested positive following a result from the RITM, although he claims to be asymptomatic. A\u00f1o stated that he had interacted with at least four people diagnosed with the virus.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Talabong|first1=Rambo|url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/256561-dilg-secretary-eduardo-ano-tests-positive-coronavirus|title=DILG Secretary Eduardo A\u00f1o tests positive for coronavirus|date=March 31, 2020|work=Rappler|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 31, former [[Prime Minister of the Philippines|Prime Minister]] and Finance Secretary [[Cesar Virata]] was reported to have been admitted to the intensive care unit of [[St. Luke's Medical Center \u2013 Global City]] due to a stroke and pneumonia. Virata was later confirmed to have the virus.<ref name=\"Virata, Alvarez\"/>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==== Cases of Filipino nationals outside the Philippines ====\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable floatright <!---mw-collapsible--->\" style=\"text-align:right; font-size:90%; width:40%; clear:right; margin:0 0 0.5em 1em;\"\n|+ Confirmed cases of Filipino nationals outside the Philippines\n! scope=\"col\" | Region{{efn|group=OF|name=of5|The Department of Foreign Affairs' data did not provide a breakdown of cases by country; instead cases were consolidated by region.}}\n! scope=\"col\" | {{abbr|Cases|Confirmed cases}}\n! scope=\"col\" | {{abbr|Treat.|Under treatment}}\n! scope=\"col\" | {{abbr|Recov.|Recovered or Discharged}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Deaths\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | '''Asia-Pacific region'''{{efn|group=OF|name=of1|Recorded from 9 countries.}}\n| 193\n| 97\n| 95\n| 1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | '''Middle East & Africa'''{{efn|group=OF|name=of2|Recorded from 8 countries.}}\n| 48\n| 2\n| 45\n| 1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | '''Americas'''{{efn|group=OF|name=of3|Only from the United States, including those identified on ''[[2020 coronavirus outbreak on the Grand Princess|Grand Princess]]''.}}\n| 33\n| 14\n| 18\n| 1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | '''Europe'''{{efn|group=OF|name=of4|Recorded from 12 countries.}}\n| 94\n| 82\n| 6\n| 6\n|- class=\"sortbottom\" style=\"font-weight:700; background-color:#eaecf0;\"\n! scope=\"row\" | '''Total'''\n| 368\n| 195\n| 117\n| 9\n|- class=\"sortbottom\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| scope=\"row\" colspan=\"5\" | Data updated as of March 31, 2020 (From the DFA).<ref name=advisory>{{Cite web |url=https://www.dfa.gov.ph/covid-19-advisories/26517-public-advisory-number-of-covid-19-cases-among-filipinos-abroad-as-of-31-march-2020 |title=Public Advisory: Number of COVID-19 Cases Among Filipinos Abroad (As of 31 March 2020) |date=March 31, 2020 |website=[[Department of Foreign Affairs (Philippines)|Department of Foreign Affairs]] |access-date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n|- class=\"sortbottom\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n| scope=\"row\" colspan=\"5\" | '''Notes''' {{notelist|group=OF}}\n|-\n|}\nThe [[Department of Foreign Affairs (Philippines)|Department of Foreign Affairs]] (DFA) relays information regarding the number of Filipino nationals abroad to have contracted COVID-19.<ref name=advisory/> The DFA keeps an official tally of confirmed Filipino COVID-19 cases per region instead of by country. As of March 31, there are a total of 368 Filipinos abroad confirmed to have contracted COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pelayo |first1=Marje |title=Filipinos abroad who tested positive for COVID-19 now at 169 \u2014 DFA |url=https://www.untvweb.com/news/filipinos-abroad-test-positive-for-covid-19-now-at-169-dfa/ |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=UNTV |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> The  first confirmed case of a Filipino national outside the Philippines was announced by the DFA on February 5, 2020\u2014that of a crew member of the ''[[Diamond Princess (ship)|Diamond Princess]]'' cruise ship quarantined off the coast of [[Yokohama]], Japan.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite news |last=Mabasa |first=Roy |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/02/05/dfa-confirms-1st-case-of-filipino-positive-for-ncov/ |title=DFA confirms 1st case of Filipino positive for nCoV |date=February 10, 2020 |work=[[Manila Bulletin]] |access-date=February 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn Asia, outside the ''Diamond Princess'', at least one Filipino case has been confirmed in [[Brunei]],<ref name=bruneiindia>{{cite news |title=2 Filipinos test positive for COVID-19 in Brunei, India |url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/22/DFA-Filipinos-test-positive-for-coronavirus-Brunei-India.html |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>[[Japan]]<ref name=\"GMA0315\">{{cite web | url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/pinoyabroad/news/729801/120-overseas-filipinos-infected-with-covid-19-doh/story | title=120 overseas Filipinos infected with COVID-19 \u2013 DOH}}</ref>, [[Hong Kong]]<ref name=\"MAR4news\">{{Cite news |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/overseas/03/04/20/another-ofw-in-hong-kong-tests-positive-for-coronavirus-dfa-official |title=Another OFW in Hong Kong tests positive for coronavirus: DFA official |date=March 4, 2020 |work=[[ABS-CBN News]] |access-date=March 10, 2020 |language=en}}</ref>, [[India]]<ref name=bruneiindia/>, [[Malaysia]]<ref name=tabligh>{{cite news |last1=Cabrera |first1=Ferdinandh |title=19 Filipino tablighs positive for COVID-19 quarantined in Malaysia |url=https://www.mindanews.com/top-stories/2020/03/19-filipino-tablighs-positive-for-covid-19-quarantined-in-malaysia/ |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |work=MindaNews |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n, [[Kuwait]]<ref>{{cite web | url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/19/Filipino-domestic-worker-tests-positive-COVID-19-Kuwait.html | title=Filipino domestic helper tests positive for COVID-19 in Kuwait}}</ref> [[Lebanon]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/09/2-filipinos-positive-for-covid-19-in-lebanon |title=DFA: 2 Filipinos positive for COVID-19 in Lebanon \u00bb Manila Bulletin News |publisher=News.mb.com.ph |date= |accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> [[Singapore]],<ref>{{Cite news |last=Tan |first=Trisha |url=https://filipinotimes.net/uncategorized/2020/02/23/breaking-dfa-confirms-first-filipino-positive-case-covid-19-singapore |title=DFA confirms first case of Filipino positive of COVID-19 in Singapore |date=February 23, 2020 |access-date=February 27, 2020 |work=The Filipino Times}}</ref> and [[United Arab Emirates]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Santos |first=Eimor |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/2/8/filipino-novel-coronavirus-UAE.html |title=Filipino in UAE tests positive for novel coronavirus |publisher=cnnphilippines.com |date=February 8, 2020 |accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nFollowing an international [[tabligh]] convention held from February 7 to March 1, 2020, at the Jamek Sri Petaling mosque near [[Kuala Lumpur]], Malaysia, the DFA reported that 19 Filipinos who attended the convention tested positive and were quarantined in Malaysia. Two others managed to return to the Philippines and later tested positive by Philippine health authorities.<ref name=tabligh/>\n\nOn April 2, the Philippine ambassador to [[Lebanon]], [[Bernardita Catalla]], died in [[Beirut]] due to complications from COVID-19 and chronic respiratory problems.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Barakat |first1=Mahmoud |title=Philippines' ambassador to Lebanon dies of coronavirus |url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/asia-pacific/philippines-ambassador-to-lebanon-dies-of-coronavirus/1789064 |accessdate=April 2, 2020 |agency=Anadolu Agency |date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn Europe, at least one Filipino case has been confirmed in [[France]]<ref name=\"ortiz2020\">{{cite news |last1=Tomacruz |first1=Sofia |title=PH Council for Foreign Relations president Alan Ortiz dies of coronavirus |url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/255528-alan-ortiz-death-coronavirus-march-23-2020?fbclid=IwAR1TWyo_IimwrE3tBbyAm9v5iDtfpt5t-qZ83Ukxt5HkEOCC-Ojm-VeFUlw |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |publisher=[[Rappler]] |date=March 23, 2020 |language=en}}</ref>, [[Greece]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cabico |first1=Gaea Katreena |title=Filipino tests positive for COVID-19 in Greece |url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/03/18/2001925/filipino-tests-positive-covid-19-greece |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=The Philippine Star |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>, and [[Switzerland]].<ref name=\"Pinay Swiss\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bomboradyo.com/pinay-mula-sa-italy-na-nagpositibo-ng-covid-19-naka-quarantine-sa-isang-hospital-sa-switzerland/ |title=Pinay mula sa Italy na nagpositibo ng Covid-19, naka-quarantine sa isang hospital sa Switzerland |date=March 10, 2020 |work=[[Bombo Radyo Philippines]] |access-date=March 10, 2020 |language=Filipino |trans-title=Filipina from Italy positive for Covid-19, quarantined at a hospital in Switzerland}}</ref> On March 23, Philippine Council for Foreign Relations President Alan Ortiz died in Paris, France.<ref name=\"ortiz2020\"/>\n\nIn the United States, it was confirmed that six Filipinos aboard the ''[[Grand Princess]]'' cruise ship, which docked in [[Oakland, California]], for quarantine, had contracted the virus.<ref name=\"MVGP\">{{cite news |title=Six Filipinos on quarantined cruise ship in US test positive for COVID-19 |url=https://www.cnn.ph/news/2020/3/11/Filipinos-Grand-Princess-COVID-19-coronavirus.html |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, a Filipino working in New York as a diplomat with the [[Philippines and the United Nations|Philippines' UN mission]] was confirmed to be positive for the virus, which led to the entire mission at [[Philippine Center]] being disinfected and closed for the day.<ref>{{cite news |title=Diplomat from Philippines first known coronavirus case at UN in New York |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/world/coronavirus-un-diplomat-new-york-philippines-us-covid-19-12533952 |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |agency=Reuters |via=CNA |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Cases of foreign nationals outside the country with travel history in the Philippines ====\n{{expand section|date=April 2020}}\nThere have been 12 confirmed cases of foreign nationals who went to the Philippines as of {{date||MDY}}.\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible\" style=\"margin:auto; width:auto; font-size:90%; text-align:center\"\n|-\n|+ Confirmed cases of foreign nationals outside the country with history of travel in the Philippines<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.doh.gov.ph/doh-press-release/DOH-REPORTS-1-COVID-DEATH-AND-3-NEW-CASES |title=DOH REPORTS 1 COVID DEATH AND 3 NEW CASES &#124; Department of Health website |publisher=Doh.gov.ph |date= |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/13/coronavirus-philippines-australia.html |title = Two people who visited PH tested positive for COVID-19 in Australia}}</ref>\n! rowspan=\"2\" | {{abbr|FC No.|Foreign case no.}}\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Nationality\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Age\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Sex\n! colspan=\"2\" | Travel dates in the country\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Date of onset<br>of symptoms\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Date of diagnosis\n|-\n! Arrival\n! Departure\n|-\n! 1\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{nowrap|{{flag icon|Japan}} [[Japan]]ese}}\n| 44\n| Male\n| February 21\n| February 28\n| February 28\n| March 4\n|-\n! 2\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{nowrap|{{flag icon|Taiwan}} [[Taiwan]]ese}}\n| 38\n| Male\n| February 28\n| March 3\n| March 2\n| March 5\n|-\n! 3\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{nowrap|{{flag icon|Australia}} [[Australia]]n}}\n| 60\n| Female\n| February 12\n| March 2\n| March 2\n| March 4\n|-\n! 4\n| style=\"text-align:left;