e=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Zamboanga del Sur]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Zamboanga del Sur reports first two COVID-19 cases |url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/regional/2020/3/30/Zamboanga-del-Sur-first-coronavirus-cases.html |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |work=CNN Philippine |date=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Northern Mindanao]] (Region X)\n**[[Camiguin]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Camiguin logs first COVID-19 case |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/regional/2020/4/5/covid-19-camiguin-jj-romualdo.html |accessdate=April 5, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n**''[[Cagayan de Oro]]''<ref>{{cite news |title=Calamba, Cagayan de Oro report first cases of COVID-19 |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/25/Philippines-cities-provinces-first-cases-COVID-19.html?fbclid=IwAR2sGxWcoZqVAzYGxaAjFYQl51801JWiKdTkNPwFezr4oVuexiqQ2yNin1k |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n**''[[Iligan]]''<ref>{{cite news |title=Iligan City records 1st COVID-19 case |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/25/iligan-city-records-1st-covid-19-case/ |accessdate=April 3, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Lanao del Norte]]<ref name=\"Inquirer-CovidLanaoDelNorte\">{{cite news |last1=Umel |first1=Richel |title=Entire village in Lanao Norte on lockdown after resident tests positive for COVID-19 |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1251150/entire-village-in-lanao-norte-on-lockdown-after-resident-tests-positive-for-covid-19 |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 30, 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n**[[Misamis Occidental]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Mayor confirms first COVID-19 case in Ozamiz City |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1250574/mayor-confirms-first-covid-19-case-in-ozamiz-city |accessdate=April 3, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Davao Region]] (Region XI)\n**''[[Davao City]]''<ref name=\"MB-CovidDavaoCity\">{{cite news |title=2 COVID-19 cases confirmed in Davao City |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/22/2-covid-19-cases-confirmed-in-davao-city/ |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 22, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"MB-CovidDavaoRegion\" />\n**[[Davao de Oro]]<ref name=\"MB-CovidDavaoRegion\">{{cite news |last1=Valdez |first1=Warren |title=Davao Region COVID-19 Update: 50 positive cases; six fatalities |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/31/davao-region-covid-19-update-50-positive-cases-six-fatalities/ |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Davao del Norte]]<ref name=\"MB-CovidDavaoRegion\" />\n**[[Davao del Sur]]<ref name=\"MB-CovidDavaoRegion\" />\n**[[Davao Oriental]]<ref name=\"MB-CovidDavaoRegion\" />\n*[[Soccsksargen]] (Region XII)\n**[[South Cotabato]]<ref name=\"PNAGovPH-CovidSouthCotabato\">{{cite news |last1=Osano |first1=Roel |title=South Cotabato confirms 1st positive Covid-19 case |url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1098326 |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |work=Philippine News Agency |date=March 31, 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n**[[Sultan Kudarat]]<ref>{{cite news |title=With confirmed COVID-19 case, Sultan Kudarat to impose lockdown, curfew |url=https://www.mindanews.com/top-stories/2020/03/with-confirmed-covid-19-case-sultan-kudarat-to-impose-lockdown-curfew/ |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |work=MindaNews |date=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Bangsamoro]] (BARMM)\n**''[[Cotabato City]]''<ref name=\"PIAGovPH-CovidCotabatoCity\">{{cite news |title=Cotabato City records first COVID 19 case in R12 |url=https://pia.gov.ph/news/articles/1036522 |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |work=Philippine Information Agency |agency=PIA Cotabato City |date=March 18, 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n**[[Lanao del Sur]]<ref name=\"ABS-CBN-CovidLanaoDelSur\">{{cite news |last1=Butardo |first1=Maria Cecilia |title=COVID-19 positive patient dies in Lanao del Sur |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/17/20/covid-19-positive-patient-dies-in-lanao-del-sur |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 17, 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n;COVID-19-free regions\n*[[Caraga Region]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Caraga readies contingency plan for COVID-19 worst-case scenario |url=https://pia.gov.ph/news/articles/1037536 |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |agency=Philippine Information Agency |date=March 30, 2020}}</ref> (Region XIII)\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[2009 flu pandemic in the Philippines]]\n\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|Philippines|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://www.covid19.gov.ph/ Philippine Government's Online Portal for the COVID-19 pandemic].\n* [https://ncovtracker.doh.gov.ph/ COVID-19 case and situation tracker] by the [[Department of Health (Philippines)|Department of Health]]\n* [https://corona.arrangy.com Worldwide Coronavirus Map, confirmed Cases] \u2013 Map the route paths of coronavirus confirmed cases.\n* [https://endcov.ph/dashboard/ University of the Philippines COVID-19 case tracker]\n* [https://covid19ph.com/ Unofficial COVID-19 Philippines data and case tracker]\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines}}\n{{Rodrigo Duterte}}\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Philippines]]\n[[Category:2020 disasters in the Philippines|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asia|Philippines]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines| ]]\n", "name_user": "Useight", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCases of Filipino nationals outside the Philippines:added comma", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_the_Philippines"}
{"title_page": "Treaty on Open Skies", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Open skies (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox treaty\n| name                = Open Skies Treaty\n| long_name           = Treaty on Open Skies\n| image               = Open Skies members.svg\n| image_width         = \n| caption             = {{legend|#008000|States that signed and ratified the treaty}}\n{{legend|#00FF00|States that have signed, but not ratified}}\n| type                =\n| date_drafted        =\n| date_signed         = 24 March 1992<ref name=\"state.gov\">{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/t/avc/trty/102337.htm|title=Open Skies Treaty|work=U.S. Department of State|accessdate=2016-02-22}}</ref> (also start of [[Provisional application (treaty)|provisional application]])\n| location_signed     =Helsinki\n| date_sealed         =\n| date_effective      = 1 January 2002\n| condition_effective = 20 ratifications\n| date_expiration     =\n| signatories         =\n| parties             =\n| ratifiers           = 35\n| depositor           = Governments of Canada and Hungary\n| language            =\n| languages           = English, French, German, Italian, Russian and Spanish\n| wikisource          =\n}}\n\nThe '''Treaty on Open Skies''' entered into force on January 1, 2002, and currently has 35 party states. It establishes a program of unarmed [[surveillance aircraft|aerial surveillance flights]] over the entire [[Territory (country subdivision)|territory]] of its participants. The [[treaty]] is designed to enhance mutual understanding and confidence by giving all participants, regardless of size, a direct role in gathering information about military forces and activities of concern to them. Open Skies is one of the most wide-ranging international efforts to date promoting openness and transparency of military forces and activities. The concept of \"mutual aerial observation\" was initially proposed to [[Soviet Premier]] [[Nikolai Bulganin]] at the Geneva Conference of 1955 by [[President of the United States|President]] [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]]; however, the Soviets promptly rejected the concept and it lay dormant for several years. The treaty was eventually signed as an initiative of US president (and former Director of Central Intelligence) [[George H. W. Bush]] in 1989. Negotiated by the then-members of [[NATO]] and the [[Warsaw Pact]], the agreement was signed in [[Helsinki]], [[Finland]], on March 24, 1992.<ref name=stategov/>\n\nThis treaty is not related to civil-aviation [[Freedoms of the air|open skies agreements]].[https://www.osce.org/mc/23457?download=true]\n\n==Membership==\nThe 35 state parties to the Open Skies Treaty are: [[Belarus]], [[Belgium]], [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]], [[Bulgaria]], [[Canada]], [[Croatia]], the [[Czech Republic]], [[Denmark]] (including [[Greenland]]), [[Estonia]], [[Finland]], [[France]], the [[Georgia (country)|Republic of Georgia]], [[Germany]], [[Greece]], [[Hungary]], [[Iceland]], [[Italy]], [[Kazakhstan]], [[Latvia]], [[Lithuania]], [[Luxembourg]], the [[Netherlands]], [[Norway]], [[Poland]], [[Portugal]], [[Romania]], the [[Russian Federation]], [[Slovakia]], [[Slovenia]], [[Spain]], [[Sweden]], [[Turkey]], [[Ukraine]], the [[United Kingdom]], and [[the United States]].\n[[Kyrgyzstan]] has signed the treaty but has not yet ratified it. [[Canada]] and [[Hungary]] are the Depositories of the treaty in recognition of their special contributions to the Open Skies process. The \"Depository\" countries maintain treaty documents and provide administrative support.\n\nThe Open Skies treaty is one of unlimited duration, and is open to accession by other states. The republics of the [[former Soviet Union]] ([[USSR]]) that have not already become state parties to the treaty may join it at any time. Applications from other interested countries are subject to a [[consensus]] decision by the [[Open Skies Consultative Commission]] (OSCC),<ref name=stategov/> the organization, based in [[Vienna, Austria]], that is charged with carrying out the implementation of the treaty. The [[Organization for Security and Co-Operation in Europe]] meets monthly at its headquarters in Vienna.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.osce.org/oscc|title=Open Skies Consultative Commission|publisher=}}</ref> \nEight countries have joined into the treaty since it entered into force in 2002: Bosnia and Herzegovina, Croatia, Estonia, Finland, Latvia, Lithuania, Slovenia, and Sweden. Notably missing are [[Austria]],[[Cyprus]], [[Switzerland]], [[Serbia]], [[Montenegro]], [[Albania]], [[North Macedonia]], [[Moldova]], [[Armenia]] and [[Uzbekistan]].The Republic of [[Cyprus]] has submitted its application to accede the Treaty in 2002, however, since then Turkey blocks its accession.\n\n== Open Skies Consultative Commission ==\nThe '''Open Skies Consultative Commission''' is the implementing body for the Treaty on Open Skies.<ref>{{cite web|title=Treaty on Open Skies|url=http://www.osce.org/oscc|publisher=Open Skies Consultative Commission|accessdate=10 August 2013}}</ref> It meets monthly at the [[Vienna]] headquarters of the [[Organization for Security and Co-Operation in Europe]], and consists of representatives from each of the states that is a party to the treaty.\n\n==Basic elements of the treaty==\n\n===Territory===\nThe Open Skies regulations covers the territory over which the parties exercise sovereignty, including [[mainland]], islands, and internal and territorial waters. The treaty specifies that the entire territory of a member state is open to observation. Observation flights may only be restricted for reasons of flight safety and not for reasons of national security.<ref name=stategov/>\n\n===Aircraft===\n[[Image:Oc-135 xxl.jpg|thumb|A [[United States Air Force|USAF]] [[Boeing OC-135B Open Skies]].]]\nObservation aircraft may be provided by either the observing party or by the observed party (the \"taxi option\"), at the latter's choice. All Open Skies aircraft and sensors must pass specific certification and [[pre-flight inspection]] procedures to ensure that they are compliant with treaty standards.<ref name=stategov/> The official certified U.S. Open Skies aircraft is the [[OC-135B Open Skies]].\n\nCanada uses a [[C-130 Hercules]] aircraft equipped with a \"SAMSON\" sensor pod to conduct flights over other treaty nations. The pod is a converted CC-130 fuel tank modified to carry the permitted sensors, along with associated on-board mission systems. A consortium of nations consisting of Belgium, Netherlands, Luxemburg, Canada, France, Greece, Italy, Portugal and Spain own and operate this system. The costs of maintaining the SAMSON Pod are shared, based on each nation's flight quota and actual use.{{Citation needed|date=September 2011}}\n\n[[Image:An-30ukrainearmy.JPG|thumb| [[An-30]] monitoring aircraft]]\n[[File:Russian Air Force Tu-214ON RA-64519 UUBW 2011-8-12.png|thumb|[[Tupolev Tu-214]]ON of the [[Russian Air Force]].]]\nBulgaria, Romania, Russia and Ukraine use the [[Antonov An-30]] for their flights. The Czech Republic also used to use the An-30 for this purpose but they apparently retired all of theirs from service in 2003.{{Citation needed|date=September 2011}}\n\nRussia also uses a [[Tupolev Tu-154A|Tu-154M-ON]] monitoring aircraft. [[Germany]] formerly used this type as well until the aircraft was lost in a 1997 [[Mid-air collision#List of notable military mid-air collisions\"List of notable military mid-air collisions|accident]]. Russia is phasing out both An-30 and Tu-154M-ON and replacing them with two [[Tupolev Tu-204#Tu-214ON|Tu-214ON]] with the registrations RA-64519 and RA-64525; though this aircraft's new sensor suite is currently being challenged by the USA.{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\nSweden uses a [[Saab 340]] aircraft (\"OS-100\") that was certified in 2004.\n\nUntil 2008, the UK designated aircraft was an [[Hawker Siddeley Andover|Andover C.1(PR)]] aircraft, registration XS596.  Since then the UK has used a variety of aircraft including a Saab 340, An-30 and an OC-135.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/wrans/?id=2013-07-16a.165334.h&s=%28%28section%3Awrans%29+open+skies%29+speaker%3A11189#g165334.q0|title=Surveillance|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, the [[German Air Force]] purchased an [[Airbus A319]] as its future Open Skies aircraft.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://augengeradeaus.net/2017/01/flugbereitschaft-erhaelt-zusaetzlichen-airbus/ |title=Flugbereitschaft erh\u00e4lt zus\u00e4tzlichen Airbus |trans-title=Open Skies Adds Airbus Aircraft |date=5 January 2017 |first=T. |last=Wiegold |work=Augen geradeaus |language=de }}</ref>\n\n===Sensors===\nOpen Skies aircraft may have video, optical panoramic and framing cameras for daylight photography, infra-red line scanners for a day/night capability, and [[synthetic aperture radar]] for a day/night all weather capability. Photographic image quality will permit recognition of major military equipment (e.g., permit a member state to distinguish between a tank and a truck), thus allowing significant transparency of military forces and activities. Sensor categories may be added and capabilities improved by agreement among member states. All sensors used in Open Skies must be commercially available to all signatories.<ref name=stategov/> Imagery resolution is limited to 30 centimetres.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.airforcemag.com/washington-debates-role-of-satellites-in-open-skies-treaty/|title=Washington Debates Role of Satellites in Open Skies Treaty|date=2019-12-09|website=Air Force Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref>{{Citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\n===Quotas===\nEach state party is obligated to receive observation flights per its passive quota allocation. Each state party may conduct as many observation flights - its active quota - as its passive quota.<ref name=stategov/> During the first three years after entry into force, each state will be obligated to accept no more than seventy-five percent of its passive quota. Since the overall annual passive quota for the United States is 42, this means that it will be obligated to accept no more than 31 observation flights a year during this three-year period. Only two flights were requested over the United States during 2005, by the Russian Federation and Republic of Belarus Group of states parties (which functions as a single entity for quota allocation purposes). The United States is entitled to 8 of the 31 annual flights available over Russia/Belarus. Additionally, the United States is entitled to one flight over Ukraine, which is shared with Canada.\n\n===Data sharing and availability===\nImagery collected from Open Skies missions is available to any state party upon request for the cost of reproduction. As a result, the data available to each state party is much greater than that which it can collect itself under the treaty quota system.<ref name=stategov/>\n\n==History==\nAt a [[Geneva Summit (1955)|Geneva Conference]] meeting with [[Premier of the Soviet Union|Soviet Premier]] [[Nikolai Bulganin]] in 1955, President Eisenhower proposed that the [[United States]] and [[Soviet Union]] conduct [[surveillance]] overflights of each other's territory to reassure each country that the other was not preparing to attack.<ref name = \"eisenhower\">{{cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/americanexperience/features/general-article/eisenhower-foreign/ |title=Foreign Affairs |work=[[American Experience]] |publisher=WGBH Educational Foundation |date= |accessdate=28 July 2013 |quote=The two sides would not meet face-to-face until the Geneva summit of 1955. At the summit, Eisenhower asserted, \"I came to Geneva because I believe mankind longs for freedom from war and the rumors of war. I came here because my lasting faith in the decent instincts and good sense of the people who populate this world of ours.\" In this spirit of good will, Eisenhower presented the Soviets with his Open Skies proposal. In it he proposed that each side provide full descriptions of all their military facilities and allow for aerial inspections to insure the information was correct. The Soviets rejected the proposal. Eisenhower was disappointed, but not surprised. In truth, the Open Skies proposal would have benefited the U.S. much more so than the Soviets -- the Russians already knew the location of most American strategic defense facilities, it was the Americans who stood to gain new information.}}</ref> The fears and suspicions of the [[Cold War]] led Soviet General Secretary [[Nikita Khrushchev]] to reject Eisenhower's proposal.<ref name = \"eisenhower\"/><ref name=dtra/>\n\nDuring a five-day summit conference held in [[Geneva]], Switzerland at the end of July 1955, the Soviet Union and United States held serious talks about disarmament and the United States put forward proposals for mutual reconnaissance flights over each other's air space, known as the '''Open Skies''' proposal. The United States had a large number of [[B-47 Stratojet|RB-47]] and [[B-36 Peacemaker|RB-36]] reconnaissance aircraft at its disposal for such activities, however the Soviets turned down this proposal. However, this Geneva Conference was universally accepted as a turning point in the Cold War. The tensions in Europe were felt to be a stalemate. However, both the Soviet Union and United States were willing to talk about their differences, rather than increase them into a state of war.\n\nThirty-four years later, the Open Skies concept was reintroduced by President George H. W. Bush as a means to build confidence and security between all [[North Atlantic Treaty Organisation]] (NATO) and [[Warsaw Pact]] countries. In February 1990, an international Open Skies conference involving all NATO and Warsaw Pact countries opened in [[Ottawa, Canada]]. Subsequent rounds of negotiations were held in [[Budapest, Hungary]]; [[Vienna, Austria]]; and [[Helsinki, Finland]].<ref name=dtra/>\n\nOn March 24, 1992,<ref name=\"state.gov\"/> the Open Skies Treaty was signed in Helsinki by Secretary of State [[James Baker]] and foreign ministers from 23 other countries. The treaty entered into force on January 2, 2002, after [[Russia]] and [[Belarus]] completed ratification procedures.<ref name=dtra/>\n\nIn November 1992, President Bush assigned responsibility for overall training, management, leadership, coordination and support for U.S. Open Skies observation missions to the [[On-Site Inspection Agency]] (OSIA), now a part of the [[Defense Threat Reduction Agency]] (DTRA). Until entry into force in January 2002, DTRA support for the treaty involved participating in training and joint trial flights (JTFs). The U.S. has conducted over 70 JTFs since 1993. By March 2003, DTRA had successfully certified 16 camera configurations on the OC-135B aircraft. They also had contributed to the certification of the Bulgarian An-30, Hungarian [[Antonov An-26|An-26]], POD Group (consisting of Belgium, Canada, France, Greece, Italy, Luxembourg, Netherlands, Norway, Portugal and Spain) C-130H, Romanian An-30, Russian An-30, and Ukrainian An-30. The United States successfully flew its first Open Skies mission over Russia in December 2002.<ref name=dtra>One or more of the preceding sentences incorporates text from a [[United States]] Government publication in the [[public domain]]: [https://web.archive.org/web/20081017174158/http://www.dtra.mil/oe/osi/programs/ops/os/index.cfm On-Site Inspection Operations: Treaty on Open Skies] page at the United States [[Defense Threat Reduction Agency]], last accessed on July 19, 2009.</ref>\n\nWith entry into force of the treaty, formal observation flights began in August 2002. During the first treaty year, state parties conducted 67 observation flights. In 2004, state parties conducted 74 missions, and planned 110 missions for 2005. On March 8 and 9, 2007, Russia conducted overflights of Canada under the Treaty.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/canada/story/2007/03/07/openskies-russians.html?ref=rss|title=Russian military to inspect Canada from above|accessdate=March 8, 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070310162645/http://www.cbc.ca/canada/story/2007/03/07/openskies-russians.html?ref=rss|archivedate=March 10, 2007}}</ref> The OSCC continues to address modalities for conducting observation missions and other implementation issues.<ref name=stategov>One or more of the preceding sentences incorporates text from a [[United States]] Government publication in the [[public domain]]: ''[https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/prs/ps/2012/03/186738.htm Open Skies Treaty Fact Sheet]'' published by the [[United States Department of State]] [[Bureau of Arms Control]] on March 23, 2012, last accessed on April 11, 2012.</ref>\n\nSince 2002 a total of 40 missions have taken place over the UK. There were 24 quota missions conducted by: Russia\u201420; Ukraine\u2014three; and Sweden\u2014one. There were 16 training flights conducted by: Benelux (joint with Estonia); Estonia (joint with Benelux); Georgia\u2014three (one joint with Sweden); Sweden\u2014three (one joint with Georgia); USA - three; Latvia; Lithuania; Romania; Slovenia; and Yugoslavia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/wrans/?id=2013-09-02d.166929.h&s=%28%28section%3Awrans%29+open+skies%29+speaker%3A11189#g166929.q0|title=Military Intelligence|publisher=}}</ref> Also since 2002 the UK has undertaken a total of 51 open skies missions. 38 were quota missions to the following countries: Ukraine (five); Georgia (seven) and Russia (26). 13 missions were training missions to the following nations: Bulgaria; Yugoslavia; Estonia; Slovenia (three); Sweden (three); USA; Latvia, Lithuania and the Benelux. The flights cost approximately \u00a350,000 per operational mission, and approximately \u00a325,000 for training missions with an approximate annual cost of \u00a3175,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/wrans/?id=2013-07-16a.165340.h&s=%28%28section%3Awrans%29+open+skies%29+speaker%3A11189#g165340.q0|title=Surveillance|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nRussian Defence Ministry spokesman stated on 4 February 2016 that Turkey had refused a Russian Open Skies mission, planned to take place in 1\u20135 February 2016, to fly over areas adjacent to Syria, as well as over NATO airbases. According to Russia, Turkey gave no explanation regarding the limitations, and claimed them to indicate illegal military activity in Syrian territory.<ref>[http://eng.syria.mil.ru/en/index/syria/news/more.htm?id=12076588@egNews Briefing of the Russian Defence Ministry spokesman concerning activities of Rus aircraft in the Syrian Arab Republic : Ministry of Defence of the Russian Federation<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The OSCC hasn't commented on the alleged violation of the Treaty by Turkey.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.osce.org/press-releases?filters=+im_taxonomy_vid_1:%28436%29|title=News and press releases|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nBy 2016, Russian aircraft had been using equipment upgraded over initial equipment.<ref>{{cite news |last=Liewer |first=Steve |date=27 March 2016 |title=Russia's 'ahead of us' on technology used in Open Skies observation flights, StratCom warns |url=http://www.omaha.com/news/military/russia-s-ahead-of-us-on-technology-used-in-open/article_59bd7ae8-39f5-5c1c-a9e6-4e953eccdb25.html |work=Omaha World-Herald |location=Omaha, Nebraska, United States |access-date=18 April 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |last=Sharkov |first=Damien |title=NEW RUSSIAN SURVEILLANCE JETS ABLE TO 'SEE UNDERGROUND' |url=http://europe.newsweek.com/new-russian-surveillance-jets-able-see-underground-328405?rx=us |magazine=Newsweek Europe |date=8 June 2015 |access-date=18 April 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |agency=Associated Press |title=Russia wants to fly surveillance planes over US with advanced cameras, congressional staffer says |url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2016/02/22/russia-to-request-permission-to-fly-planes-with-enhanced-digital-cameras-over-us.html |work=Fox News |location=New York, New York, United States |date=22 February 2016 |access-date=18 April 2017 }}</ref>\n\n===Challenges to the treaty===\n\nBoth Russia and the United States have alleged that the other is violating the provisions of the treaty.<ref>{{cite news |agency=AINOnline |title=U.S., Russia Trade Charges Over Open Skies Treaty Compliance |url=https://www.ainonline.com/aviation-news/defense/2017-09-27/us-russia-trade-charges-over-open-skies-treaty-compliance |date= 27 September 2017 |access-date=14 August 2018 }}</ref>\n\n===Potential U.S. withdrawal===\nIn October 2019, according to documents from the House of Representatives, the United States' President is considering a US withdrawal from the Open Skies Treaty.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thebulwark.com/unfriendly-skies-trump-wants-to-scrap-valuable-intelligence-treaty/|title=Unfriendly Skies: Trump Wants to Scrap Valuable Intelligence Treaty|date=2019-10-15|website=The Bulwark|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://foreignaffairs.house.gov/_cache/files/4/6/46136e03-1d92-431b-aa31-7d20d2f266f9/5B01C6DD219BB03F508CB4377B03183E.ele-letter-to-o-brien-open-skies-treaty-final.pdf|title=ele-letter-to-o-brien-open-skies-treaty-final.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> NATO allies and partners, in particular [[Ukraine]], are against the move, fearing it would license Russia to reduce further or ban overflights, thus reducing their knowledge of Russian military movements.<ref>{{Cite web|author=Iain King|url=https://www.csis.org/analysis/storm-clouds-gather-over-open-skies-treaty|title=Storm Clouds Gather over Open Skies Treaty|date=2019-10-27|website=CSIS|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-25}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Open skies]]\n*[[Open Skies Treaty between Hungary and Romania|Treaty on Open Skies between Hungary and Romania]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Open Skies aircraft}}\n* {{wikinews-inline|Norway and Denmark conducting observation flights over Belarus and Russia}}\n* [http://www.osce.org/fsc/66205 Photogallery of flights under the Open Skies Treaty on the [[Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe]] website] last access June, 18th 2012\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pIGJw-h0F-U YouTube historical video on Open Skies Treaty]\n* [http://www.osce.org/library/14127 Text of the treaty]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20141222084802/http://cns.miis.edu/inventory/pdfs/oskies.pdf Open Skies Treaty Factsheet], cns. miis.edu\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20041208222304/http://www.osmpf.wpafb.af.mil/Treaty_info/Treaty.htm Treaty Information] (including [https://web.archive.org/web/20041017234005/http://www.osmpf.wpafb.af.mil/Treaty_info/Updated_Decisions.htm recent updates]) from the [https://web.archive.org/web/20041129200429/http://www.osmpf.wpafb.af.mil/ Open Skies Media Processing Facility] at [[Wright-Patterson Air Force Base]]\n* \"[https://archive.today/20040117185420/http://www.mosnews.com/news/2005/06/15/usairinspections.shtml U.S. Starts Air Inspections Over Russian, Belarus Military Objects]\" MosNews.com June 15, 2005\n* [http://williamlambers.com/2011/08/28/open-skies-for-peace-in-the-age-of-nuclear-weapons/ Open Skies for Peace in the Age of Nuclear Weapons] Video and documents about President Eisenhower's open skies proposal.\n* [http://williamlambersdotcom.files.wordpress.com/2011/07/openskiescolumn.jpg Open Skies to Build Trust] Article in the Cincinnati Post on 1/10/2006\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081014155631/http://blogcritics.org/archives/2008/07/12/211906.php Eisenhower's Open Skies to Reach 500th Flight]\n* [http://google.com/search?q=cache:kvJuIxSJZqUJ:https://www.afresearch.org/skins/rims/q_mod_be0e99f3-fc56-4ccb-8dfe-670c0822a153/q_act_downloadpaper/q_obj_49edf999-d812-4262-9404-264d1f2f96eb/display.aspx%3Frs%3Denginespage+% Relevance of the Open Skies Treaty Program in the Twenty-First Century by Tony D. Holmes, Major, USAF]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Open Skies Treaty}}\n[[Category:1990 in aviation]]\n[[Category:1990 in Finland]]\n[[Category:2002 in aviation]]\n[[Category:Aviation agreements]]\n[[Category:Military treaties]]\n[[Category:Cold War treaties]]\n[[Category:Surveillance]]\n[[Category:Treaties concluded in 1990]]\n[[Category:Treaties entered into force in 2002]]\n[[Category:Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Belarus]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Belgium]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Bulgaria]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Canada]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Croatia]]\n[[Category:Treaties of the Czech Republic]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Denmark]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Estonia]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Finland]]\n[[Category:Treaties of France]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Georgia (country)]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Germany]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Greece]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Hungary]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Iceland]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Italy]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Latvia]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Lithuania]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Luxembourg]]\n[[Category:Treaties of the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Norway]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Poland]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Portugal]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Romania]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Russia]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Slovakia]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Slovenia]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Spain]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Sweden]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Turkey]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Ukraine]]\n[[Category:Treaties of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Treaties of the United States]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to Aruba]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to the Netherlands Antilles]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to the Faroe Islands]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to Greenland]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to Akrotiri and Dhekelia]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to Anguilla]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to Bermuda]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to the British Indian Ocean Territory]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to the British Virgin Islands]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to the Cayman Islands]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to the Falkland Islands]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to Gibraltar]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to Guernsey]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to the Isle of Man]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to Jersey]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to Montserrat]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to the Pitcairn Islands]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to the Turks and Caicos Islands]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|Open skies (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox treaty\n| name                = Open Skies Treaty\n| long_name           = Treaty on Open Skies\n| image               = Open Skies members.svg\n| image_width         = \n| caption             = {{legend|#008000|States that signed and ratified the treaty}}\n{{legend|#00FF00|States that have signed, but not ratified}}\n| type                =\n| date_drafted        =\n| date_signed         = 24 March 1992<ref name=\"state.gov\">{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/t/avc/trty/102337.htm|title=Open Skies Treaty|work=U.S. Department of State|accessdate=2016-02-22}}</ref> (also start of [[Provisional application (treaty)|provisional application]])\n| location_signed     =Helsinki\n| date_sealed         =\n| date_effective      = 1 January 2002\n| condition_effective = 20 ratifications\n| date_expiration     =\n| signatories         =\n| parties             =\n| ratifiers           = 35\n| depositor           = Governments of Canada and Hungary\n| language            =\n| languages           = English, French, German, Italian, Russian and Spanish\n| wikisource          =\n}}\n\nThe '''Treaty on Open Skies''' entered into force on January 1, 2002, and currently has 35 party states. It establishes a program of unarmed [[surveillance aircraft|aerial surveillance flights]] over the entire [[Territory (country subdivision)|territory]] of its participants. The [[treaty]] is designed to enhance mutual understanding and confidence by giving all participants, regardless of size, a direct role in gathering information about military forces and activities of concern to them. Open Skies is one of the most wide-ranging international efforts to date promoting openness and transparency of military forces and activities. The concept of \"mutual aerial observation\" was initially proposed to [[Soviet Premier]] [[Nikolai Bulganin]] at the Geneva Conference of 1955 by [[President of the United States|President]] [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]]; however, the Soviets promptly rejected the concept and it lay dormant for several years. The treaty was eventually signed as an initiative of US president (and former Director of Central Intelligence) [[George H. W. Bush]] in 1989. Negotiated by the then-members of [[NATO]] and the [[Warsaw Pact]], the agreement was signed in [[Helsinki]], [[Finland]], on March 24, 1992.<ref name=stategov/>\n\nThis treaty is not related to civil-aviation [[Freedoms of the air|open skies agreements]].\n\nhttps://www.osce.org/mc/23457?download=true==Membership==\nThe 35 state parties to the Open Skies Treaty are: [[Belarus]], [[Belgium]], [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]], [[Bulgaria]], [[Canada]], [[Croatia]], the [[Czech Republic]], [[Denmark]] (including [[Greenland]]), [[Estonia]], [[Finland]], [[France]], the [[Georgia (country)|Republic of Georgia]], [[Germany]], [[Greece]], [[Hungary]], [[Iceland]], [[Italy]], [[Kazakhstan]], [[Latvia]], [[Lithuania]], [[Luxembourg]], the [[Netherlands]], [[Norway]], [[Poland]], [[Portugal]], [[Romania]], the [[Russian Federation]], [[Slovakia]], [[Slovenia]], [[Spain]], [[Sweden]], [[Turkey]], [[Ukraine]], the [[United Kingdom]], and [[the United States]].\n[[Kyrgyzstan]] has signed the treaty but has not yet ratified it. [[Canada]] and [[Hungary]] are the Depositories of the treaty in recognition of their special contributions to the Open Skies process. The \"Depository\" countries maintain treaty documents and provide administrative support.\n\nThe Open Skies treaty is one of unlimited duration, and is open to accession by other states. The republics of the [[former Soviet Union]] ([[USSR]]) that have not already become state parties to the treaty may join it at any time. Applications from other interested countries are subject to a [[consensus]] decision by the [[Open Skies Consultative Commission]] (OSCC),<ref name=stategov/> the organization, based in [[Vienna, Austria]], that is charged with carrying out the implementation of the treaty. The [[Organization for Security and Co-Operation in Europe]] meets monthly at its headquarters in Vienna.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.osce.org/oscc|title=Open Skies Consultative Commission|publisher=}}</ref> \nEight countries have joined into the treaty since it entered into force in 2002: Bosnia and Herzegovina, Croatia, Estonia, Finland, Latvia, Lithuania, Slovenia, and Sweden. Notably missing are [[Austria]],[[Cyprus]], [[Switzerland]], [[Serbia]], [[Montenegro]], [[Albania]], [[North Macedonia]], [[Moldova]], [[Armenia]] and [[Uzbekistan]].The Republic of [[Cyprus]] has submitted its application to accede the Treaty in 2002, however, since then Turkey blocks its accession.\n\n== Open Skies Consultative Commission ==\nThe '''Open Skies Consultative Commission''' is the implementing body for the Treaty on Open Skies.<ref>{{cite web|title=Treaty on Open Skies|url=http://www.osce.org/oscc|publisher=Open Skies Consultative Commission|accessdate=10 August 2013}}</ref> It meets monthly at the [[Vienna]] headquarters of the [[Organization for Security and Co-Operation in Europe]], and consists of representatives from each of the states that is a party to the treaty.\n\n==Basic elements of the treaty==\n\n===Territory===\nThe Open Skies regulations covers the territory over which the parties exercise sovereignty, including [[mainland]], islands, and internal and territorial waters. The treaty specifies that the entire territory of a member state is open to observation. Observation flights may only be restricted for reasons of flight safety and not for reasons of national security.<ref name=stategov/>\n\n===Aircraft===\n[[Image:Oc-135 xxl.jpg|thumb|A [[United States Air Force|USAF]] [[Boeing OC-135B Open Skies]].]]\nObservation aircraft may be provided by either the observing party or by the observed party (the \"taxi option\"), at the latter's choice. All Open Skies aircraft and sensors must pass specific certification and [[pre-flight inspection]] procedures to ensure that they are compliant with treaty standards.<ref name=stategov/> The official certified U.S. Open Skies aircraft is the [[OC-135B Open Skies]].\n\nCanada uses a [[C-130 Hercules]] aircraft equipped with a \"SAMSON\" sensor pod to conduct flights over other treaty nations. The pod is a converted CC-130 fuel tank modified to carry the permitted sensors, along with associated on-board mission systems. A consortium of nations consisting of Belgium, Netherlands, Luxemburg, Canada, France, Greece, Italy, Portugal and Spain own and operate this system. The costs of maintaining the SAMSON Pod are shared, based on each nation's flight quota and actual use.{{Citation needed|date=September 2011}}\n\n[[Image:An-30ukrainearmy.JPG|thumb| [[An-30]] monitoring aircraft]]\n[[File:Russian Air Force Tu-214ON RA-64519 UUBW 2011-8-12.png|thumb|[[Tupolev Tu-214]]ON of the [[Russian Air Force]].]]\nBulgaria, Romania, Russia and Ukraine use the [[Antonov An-30]] for their flights. The Czech Republic also used to use the An-30 for this purpose but they apparently retired all of theirs from service in 2003.{{Citation needed|date=September 2011}}\n\nRussia also uses a [[Tupolev Tu-154A|Tu-154M-ON]] monitoring aircraft. [[Germany]] formerly used this type as well until the aircraft was lost in a 1997 [[Mid-air collision#List of notable military mid-air collisions\"List of notable military mid-air collisions|accident]]. Russia is phasing out both An-30 and Tu-154M-ON and replacing them with two [[Tupolev Tu-204#Tu-214ON|Tu-214ON]] with the registrations RA-64519 and RA-64525; though this aircraft's new sensor suite is currently being challenged by the USA.{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\nSweden uses a [[Saab 340]] aircraft (\"OS-100\") that was certified in 2004.\n\nUntil 2008, the UK designated aircraft was an [[Hawker Siddeley Andover|Andover C.1(PR)]] aircraft, registration XS596.  Since then the UK has used a variety of aircraft including a Saab 340, An-30 and an OC-135.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/wrans/?id=2013-07-16a.165334.h&s=%28%28section%3Awrans%29+open+skies%29+speaker%3A11189#g165334.q0|title=Surveillance|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, the [[German Air Force]] purchased an [[Airbus A319]] as its future Open Skies aircraft.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://augengeradeaus.net/2017/01/flugbereitschaft-erhaelt-zusaetzlichen-airbus/ |title=Flugbereitschaft erh\u00e4lt zus\u00e4tzlichen Airbus |trans-title=Open Skies Adds Airbus Aircraft |date=5 January 2017 |first=T. |last=Wiegold |work=Augen geradeaus |language=de }}</ref>\n\n===Sensors===\nOpen Skies aircraft may have video, optical panoramic and framing cameras for daylight photography, infra-red line scanners for a day/night capability, and [[synthetic aperture radar]] for a day/night all weather capability. Photographic image quality will permit recognition of major military equipment (e.g., permit a member state to distinguish between a tank and a truck), thus allowing significant transparency of military forces and activities. Sensor categories may be added and capabilities improved by agreement among member states. All sensors used in Open Skies must be commercially available to all signatories.<ref name=stategov/> Imagery resolution is limited to 30 centimetres.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.airforcemag.com/washington-debates-role-of-satellites-in-open-skies-treaty/|title=Washington Debates Role of Satellites in Open Skies Treaty|date=2019-12-09|website=Air Force Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-10}}</ref>{{Citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\n===Quotas===\nEach state party is obligated to receive observation flights per its passive quota allocation. Each state party may conduct as many observation flights - its active quota - as its passive quota.<ref name=stategov/> During the first three years after entry into force, each state will be obligated to accept no more than seventy-five percent of its passive quota. Since the overall annual passive quota for the United States is 42, this means that it will be obligated to accept no more than 31 observation flights a year during this three-year period. Only two flights were requested over the United States during 2005, by the Russian Federation and Republic of Belarus Group of states parties (which functions as a single entity for quota allocation purposes). The United States is entitled to 8 of the 31 annual flights available over Russia/Belarus. Additionally, the United States is entitled to one flight over Ukraine, which is shared with Canada.\n\n===Data sharing and availability===\nImagery collected from Open Skies missions is available to any state party upon request for the cost of reproduction. As a result, the data available to each state party is much greater than that which it can collect itself under the treaty quota system.<ref name=stategov/>\n\n==History==\nAt a [[Geneva Summit (1955)|Geneva Conference]] meeting with [[Premier of the Soviet Union|Soviet Premier]] [[Nikolai Bulganin]] in 1955, President Eisenhower proposed that the [[United States]] and [[Soviet Union]] conduct [[surveillance]] overflights of each other's territory to reassure each country that the other was not preparing to attack.<ref name = \"eisenhower\">{{cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/americanexperience/features/general-article/eisenhower-foreign/ |title=Foreign Affairs |work=[[American Experience]] |publisher=WGBH Educational Foundation |date= |accessdate=28 July 2013 |quote=The two sides would not meet face-to-face until the Geneva summit of 1955. At the summit, Eisenhower asserted, \"I came to Geneva because I believe mankind longs for freedom from war and the rumors of war. I came here because my lasting faith in the decent instincts and good sense of the people who populate this world of ours.\" In this spirit of good will, Eisenhower presented the Soviets with his Open Skies proposal. In it he proposed that each side provide full descriptions of all their military facilities and allow for aerial inspections to insure the information was correct. The Soviets rejected the proposal. Eisenhower was disappointed, but not surprised. In truth, the Open Skies proposal would have benefited the U.S. much more so than the Soviets -- the Russians already knew the location of most American strategic defense facilities, it was the Americans who stood to gain new information.}}</ref> The fears and suspicions of the [[Cold War]] led Soviet General Secretary [[Nikita Khrushchev]] to reject Eisenhower's proposal.<ref name = \"eisenhower\"/><ref name=dtra/>\n\nDuring a five-day summit conference held in [[Geneva]], Switzerland at the end of July 1955, the Soviet Union and United States held serious talks about disarmament and the United States put forward proposals for mutual reconnaissance flights over each other's air space, known as the '''Open Skies''' proposal. The United States had a large number of [[B-47 Stratojet|RB-47]] and [[B-36 Peacemaker|RB-36]] reconnaissance aircraft at its disposal for such activities, however the Soviets turned down this proposal. However, this Geneva Conference was universally accepted as a turning point in the Cold War. The tensions in Europe were felt to be a stalemate. However, both the Soviet Union and United States were willing to talk about their differences, rather than increase them into a state of war.\n\nThirty-four years later, the Open Skies concept was reintroduced by President George H. W. Bush as a means to build confidence and security between all [[North Atlantic Treaty Organisation]] (NATO) and [[Warsaw Pact]] countries. In February 1990, an international Open Skies conference involving all NATO and Warsaw Pact countries opened in [[Ottawa, Canada]]. Subsequent rounds of negotiations were held in [[Budapest, Hungary]]; [[Vienna, Austria]]; and [[Helsinki, Finland]].<ref name=dtra/>\n\nOn March 24, 1992,<ref name=\"state.gov\"/> the Open Skies Treaty was signed in Helsinki by Secretary of State [[James Baker]] and foreign ministers from 23 other countries. The treaty entered into force on January 2, 2002, after [[Russia]] and [[Belarus]] completed ratification procedures.<ref name=dtra/>\n\nIn November 1992, President Bush assigned responsibility for overall training, management, leadership, coordination and support for U.S. Open Skies observation missions to the [[On-Site Inspection Agency]] (OSIA), now a part of the [[Defense Threat Reduction Agency]] (DTRA). Until entry into force in January 2002, DTRA support for the treaty involved participating in training and joint trial flights (JTFs). The U.S. has conducted over 70 JTFs since 1993. By March 2003, DTRA had successfully certified 16 camera configurations on the OC-135B aircraft. They also had contributed to the certification of the Bulgarian An-30, Hungarian [[Antonov An-26|An-26]], POD Group (consisting of Belgium, Canada, France, Greece, Italy, Luxembourg, Netherlands, Norway, Portugal and Spain) C-130H, Romanian An-30, Russian An-30, and Ukrainian An-30. The United States successfully flew its first Open Skies mission over Russia in December 2002.<ref name=dtra>One or more of the preceding sentences incorporates text from a [[United States]] Government publication in the [[public domain]]: [https://web.archive.org/web/20081017174158/http://www.dtra.mil/oe/osi/programs/ops/os/index.cfm On-Site Inspection Operations: Treaty on Open Skies] page at the United States [[Defense Threat Reduction Agency]], last accessed on July 19, 2009.</ref>\n\nWith entry into force of the treaty, formal observation flights began in August 2002. During the first treaty year, state parties conducted 67 observation flights. In 2004, state parties conducted 74 missions, and planned 110 missions for 2005. On March 8 and 9, 2007, Russia conducted overflights of Canada under the Treaty.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/canada/story/2007/03/07/openskies-russians.html?ref=rss|title=Russian military to inspect Canada from above|accessdate=March 8, 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070310162645/http://www.cbc.ca/canada/story/2007/03/07/openskies-russians.html?ref=rss|archivedate=March 10, 2007}}</ref> The OSCC continues to address modalities for conducting observation missions and other implementation issues.<ref name=stategov>One or more of the preceding sentences incorporates text from a [[United States]] Government publication in the [[public domain]]: ''[https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/prs/ps/2012/03/186738.htm Open Skies Treaty Fact Sheet]'' published by the [[United States Department of State]] [[Bureau of Arms Control]] on March 23, 2012, last accessed on April 11, 2012.</ref>\n\nSince 2002 a total of 40 missions have taken place over the UK. There were 24 quota missions conducted by: Russia\u201420; Ukraine\u2014three; and Sweden\u2014one. There were 16 training flights conducted by: Benelux (joint with Estonia); Estonia (joint with Benelux); Georgia\u2014three (one joint with Sweden); Sweden\u2014three (one joint with Georgia); USA - three; Latvia; Lithuania; Romania; Slovenia; and Yugoslavia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/wrans/?id=2013-09-02d.166929.h&s=%28%28section%3Awrans%29+open+skies%29+speaker%3A11189#g166929.q0|title=Military Intelligence|publisher=}}</ref> Also since 2002 the UK has undertaken a total of 51 open skies missions. 38 were quota missions to the following countries: Ukraine (five); Georgia (seven) and Russia (26). 13 missions were training missions to the following nations: Bulgaria; Yugoslavia; Estonia; Slovenia (three); Sweden (three); USA; Latvia, Lithuania and the Benelux. The flights cost approximately \u00a350,000 per operational mission, and approximately \u00a325,000 for training missions with an approximate annual cost of \u00a3175,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/wrans/?id=2013-07-16a.165340.h&s=%28%28section%3Awrans%29+open+skies%29+speaker%3A11189#g165340.q0|title=Surveillance|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nRussian Defence Ministry spokesman stated on 4 February 2016 that Turkey had refused a Russian Open Skies mission, planned to take place in 1\u20135 February 2016, to fly over areas adjacent to Syria, as well as over NATO airbases. According to Russia, Turkey gave no explanation regarding the limitations, and claimed them to indicate illegal military activity in Syrian territory.<ref>[http://eng.syria.mil.ru/en/index/syria/news/more.htm?id=12076588@egNews Briefing of the Russian Defence Ministry spokesman concerning activities of Rus aircraft in the Syrian Arab Republic : Ministry of Defence of the Russian Federation<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The OSCC hasn't commented on the alleged violation of the Treaty by Turkey.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.osce.org/press-releases?filters=+im_taxonomy_vid_1:%28436%29|title=News and press releases|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nBy 2016, Russian aircraft had been using equipment upgraded over initial equipment.<ref>{{cite news |last=Liewer |first=Steve |date=27 March 2016 |title=Russia's 'ahead of us' on technology used in Open Skies observation flights, StratCom warns |url=http://www.omaha.com/news/military/russia-s-ahead-of-us-on-technology-used-in-open/article_59bd7ae8-39f5-5c1c-a9e6-4e953eccdb25.html |work=Omaha World-Herald |location=Omaha, Nebraska, United States |access-date=18 April 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |last=Sharkov |first=Damien |title=NEW RUSSIAN SURVEILLANCE JETS ABLE TO 'SEE UNDERGROUND' |url=http://europe.newsweek.com/new-russian-surveillance-jets-able-see-underground-328405?rx=us |magazine=Newsweek Europe |date=8 June 2015 |access-date=18 April 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |agency=Associated Press |title=Russia wants to fly surveillance planes over US with advanced cameras, congressional staffer says |url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2016/02/22/russia-to-request-permission-to-fly-planes-with-enhanced-digital-cameras-over-us.html |work=Fox News |location=New York, New York, United States |date=22 February 2016 |access-date=18 April 2017 }}</ref>\n\n===Challenges to the treaty===\n\nBoth Russia and the United States have alleged that the other is violating the provisions of the treaty.<ref>{{cite news |agency=AINOnline |title=U.S., Russia Trade Charges Over Open Skies Treaty Compliance |url=https://www.ainonline.com/aviation-news/defense/2017-09-27/us-russia-trade-charges-over-open-skies-treaty-compliance |date= 27 September 2017 |access-date=14 August 2018 }}</ref>\n\n===Potential U.S. withdrawal===\nIn October 2019, according to documents from the House of Representatives, the United States' President is considering a US withdrawal from the Open Skies Treaty.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thebulwark.com/unfriendly-skies-trump-wants-to-scrap-valuable-intelligence-treaty/|title=Unfriendly Skies: Trump Wants to Scrap Valuable Intelligence Treaty|date=2019-10-15|website=The Bulwark|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://foreignaffairs.house.gov/_cache/files/4/6/46136e03-1d92-431b-aa31-7d20d2f266f9/5B01C6DD219BB03F508CB4377B03183E.ele-letter-to-o-brien-open-skies-treaty-final.pdf|title=ele-letter-to-o-brien-open-skies-treaty-final.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> NATO allies and partners, in particular [[Ukraine]], are against the move, fearing it would license Russia to reduce further or ban overflights, thus reducing their knowledge of Russian military movements.<ref>{{Cite web|author=Iain King|url=https://www.csis.org/analysis/storm-clouds-gather-over-open-skies-treaty|title=Storm Clouds Gather over Open Skies Treaty|date=2019-10-27|website=CSIS|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-25}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Open skies]]\n*[[Open Skies Treaty between Hungary and Romania|Treaty on Open Skies between Hungary and Romania]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Open Skies aircraft}}\n* {{wikinews-inline|Norway and Denmark conducting observation flights over Belarus and Russia}}\n* [http://www.osce.org/fsc/66205 Photogallery of flights under the Open Skies Treaty on the [[Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe]] website] last access June, 18th 2012\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pIGJw-h0F-U YouTube historical video on Open Skies Treaty]\n* [http://www.osce.org/library/14127 Text of the treaty]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20141222084802/http://cns.miis.edu/inventory/pdfs/oskies.pdf Open Skies Treaty Factsheet], cns. miis.edu\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20041208222304/http://www.osmpf.wpafb.af.mil/Treaty_info/Treaty.htm Treaty Information] (including [https://web.archive.org/web/20041017234005/http://www.osmpf.wpafb.af.mil/Treaty_info/Updated_Decisions.htm recent updates]) from the [https://web.archive.org/web/20041129200429/http://www.osmpf.wpafb.af.mil/ Open Skies Media Processing Facility] at [[Wright-Patterson Air Force Base]]\n* \"[https://archive.today/20040117185420/http://www.mosnews.com/news/2005/06/15/usairinspections.shtml U.S. Starts Air Inspections Over Russian, Belarus Military Objects]\" MosNews.com June 15, 2005\n* [http://williamlambers.com/2011/08/28/open-skies-for-peace-in-the-age-of-nuclear-weapons/ Open Skies for Peace in the Age of Nuclear Weapons] Video and documents about President Eisenhower's open skies proposal.\n* [http://williamlambersdotcom.files.wordpress.com/2011/07/openskiescolumn.jpg Open Skies to Build Trust] Article in the Cincinnati Post on 1/10/2006\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081014155631/http://blogcritics.org/archives/2008/07/12/211906.php Eisenhower's Open Skies to Reach 500th Flight]\n* [http://google.com/search?q=cache:kvJuIxSJZqUJ:https://www.afresearch.org/skins/rims/q_mod_be0e99f3-fc56-4ccb-8dfe-670c0822a153/q_act_downloadpaper/q_obj_49edf999-d812-4262-9404-264d1f2f96eb/display.aspx%3Frs%3Denginespage+% Relevance of the Open Skies Treaty Program in the Twenty-First Century by Tony D. Holmes, Major, USAF]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Open Skies Treaty}}\n[[Category:1990 in aviation]]\n[[Category:1990 in Finland]]\n[[Category:2002 in aviation]]\n[[Category:Aviation agreements]]\n[[Category:Military treaties]]\n[[Category:Cold War treaties]]\n[[Category:Surveillance]]\n[[Category:Treaties concluded in 1990]]\n[[Category:Treaties entered into force in 2002]]\n[[Category:Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Belarus]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Belgium]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Bulgaria]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Canada]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Croatia]]\n[[Category:Treaties of the Czech Republic]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Denmark]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Estonia]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Finland]]\n[[Category:Treaties of France]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Georgia (country)]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Germany]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Greece]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Hungary]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Iceland]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Italy]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Latvia]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Lithuania]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Luxembourg]]\n[[Category:Treaties of the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Norway]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Poland]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Portugal]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Romania]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Russia]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Slovakia]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Slovenia]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Spain]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Sweden]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Turkey]]\n[[Category:Treaties of Ukraine]]\n[[Category:Treaties of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Treaties of the United States]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to Aruba]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to the Netherlands Antilles]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to the Faroe Islands]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to Greenland]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to Akrotiri and Dhekelia]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to Anguilla]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to Bermuda]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to the British Indian Ocean Territory]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to the British Virgin Islands]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to the Cayman Islands]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to the Falkland Islands]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to Gibraltar]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to Guernsey]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to the Isle of Man]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to Jersey]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to Montserrat]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to the Pitcairn Islands]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands]]\n[[Category:Treaties extended to the Turks and Caicos Islands]]\n", "name_user": "Robofish", "label": "safe", "comment": "corrected reference which was breaking formatting", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_on_Open_Skies"}
{"title_page": "KJ-2000", "text_new": "{{short description|Airborne early warning and control aircraft}}\n<!-- This article is a part of [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Aircraft]]. Please see\n{{Refimprove|date=November 2009}}\n[[Wikipedia:WikiProject Aircraft/page content]] for recommended layout. -->\n{|{{Infobox Aircraft Begin\n  |name = KJ-2000\n  |image = KJ2000 at 2014 Zhuhai Air Show.jpg\n  |caption = A KJ-2000 in flight at the 2014 [[Zhuhai Air Show]]\n}}{{Infobox Aircraft Type\n  |type = [[Airborne early warning and control]]\n  |national origin = China\n  |manufacturer =\n  |program cost =\n  |designer = NRIET (radar)\n  |first flight = 2003\n  |introduced =\n  <!-- |retired = -->\n  |status = Active\n  |primary user = [[People's Liberation Army Air Force]] (PLAAF)\n  |more users =\n  |produced =\n  |number built = 5<ref name=\"plaaf_saic\">{{cite web|url=http://china.usc.edu/App_Images/military%20conflict%202008.pdf|title=Capabilities of the Chinese People's Liberation Army to Carry Out Military Action in the Event of Regional Military Conflict|publisher=[[State Administration for Industry and Commerce|SAIC]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110813132436/http://china.usc.edu/App_Images/military%20conflict%202008.pdf|archivedate=2011-08-13}}</ref>\n  |unit cost =\n  |developed from = [[Ilyushin Il-76]] ([[airframe]])\n  |variants with their own articles=\n}}\n|}\n\nThe '''KJ-2000''' ({{zh| c=\u7a7a\u8b66-2000| p=K\u014dngj\u01d0ng Li\u01cengqi\u0101n| l=Airwarn-2000}}), [[NATO reporting name]]: '''Mainring''' is a [[People's Republic of China|Chinese]] [[Airborne early warning and control]] system comprising domestically designed electronics and radars installed on a modified [[Ilyushin Il-76]] airframe.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sinodefence.com/airforce/specialaircraft/kj2000.asp|title=KJ200_1|work=SinoDefence|accessdate=4 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121208061955/http://www.sinodefence.com/airforce/specialaircraft/kj2000.asp|archive-date=8 December 2012|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Development==\n[[File:Kongyu 2000, People's Liberation Army Air Force, China.jpg|thumb|KJ-2000 in 2008]]\nThe KJ-2000 development program started after the cancellation of the [[Beriev A-50#A50I|A-50I]] deal with Israel and Russia in July 2000, due to strong U.S. pressure regarding the Israeli radar that was to be mounted. China then went on to develop a domestic [[Airborne Early Warning and Control|AWACS]] and the first aircraft made its maiden flight in 2003.\n\nFour KJ-2000 aircraft have been identified so far, but production of new aircraft will likely be delayed, dependent on the acquisition of IL-76 airframes. Currently, the Russian defense exporter [[Rosoboronexport]] has imposed a significant price hike on all future IL-76s delivered to China and India despite previous contracts. Both countries are currently in negotiation with Russia regarding this matter as of early 2008. In March 2011, Russia/China negotiations reached a new agreement to move production of IL-76s to Chinese owned companies, in this way it is expected production can be run smoothly to supply China with new IL-76 airframes, while delivery of [[Soloviev D-30]]KP-2 engines is not affected by recent issues.<ref name=\"AirForceWorld.com_IL76_russia_china_export_agreement_2011\">{{cite web |url=http://airforceworld.com/pla/il-76-transporter-china.htm |title=IL76 russia china export agreement2011 |work=AirForceWorld.com |accessdate=30 April 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110303183904/http://www.airforceworld.com/pla/il-76-transporter-china.htm |archivedate=3 March 2011 }}</ref>\n\nDue to unreliable external supplier sources, China has developed a backup known as the [[KJ-200]] by installing a simplified system on board the [[Shaanxi Y-8]]. This aircraft has a similar configuration to that of the KJ-2000 and is characterized by the triple tail-fin configuration (one large and two small).\n\n==Design==\nThe Chinese AWACS has a phased array radar (PAR) carried in a round radome. Unlike the US AWACS aircraft, which rotate their rotodomes to give a 360{{nbh}}degree coverage, the radar antenna of the Chinese AWACS does not rotate. Instead, three PAR antenna modules are placed in a triangular configuration inside the round radome to provide a 360{{nbh}}degree coverage. The multi-function, three-dimensional pulse-Doppler radar was developed by NII (Nanjing Electronic Technology Research Institute), and is designed to detect and track airborne and surface targets. It operates in the frequency range of 1200\u20131400 MHz. The antenna system consists of three phased arrays, located in a {{convert|14|m|ft|adj=mid|-diameter|}} disc. In contrast, the Russian [[Beriev A-50]] and American [[Boeing E-3 Sentry]] use a {{convert|9|m|ft|adj=mid|-diameter}} disc. Each phased array has a 120-degree field of view. Maximum range of detection of air targets is {{cvt|470|km|||}}. A-50I of India made by Israel adopted its design and entered service later than KJ-2000(service 2004) in 2009.<ref name=\"Kongjing-2000 (KJ-2000) Mainring\">{{cite web|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/china/kj-2000.htm|website=globalsecurity.org|accessdate=22 September 2015|title=Kongjing-2000 (KJ-2000) Mainring|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924142931/http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/china/kj-2000.htm|archive-date=24 September 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===KJ-3000===\nA new variant with a claimed fixed next generation radar was spotted in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chinadailymail.com/2013/06/06/chinas-aewc-kj-3000-air-to-surface-combat-aircraft|title=China's AEW&C KJ-3000 air-to-surface combat aircraft \u2013 China Daily Mail|work=China Daily Mail|accessdate=4 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150412200302/http://chinadailymail.com/2013/06/06/chinas-aewc-kj-3000-air-to-surface-combat-aircraft/|archive-date=12 April 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all|date=2013-06-06}}</ref>\n\n==Operational history==\nThe PLAAF's first [[Airborne Early Warning and Control|AWACS]] regiment was established at a small and remote airfield in southern China, for security reasons, during late 2004. The commander appointed to the regiment was Zhang Guangjian (\u5f20\u5e7f\u5efa), a pilot with over 6,000 hours of flight time on various aircraft including the [[Il-76]]. The base was re-built and re-equipped for handling the KJ-2000, the first of which reached the base in 2005. A mixed fleet of KJ-2000 and the smaller [[KJ-200]] has been operated at the base. During 2006 a war exercise was held in north west China, during which a KJ-2000 and KJ-200 were deployed from the regiment for evaluation.{{Citation needed|date=November 2009}} Finally in 2013 a 24-hour coverage drill was held using three KJ-2000s that covered NW China, the East China Sea, and the South China Sea.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/wmd/library/news/china/2013/china-130406-cna01.htm|title=China holds airborne early warning drill targeting Japan: report|author=John Pike|accessdate=4 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141205014107/http://www.globalsecurity.org/wmd/library/news/china/2013/china-130406-cna01.htm|archive-date=5 December 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nRecent satellite photos show eight new Shaanxi [[KJ-500]] airborne early warning and control, or [[Airborne_early_warning_and_control|AEW&C]] aircraft at the company's factory airfield at Hanzhong, Shaanxi Province in mid-December 2017. The aircraft were undergoing testing before delivery to the military. Satellite imagery released by Stratfor has also revealed the PLAAF has deployed KJ-500s to Lhasa-Gonggar Airport in Tibet. The KJ-500 has a fixed dorsal rotodome containing three radar arrays each containing active electronically scanned array or AESA radars arranged in a triangular configuration to give full 360\u00b0 coverage. The new radar design supplants the \u201cbalance beam\u201d design used on the earlier Shaanxi KJ-200 AEW&C aircraft.\n\nSince IL-76s are supplied by Russia and the quantity is limited, China seeks to replace the IL-76 platform currently used by the KJ-2000 with the Y-20. <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.defenseworld.net/news/17311/China_To_Develop_AEW_C_Aircraft_On_Y_20_Transport_Plane_Platform#.XI_3t-HYrnE |title=China to Develop AEW&C Aircraft on Y-20 Transport Plane Platform |access-date=2019-03-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161024220841/http://www.defenseworld.net/news/17311/China_To_Develop_AEW_C_Aircraft_On_Y_20_Transport_Plane_Platform#.XI_3t-HYrnE |archive-date=2016-10-24 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Operators==\n;{{flagicon|PRC}} [[People's Republic of China]]\n* [[People's Liberation Army Air Force]] \u2013 5 were estimated in service {{as of|2008|lc=on}}.<ref name=\"plaaf_saic\"/>\n\n==Specifications==\nLimited performance parameters of KJ-2000 have been published as follows:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mil.news.sina.com.cn/2013-01-20/1408713237.html|title=\u592e\u89c6\u66dd\u7a7a\u8b66-2000\u8bd5\u9a8c\u5e73\u53f0 \u516c\u5f00\u96f7\u5185\u90e8\u8fbe\u7ed3\u6784|accessdate=4 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129014801/http://mil.news.sina.com.cn/2013-01-20/1408713237.html|archive-date=29 November 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* Max speed (km/hr): 850\n* Max range (km): 5500\n* Max endurance (hr): 12\n* Take-off weight (t): 175\n* Range against fighter sized targets (km): 470\n* Range against ballistic missiles (km): 1200\n* Max # of target that can be tracked simultaneously: 100\n\n==See also==\n{{aircontent\n|see also=\n* [[Airborne Early Warning and Control]]\n|related=\n* [[Beriev A-50]]\n* [[Ilyushin Il-76]]\n* [[KJ-200]]\n* [[KJ-500]]\n<!--- |similar aircraft --->\n|lists=\n* [[Airborne Early Warning and Control#List of AEW&C aircraft|List of AEW&C aircraft]]\n* [[List of aircraft produced by the People's Republic of China]]\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|1}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.sinodefence.com/airforce/specialaircraft/kj2000.asp SinoDefence.com article \u2013 KJ-2000 AWACS (Airborne Warning And Control System).]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110303235610/http://www.airforceworld.com/pla/KJ2000-AWACS-pla-china-.htm AirForceWorld.com KJ2000 Photo Collection]\n\n{{Chinese Military Aircraft}}\n\n[[Category:AWACS aircraft]]\n[[Category:2000s Chinese military aircraft]]\n[[Category:Quadjets]]\n[[Category:Aircraft first flown in 2003]]\n[[Category:High-wing aircraft]]\n[[Category:T-tail aircraft]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Airborne early warning and control aircraft}}\n<!-- This article is a part of [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Aircraft]]. Please see\n{{Refimprove|date=November 2009}}\n[[Wikipedia:WikiProject Aircraft/page content]] for recommended layout. -->\n{|{{Infobox Aircraft Begin\n  |name = KJ-2000\n  |image = KJ2000 at 2014 Zhuhai Air Show.jpg\n  |caption = A KJ-2000 in flight at the 2014 [[Zhuhai Air Show]]\n}}{{Infobox Aircraft Type\n  |type = [[Airborne early warning and control]]\n  |national origin = China\n  |manufacturer =\n  |program cost =\n  |designer = NRIET (radar)\n  |first flight = 2003\n  |introduced =\n  <!-- |retired = -->\n  |status = Active\n  |primary user = [[People's Liberation Army Air Force]] (PLAAF)\n  |more users =\n  |produced =\n  |number built = 5<ref name=\"plaaf_saic\">{{cite web|url=http://china.usc.edu/App_Images/military%20conflict%202008.pdf|title=Capabilities of the Chinese People's Liberation Army to Carry Out Military Action in the Event of Regional Military Conflict|publisher=[[State Administration for Industry and Commerce|SAIC]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110813132436/http://china.usc.edu/App_Images/military%20conflict%202008.pdf|archivedate=2011-08-13}}</ref>\n  |unit cost =\n  |developed from = [[Ilyushin Il-76]] ([[airframe]])\n  |variants with their own articles=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''KJ-2000''' ({{zh| c=\u7a7a\u8b66-2000| p=K\u014dngj\u01d0ng Li\u01cengqi\u0101n| l=Airwarn-2000}}), [[NATO reporting name]]: '''Mainring''' is a [[People's Republic of China|Chinese]] [[Airborne early warning and control]] system comprising domestically designed electronics and radars installed on a modified [[Ilyushin Il-76]] airframe.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sinodefence.com/airforce/specialaircraft/kj2000.asp|title=KJ200_1|work=SinoDefence|accessdate=4 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121208061955/http://www.sinodefence.com/airforce/specialaircraft/kj2000.asp|archive-date=8 December 2012|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Development==\n[[File:Kongyu 2000, People's Liberation Army Air Force, China.jpg|thumb|KJ-2000 in 2008]]\nThe KJ-2000 development program started after the cancellation of the [[Beriev A-50#A50I|A-50I]] deal with Israel and Russia in July 2000, due to strong U.S. pressure regarding the Israeli radar that was to be mounted. China then went on to develop a domestic [[Airborne Early Warning and Control|AWACS]] and the first aircraft made its maiden flight in 2003.\n\nFour KJ-2000 aircraft have been identified so far, but production of new aircraft will likely be delayed, dependent on the acquisition of IL-76 airframes. Currently, the Russian defense exporter [[Rosoboronexport]] has imposed a significant price hike on all future IL-76s delivered to China and India despite previous contracts. Both countries are currently in negotiation with Russia regarding this matter as of early 2008. In March 2011, Russia/China negotiations reached a new agreement to move production of IL-76s to Chinese owned companies, in this way it is expected production can be run smoothly to supply China with new IL-76 airframes, while delivery of [[Soloviev D-30]]KP-2 engines is not affected by recent issues.<ref name=\"AirForceWorld.com_IL76_russia_china_export_agreement_2011\">{{cite web |url=http://airforceworld.com/pla/il-76-transporter-china.htm |title=IL76 russia china export agreement2011 |work=AirForceWorld.com |accessdate=30 April 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110303183904/http://www.airforceworld.com/pla/il-76-transporter-china.htm |archivedate=3 March 2011 }}</ref>\n\nDue to unreliable external supplier sources, China has developed a backup known as the [[KJ-200]] by installing a simplified system on board the [[Shaanxi Y-8]]. This aircraft has a similar configuration to that of the KJ-2000 and is characterized by the triple tail-fin configuration (one large and two small).\n\n==Design==\nThe Chinese AWACS has a phased array radar (PAR) carried in a round radome. Unlike the US AWACS aircraft, which rotate their rotodomes to give a 360{{nbh}}degree coverage, the radar antenna of the Chinese AWACS does not rotate. Instead, three PAR antenna modules are placed in a triangular configuration inside the round radome to provide a 360{{nbh}}degree coverage. The multi-function, three-dimensional pulse-Doppler radar was developed by NII (Nanjing Electronic Technology Research Institute), and is designed to detect and track airborne and surface targets. It operates in the frequency range of 1200\u20131400 MHz. The antenna system consists of three phased arrays, located in a {{convert|14|m|ft|adj=mid|-diameter|}} disc. In contrast, the Russian [[Beriev A-50]] and American [[Boeing E-3 Sentry]] use a {{convert|9|m|ft|adj=mid|-diameter}} disc. Each phased array has a 120-degree field of view. Maximum range of detection of air targets is {{cvt|470|km|||}}. A-50I of India made by Israel adopted its design and entered service later than KJ-2000(service 2004) in 2009.<ref name=\"Kongjing-2000 (KJ-2000) Mainring\">{{cite web|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/china/kj-2000.htm|website=globalsecurity.org|accessdate=22 September 2015|title=Kongjing-2000 (KJ-2000) Mainring|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924142931/http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/china/kj-2000.htm|archive-date=24 September 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===KJ-3000===\nA new variant with a claimed fixed next generation radar was spotted in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chinadailymail.com/2013/06/06/chinas-aewc-kj-3000-air-to-surface-combat-aircraft|title=China's AEW&C KJ-3000 air-to-surface combat aircraft \u2013 China Daily Mail|work=China Daily Mail|accessdate=4 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150412200302/http://chinadailymail.com/2013/06/06/chinas-aewc-kj-3000-air-to-surface-combat-aircraft/|archive-date=12 April 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all|date=2013-06-06}}</ref>\n\n==Operational history==\nThe PLAAF's first [[Airborne Early Warning and Control|AWACS]] regiment was established at a small and remote airfield in southern China, for security reasons, during late 2004. The commander appointed to the regiment was Zhang Guangjian (\u5f20\u5e7f\u5efa), a pilot with over 6,000 hours of flight time on various aircraft including the [[Il-76]]. The base was re-built and re-equipped for handling the KJ-2000, the first of which reached the base in 2005. A mixed fleet of KJ-2000 and the smaller [[KJ-200]] has been operated at the base. During 2006 a war exercise was held in north west China, during which a KJ-2000 and KJ-200 were deployed from the regiment for evaluation.{{Citation needed|date=November 2009}} Finally in 2013 a 24-hour coverage drill was held using three KJ-2000s that covered NW China, the East China Sea, and the South China Sea.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/wmd/library/news/china/2013/china-130406-cna01.htm|title=China holds airborne early warning drill targeting Japan: report|author=John Pike|accessdate=4 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141205014107/http://www.globalsecurity.org/wmd/library/news/china/2013/china-130406-cna01.htm|archive-date=5 December 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nRecent satellite photos show eight new Shaanxi [[KJ-500]] airborne early warning and control, or [[Airborne_early_warning_and_control|AEW&C]] aircraft at the company's factory airfield at Hanzhong, Shaanxi Province in mid-December 2017. The aircraft were undergoing testing before delivery to the military. Satellite imagery released by Stratfor has also revealed the PLAAF has deployed KJ-500s to Lhasa-Gonggar Airport in Tibet. The KJ-500 has a fixed dorsal rotodome containing three radar arrays each containing active electronically scanned array or AESA radars arranged in a triangular configuration to give full 360\u00b0 coverage. The new radar design supplants the \u201cbalance beam\u201d design used on the earlier Shaanxi KJ-200 AEW&C aircraft.\n\nSince IL-76s are supplied by Russia and the quantity is limited, China seeks to replace the IL-76 platform currently used by KJ-2000 by Y-20. <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.defenseworld.net/news/17311/China_To_Develop_AEW_C_Aircraft_On_Y_20_Transport_Plane_Platform#.XI_3t-HYrnE |title=China to Develop AEW&C Aircraft on Y-20 Transport Plane Platform |access-date=2019-03-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161024220841/http://www.defenseworld.net/news/17311/China_To_Develop_AEW_C_Aircraft_On_Y_20_Transport_Plane_Platform#.XI_3t-HYrnE |archive-date=2016-10-24 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Operators==\n;{{flagicon|PRC}} [[People's Republic of China]]\n* [[People's Liberation Army Air Force]] \u2013 5 were estimated in service {{as of|2008|lc=on}}.<ref name=\"plaaf_saic\"/>\n\n==Specifications==\nLimited performance parameters of KJ-2000 have been published as follows:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mil.news.sina.com.cn/2013-01-20/1408713237.html|title=\u592e\u89c6\u66dd\u7a7a\u8b66-2000\u8bd5\u9a8c\u5e73\u53f0 \u516c\u5f00\u96f7\u5185\u90e8\u8fbe\u7ed3\u6784|accessdate=4 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129014801/http://mil.news.sina.com.cn/2013-01-20/1408713237.html|archive-date=29 November 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* Max speed (km/hr): 850\n* Max range (km): 5500\n* Max endurance (hr): 12\n* Take-off weight (t): 175\n* Range against fighter sized targets (km): 470\n* Range against ballistic missiles (km): 1200\n* Max # of target that can be tracked simultaneously: 100\n\n==See also==\n{{aircontent\n|see also=\n* [[Airborne Early Warning and Control]]\n|related=\n* [[Beriev A-50]]\n* [[Ilyushin Il-76]]\n* [[KJ-200]]\n* [[KJ-500]]\n<!--- |similar aircraft --->\n|lists=\n* [[Airborne Early Warning and Control#List of AEW&C aircraft|List of AEW&C aircraft]]\n* [[List of aircraft produced by the People's Republic of China]]\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|1}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.sinodefence.com/airforce/specialaircraft/kj2000.asp SinoDefence.com article \u2013 KJ-2000 AWACS (Airborne Warning And Control System).]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110303235610/http://www.airforceworld.com/pla/KJ2000-AWACS-pla-china-.htm AirForceWorld.com KJ2000 Photo Collection]\n\n{{Chinese Military Aircraft}}\n\n[[Category:AWACS aircraft]]\n[[Category:2000s Chinese military aircraft]]\n[[Category:Quadjets]]\n[[Category:Aircraft first flown in 2003]]\n[[Category:High-wing aircraft]]\n[[Category:T-tail aircraft]]\n", "name_user": "Aldis90", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/KJ-2000"}
{"title_page": "Groundhog Day (film)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Groundhog Day\n| image          = Groundhog Day (movie poster).jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Harold Ramis]]\n| producer       = {{ubl|Trevor Albert|Harold Ramis}}\n| screenplay     = {{ubl|[[Danny Rubin]]|Harold Ramis}}\n| story          = Danny Rubin\n| starring       = {{Plain list|\n* [[Bill Murray]]\n* [[Andie MacDowell]]\n* [[Chris Elliott]]\n}}\n| music          = [[George Fenton]]\n| cinematography = [[John Bailey (cinematographer)|John Bailey]]\n| editing        = [[Pembroke J. Herring]]\n| distributor    = [[Columbia Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1993|2|12}}\n| runtime        = 101 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $14.6 million<ref name=\"Numbers\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Groundhog-Day#tab=summary |title=Groundhog Day \u2013 Box Office Data, DVD and Blu-ray Sales, Movie News, Cast and Crew Information |website=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] |access-date=November 30, 2014}}</ref>\n| gross          = $70.9 million {{No wrap|(North America)}}<ref name=\"Mojo\">{{Cite web |url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=groundhogday.htm |title=Groundhog Day (1993) |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |access-date=May 5, 2010}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Groundhog Day''''' is a 1993 American <!-- DON'T CHANGE GENRES WITHOUT DISCUSSION --> [[fantasy comedy]] film directed by [[Harold Ramis]] and written by Ramis and [[Danny Rubin]]. It stars [[Bill Murray]] as Phil Connors, a TV weatherman who, during an assignment covering the annual [[Groundhog Day]] event, is caught in a [[time loop]], repeatedly reliving the same day. [[Andie MacDowell]] and [[Chris Elliott]] co-star.\n\n''Groundhog Day'' was a modest success on release and garnered generally positive reviews. It later attracted critical acclaim and is often included in lists of the best comedy films. The term \"groundhog day\" is now commonly used in the English language to describe a recurring situation. In 2006, the film was added to the United States [[National Film Registry]] as being deemed \"culturally, historically, or aesthetically significant\".<ref>{{Cite press release |title=Films Added to National Film Registry for 2006 |date=December 27, 2006 |publisher=[[Library of Congress]] |url=https://www.loc.gov/today/pr/2006/06-234.html |access-date=May 5, 2010}}</ref> [[Groundhog Day (musical)|A stage musical adaptation]] premiered in 2016.\n\n==Plot==\nOn February 1st, weatherman Phil Connors reassures [[Pittsburgh]] viewers that an approaching blizzard will miss [[Western Pennsylvania]]. He goes with news producer Rita Hanson and cameraman Larry to [[Punxsutawney, Pennsylvania]], to cover the [[Groundhog Day]] festivities, which he has done for several years. Phil makes no secret of his contempt for the assignment, the small town, and the \"hicks\" who live there.\n\nThe next day, February 2nd, Phil awakens at his Punxsutawney [[bed and breakfast]] to [[Sonny & Cher]]'s \"[[I Got You Babe]]\" on the clock radio. He tapes a half-hearted report on [[Punxsutawney Phil]] and the town's festivities. Rita wants to stay and cover other events, but Phil wants to return to Pittsburgh. The blizzard blankets the region in snow, stranding them in Punxsutawney. Phil shuns the celebrations and retires to bed early.\n\nPhil wakes to \"I Got You Babe\" and the same DJ banter on the radio, and discovers the day's events repeating exactly. Phil relives the day and returns to bed, assuming it was a dream, but it is again February 2nd when he wakes : he is trapped in a [[time loop]] that no one else is aware of. Realizing there are no consequences for his actions, he spends the first several loops indulging in binge eating and drinking, one-night stands, robbery, and reckless driving. After spending several loops trying and failing to court Rita, he becomes depressed and desperate for a solution to end the loop. He tries numerous times to commit suicide, including going so far as to kidnap Punxsutawney Phil and drive off a cliff with him, but he continuously wakes up to \"I Got You Babe\" on the radio.\n\nPhil tries to explain his situation to Rita, for whom he has feelings, by accurately predicting the day's events. Rita sympathizes, and they spend the entirety of one loop together, but Phil wakes up alone as usual. He decides to use his knowledge of the day's events to better himself and the lives of others; he learns how to play the piano, sculpt ice, and speak French, but is unable to save a homeless man, who dies regardless of his actions.\n\nDuring one loop, Phil enthusiastically reports the Groundhog Day festivities, amazing Rita. They spend the rest of the day together, and Phil impresses her with his apparent overnight transformation and charitable deeds. She successfully bids for Phil at a charity bachelor auction. Phil makes an ice sculpture of Rita's face, and tells her that no matter what happens, even if he is doomed to continue awakening alone each morning forever, he wants her to know that he is finally happy, because he loves her. They retire together to Phil's lodgings. Phil wakes to \"I Got You Babe\" again, but finds Rita is still in bed with him and the radio banter is different; it is now February 3rd, he has escaped the time loop. He tells Rita he wants to live together with her in Punxsutawney.\n\n== Cast ==\n[[File:Andiegroundhog.png|thumb|Andie MacDowell with a groundhog, 2008]]\n{{Cast listing|\n* [[Bill Murray]] as Phil Connors\n* [[Andie MacDowell]] as Rita Hanson\n* [[Chris Elliott]] as Larry the cameraman\n* [[Stephen Tobolowsky]] as Ned Ryerson\n* [[Brian Doyle-Murray]] as Buster Green\n* [[Angela Paton]] as Mrs. Lancaster\n* [[Rick Ducommun]] as Gus\n* [[Rick Overton]] as Ralph\n* [[Robin Duke]] as Doris the waitress\n* [[Marita Geraghty]] as Nancy Taylor\n* [[Harold Ramis]] as Neurologist\n* [[Richard Henzel]] as D.J. #1\n* Rob Riley as D.J. #2\n* [[David Pasquesi]] as Psychiatrist\n* [[Hynden Walch]] as Debbie the bride\n* [[Michael Shannon]] as Fred the groom\n* Rod Sell as Groundhog official\n* [[Ken Hudson Campbell]] as Man in the hallway\n}}\n\n== Production ==\n===Concept===\nDanny Rubin had completed and sold his script for ''[[Hear No Evil (1993 film)|Hear No Evil]]'' and moved from Chicago to Los Angeles to become a professional screenwriter around 1990.<ref name=\"telegraph interview\">{{cite web | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/2016/08/07/how-i-wrote-the-script-for-groundhog-day-in-less-than-a-week/ | title = How I wrote the script for Groundhog Day in less than a week | first = Danny | last = Rubin | date = August 7, 2016 | accessdate = February 27, 2017 | work = [[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] }}</ref> His agent suggested that he prepare a \"calling-card\" script that he could use to gain meetings with various producers.<ref name=\"telegraph interview\"/> He came up with the core idea of the script which would become ''Groundhog Day'' while sitting in a movie theater.<ref name=\"telegraph interview\"/> He asked himself the question \"If a person could live forever, if a person was immortal, how would they change over time?\"<ref name=\"bigthink rubin\">{{Cite web | url = http://bigthink.com/videos/big-think-interview-with-danny-rubin | title = Big Think Interview With Danny Rubin | first=  Paul | last = Hoffman | date = May 10, 2010 | accessdate = February 24, 2017 | work = [[Big Think]] }}</ref> Having this character be immortal and having the world change around them would have been too cumbersome for filming. Instead he came back to a concept he had written down about two years earlier about a man living the same day over and over. With the idea of a person changing over time, this repeating day motif found its \"deeper purpose\" within the new script.<ref name=\"telegraph interview\"/> The two ideas, combined, answered his proverbial question as well as opened up several possibilities of drama and comedy with that framework.<ref name=\"bigthink rubin\"/>\n\nRubin first conceived of the dating aspect for the film, \"being able to use your superior knowledge to pick up women\", which led to the film leaning more to the comedy side.<ref name=\"bigthink rubin\"/> He knew he needed some calendar date to use for the day, and his earlier concept had the character reliving a late January day over and over; when he looked at his calendar, he saw Groundhog Day, February 2, as a date with great potential as a recognized holiday but one with little fanfare, and a date on which the film could be played annually, similar to Christmas or Halloween specials. Groundhog Day also presented Rubin with the idea of being able to take his character out of his home town into the unfamiliar territory and relative isolation of Punxsutawney, and cementing the character being named Phil in honor of Punxsutawney Phil, as well as making him a weatherman.<ref name=\"telegraph interview\"/><ref name=\"bigthink rubin\"/> Rubin took about seven weeks to fix the basic concepts and \"rules\" for the time loop in the film, and then completed the first draft of the screenplay within three to four days.<ref name=\"bigthink rubin\"/>\n\nRubin started to shop the screenplay to around 50 producers. While many studios expressed interest, they told him they would not be able to film it, though Rubin was able to secure additional work through these meetings. After his own agent left the industry, Rubin hired a [[Spec script|spec agent]] to help sell the script more. The script got to the hands of Richard Lovett in the [[Creative Artists Agency]], who was able to get it to Harold Ramis around 1991, leading to Ramis offering to produce the film.<ref name=\"bigthink rubin\"/><ref name=\"new yorker\"/>\n\n===Writing and casting===\nIn the first draft of the script, Rubin had not wanted to have to explain to the audience how Phil got in the loop, and so had the movie start ''[[in medias res]]'', with Phil already in the midst of the looping; the audience would have followed one of his days after waking up to \"I Got You Babe\" where he is already aware of what will be happening, and thus provoking the audience's curiosity; the film would then have used voice-over narration by Phil to provide some of the backstory.<ref name=\"bigthink rubin\"/> Rita would also confess to being trapped in a time loop of her own.<ref name=\"Mentalfloss\">{{cite web|last1=Cormier|first1=Roger|title=16 Repeatable Facts About 'Groundhog Day'|url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/70147/16-repeatable-facts-about-groundhog-day|website=Mental Floss|accessdate=March 26, 2016}}</ref> Rubin considered this draft to be more in line with the black comedy ''[[Kind Hearts and Coronets]]'', particularly with regards to how Phil's suicides were presented.<ref name=\"telegraph interview\"/>\n\nWhile Ramis wanted to keep this approach, the studio applied pressure to use a more standard narrative structure, forcing Rubin to rewrite the script under Ramis's direction.<ref name=\"bigthink rubin\"/> A major change was to restructure the film as a standard three-act piece.<ref name=\"uproxx rift\">{{cite web | url = http://uproxx.com/movies/the-story-behind-bill-murray-and-harold-ramis-21-year-rift/ | title = The Story Behind Bill Murray And Harold Ramis's 21 Year Rift | first = Dariel | last = Figueroa | date = September 21, 2014 | accessdate = February 25, 2017 | work = [[Uproxx]] }}</ref> This second draft of the screenplay established the reason for Phil being put in a time loop, according to actor [[Eddie Deezen]]. In that version, Phil unceremoniously dumps his current girlfriend Stephanie during the introductory scenes of the film at the studio. While Phil is at Punxsutawney, a scorned Stephanie devises a way to cast a spell to trap Phil within the loop for 10,000 years.<ref name=\"deezen\">{{cite web | url = http://www.neatorama.com/2012/02/01/why-did-bill-murray-keep-going-back-in-groundhog-day/ | title = Why Did Bill Murray Keep Going Back in Groundhog Day? | author = Miss Cellonia | date = February 1, 2012 | accessdate = February 21, 2017 | work = [[Neatorama]] }}</ref> According to Rubin, he felt that he had taken a defensive position in writing these new scenes, feeling that it would \"take away everything that was innovative and interesting and turn it into an easily-dismissed Hollywood comedy\", and acknowledges that Ramis interceded on his behalf to remove these explanatory scenes while keeping the three-act format.<ref name=\"telegraph interview\"/>\n\nAnother change in the second draft was to change Phil's attitude from having come to accept the nature of the time loop, to one that was more optimistic about being able to end the loop, making the role more suited to Murray's comedy talents.<ref name=\"new yorker\"/> Ramis had known Murray since their days in [[The Second City]] improv troupe and had used him in several successful films prior to ''Groundhog Day'', so he knew how to play on his strengths to convince Murray to take the role. Prior to Murray's casting, [[Tom Hanks]]<ref name=\"Hollywoodreporterhanks\">{{cite web|title=Happy 'Groundhog Day': Here's 5 Things You Didn't Know About the Movie|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/happy-groundhog-day-heres-5-769137|website=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=March 26, 2016}}</ref> and [[Michael Keaton]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Acuna|first1=Kristen|title=Why Michael Keaton Turned Down The Chance To Star In 'Groundhog Day' And 'Lost'|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/michael-keaton-turned-down-caddyshack-lost-2014-10|website=Business Insider|accessdate=March 26, 2016}}</ref> turned down the lead role.\n\n===Filming===\n[[File:Groundhog day tip top bistro.jpg|thumb|left|Tip Top Bistro, established at the site of the fictional Tip Top Cafe in Woodstock]]\nPrior to filming, and to gain a better understanding of the event, Rubin and Murray attended the 1992 Groundhog Day festival in Punxsutawney.  They remained discreet and did not reveal the intent of their visit.<ref>{{cite web | url =  http://www.philly.com/news/groundhog-billmuray-punxsutawney-pittsburgh-holiday-weird-eagles-20190202.html | title=  Groundhog Day, the improbable holiday that brings a shot in the arm to a former coal town | first = Jason | last = Nark | date = February 2, 2019 | accessdate =February 3, 2019 | work = [[The Philadelphia Inquirer]] }}</ref> The film was shot in [[Woodstock, Illinois]], {{convert|60|miles|abbr=off}} northwest of [[Chicago]] near the [[Wisconsin]] border, because Punxsutawney \"didn't have a town center that looked good on camera\", according to Ramis,<ref name=\"Mentalfloss\"/> and because Punxsutawney's remote location (located two hours from Pittsburgh and not near any major highways or airports) magnified the logistical problems and expense of filming there.<ref>[http://pittsburgh.about.com/cs/punxsutawney/a/groundhog_day.htm What the Heck is Groundhog Day Anyway?] pittsburgh.about.com, retrieved August 9, 2016.</ref><ref name=\"morning call\"/> Woodstock was a suitable replacement for Pennsylvania in the winter months; further, Ramis knew the area as a [[List of people from Chicago|Chicago native]] and recognized it would be easy to obtain licenses to film there and operate the film's production during the winter months.<ref name=\"morning call\"/> Punxsutawney officials, miffed that their town had been passed over, refused to allow the real Punxsutawney Phil to appear in the movie,<ref name=\"Mentalfloss\"/> but sent representatives to Woodstock to make sure the ceremony was being depicted accurately;<ref>[http://www.midniteticket.com/blog/15-behind-the-scenes-factoids-from-the-harold-ramis-groundhog-day-commentary ''Groundhog Day''.] MidniteTicket.com, retrieved August 9, 2016.</ref> according to producer Trevor Albert, the Punxsutawney officials \"were actually very pleased\" with their recreation of Gobbler's Knob, the site near Punxsutawney used for the Groundhog Day ceremonies.<ref name=\"morning call\"/> Filming began on March 16, 1992, and continued through May. Much of the filming was done in colder-than-normal weather, with Murray saying that temperatures were often under {{convert|20|F|C}}, and had snowfall that lasted through May.<ref name=\"morning call\">{{Cite web | url = http://articles.mcall.com/1993-02-12/features/2902959_1_groundhog-day-punxsutawney-phil-harold-ramis | title = Groundhog Sinks Teeth Into Film Role Bill Murray Calls Co-star `Cranky' | first = Paul | last=  Willistein | date = February 12, 1993 | accessdate = February 24, 2017 | work = [[The Morning Call]] }}</ref>\n[[File:Groundhog day movie 1992 location 2007-03-18 IMG 4313.JPG|thumb|right|The \"Cherry Street Inn\", which was a private home at the time of filming, is on Fremont Street]]\nPunxsutawney Phil was played by a series of groundhogs collectively known as Scooter. \"[The animals] hated my guts from day one,\" said Murray, who was bitten twice during shooting, including during the filming of the scene where he drives himself and Phil into a ravine. The bites were severe enough that he was forced to undergo precautionary [[Rabies vaccine|rabies immunization]] afterward.<ref name=\"morning call\"/><ref>[http://articles.philly.com/1993-02-07/entertainment/25955852_1_groundhog-s-day-phil-connors-punxsutawney-phil Bill Murray And The Beast Filming \"Groundhog Day\" Turned Out To Be A Nightmare For The Actor. His Furry Co-star Had A Hankering For His Blood.] ''The Philadelphia Inquirer'', February 7, 1993, retrieved August 9, 2016.</ref>\n\nThe Tip Top Cafe, where many indoor scenes took place, was a set created for the film, but it became an actual restaurant, the Tip Top Bistro, following the movie's success. Later, it became a coffee and Italian ice cream shop,<ref name=\"location\">[http://www.locationshub.com/blog/2013/10/26/about-those-famous-groundhog-days-filming-locations ''Groundhog Day'' filming locations].locationshub.com, retrieved August 9, 2016.</ref> and now is a [[Taco stand|taqueria]].<ref name=\"roadsideamerica.com\">{{cite web | url=http://sightseeker.blogspot.com/2014/07/groundhogday.html | title=Groundhogday Puddle scene location after 20 years. | accessdate=January 4, 2015}}</ref> The Cherry Street Inn, the [[Queen Anne style architecture in the United States|Queen Anne]]-[[Victorian architecture|Victorian]] bed and breakfast where Murray's character stayed, was a private home at the time of filming. Today, it is an actual bed and breakfast.<ref name=\"location\"/>\n\nDuring filming, Murray was in the midst of marital problems and several members of the crew reported his attitude as being erratic. Murray had wanted to make the film more contemplative and less of a comedy, contrary to Ramis's view. Rather than have to handle Murray's constant phone calls, Ramis had Murray work with Rubin in New York City directly to adjust the script to satisfy Murray's requests.<ref name=\"new yorker\">{{cite web |url = http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2004/04/19/comedy-first?currentPage=all | title = Comedy First | first= Tad | last = Friend | date = April 19, 2004 | accessdate = February 25, 2017 | work = [[The New Yorker]] }}</ref> Actor [[Stephen Tobolowsky]] described the script changes: \"When I got the part, it was still kind of a mediocre Bill Murray movie,\" he said. \"You know, Bill Murray, with no consequences, in comic situations ... It wasn't until we got into the shooting that everything turned on its head. And it became not only a good movie, not only a great movie, but a classic.\"<ref name=\"ned-ryerson\"/>\n\nDuring the time he was working with Rubin, Murray refused to talk to Ramis, according to Rubin. When Murray returned to Woodstock to complete filming, Ramis described his behavior as \"just really irrationally mean\", and difficult to work with.<ref name=\"new yorker\"/> Following the filming, Ramis and Murray's longtime collaboration and friendship ended abruptly, without public explanation. Except for a few words at a wake, and later at a bar mitzvah, the two men did not speak for over 20 years after the film's release.<ref name=\"new yorker\"/><ref>{{cite news | last=Heisler | first=Steve | url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/harold-ramis,29410/ | title=Harold Ramis &#124; Film | newspaper=A.V. Club | accessdate=August 31, 2009}}</ref> Murray finally initiated a reconciliation\u2014at the suggestion of [[Brian Doyle Murray]]\u2014only after Ramis entered the final stages of his terminal illness.<ref>{{cite web | last=Wakeman | first=Gregory | title=How Groundhog Day Ruined Bill Murray And Harold Ramis' Partnership|url=http://www.cinemablend.com/new/How-Groundhog-Day-Ruined-Bill-Murray-Harold-Ramis-Partnership-67345.html | work = Cinema Blend  |accessdate=May 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Music==\nSongs featured in the film include:\n\n*\"Weatherman\" by [[Delbert McClinton]]\n*\"[[I Got You Babe]]\" by [[Sonny & Cher]]\n*\"Pennsylvania Polka\" by [[Frank Yankovic]]\n*\"[[You Don't Know Me]]\" by [[Ray Charles]]\n*\"[[Rhapsody on a Theme of Paganini]]\"\n*\"[[Almost Like Being in Love]]\" by [[Nat King Cole]]\n\n==Interpretations and analysis==\nThe film is often considered an allegory of [[self-help|self-improvement]], emphasizing that happiness comes from placing the needs of others above one's own selfish desires. As the released film offers no explanation why the time loop occurs\u2014or why it ends\u2014viewers are left to draw their own conclusions. Rubin has said that while he and Ramis discussed several of the philosophical and spiritual aspects of the film, they \"never intended [it] to be anything more than a good, heartfelt, entertaining story\".<ref name=\"telegraph interview\"/>\n\n\"Groundhog Day\", as an expression, has become shorthand for the concept of [[Transcendence (philosophy)|spiritual transcendence]].<ref>\"The spiritual power of repetitive form: Steps toward transcendence in Groundhog Day\". Suzanne Daughton, ''Critical Studies in Mass Communication.'' Annandale: Jun 1996. Vol. 13, Iss. 2; pg. 138, 17 pgs.</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=Groundhog Almighty | first=Alex | last=Kuczynski | url=http://www.times.com | newspaper=[[The New York Times]] | date=December 7, 2003 | accessdate=October 10, 2009 | quote=Angela Zito, a co-director of the Center for Religion and Media at New York University, screens the film for students in her Buddhism class. She said that ''Groundhog Day'' perfectly illustrates the Buddhist notion of samsara, the continuing cycle of rebirth that Buddhists regard as suffering that humans must try to escape (a belief, Dr. Zito noted, that was missed by executives at Guerlain, who, searching for an exotic name, introduced a perfume called Samsara in the 1980s, overlooking the negative connotations). ''Groundhog Day,'' Dr. Zito said, is a cinematic version of the teachings in Mahayana Buddhism, known as \"the greater vehicle.\" \"In Mahayana,\" she said, \"nobody ever imagines they are going to escape samsara until everybody else does. That is why you have bodhisattvas, who reach the brink of nirvana, and stop and come back and save the rest of us. Bill Murray is the bodhisattva. He is not going to abandon the world. On the contrary, he is released back into the world to save it.\" |archive-url=http://www2.kenyon.edu/Depts/Religion/Fac/Adler/Misc/GroundhogDay.htm |archive-date=December 7, 2003}}</ref> As such, the film has become a favorite of some [[Buddhism|Buddhists]],<ref>{{cite web | title=Groundhog Day The Movie, Buddhism and Me | last=Schindler|first=Paul | url=http://www.schindler.org/psacot/20010813_ghd.shtml | publisher=schindler.org | date= | accessdate=January 25, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last=Garfinkel|first=Perry|publisher=[[Lion's Roar (magazine)|Lion's Roar]] | url=http://www.lionsroar.com/harold-ramis-profile-by-perry-garfinkel/ | title=And If He Sees His Shadow ...|date=February 2, 2014|accessdate=April 5, 2015}}</ref> who see its themes of selflessness and rebirth as reflections of their own spiritual messages. In the Roman Catholic tradition, it has been seen as a representation of [[purgatory]]. \"Connors goes to his own version of hell, but since he's not evil it turns out to be purgatory, from which he is released by shedding his selfishness and committing to acts of love,\" wrote [[Jonah Goldberg]]. \"Meanwhile, Hindus and Buddhists see versions of reincarnation here, and Jews find great significance in the fact that Connors is saved only after he performs ''[[mitzvah]]s'' (good deeds) and is returned to earth, not heaven, to perform more.\" It has even been described by some religious leaders as the \"most spiritual film of our time\".<ref>{{cite news | title=Is this the greatest story ever told? | author=Andrew Buncombe | work=The Independent | url=http://isgodimaginary.com/forum/index.php?topic=31369.0 | publisher=isgodimaginary.com | date=February 2, 2004 | accessdate=January 30, 2013 | location=London}}</ref> \"The curse is lifted when Bill Murray blesses the day he has just lived,\" wrote the critic Rick Brookhiser. \"And his reward is that the day is taken from him. Loving life includes loving the fact that it goes.\"<ref name=\"natrev\"/> Albert said that after the film was released, he was contacted by a Buddhist leader praising him for making a film that captures the ideologies of regeneration, and later from a Jewish group that commenended him for depicting the ideas of ''[[mitzvah]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.thewrap.com/groundhog-day-bill-murray-accidental-classic/ | title = \u2018Groundhog Day': How Bill Murray Rom-Com Became an Accidental Classic | first = Brian | last = Welk | date = February 2, 2020 | accessdate = February 2, 2020 | work = [[The Wrap]] }}</ref>\n\nTheologian Michael P. Foley, writing for ''[[Touchstone Magazine]]'', commented on the difficulty of determining a single religious or philosophical interpretation of the film, given Ramis's \"ambiguous religious beliefs\" as \"an agnostic raised Jewish and married to a Buddhist\", and suggested that when not viewed through a \"single hermeneutical lens\", the film could be seen as \"a stunning allegory of moral, intellectual, and even religious excellence in the face of postmodern decay, a sort of Christian-Aristotelian ''[[The Pilgrim's Progress|Pilgrim's Progress]]'' for those lost in the contemporary cosmos.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Foley|first1=Michael P.|title=Phil's Shadow|magazine=Touchstone|date=April 2004|volume=17|issue=3|url=http://www.touchstonemag.com/archives/article.php?id=17-03-012-v|accessdate=August 19, 2014}}</ref> Others see an interpretation of [[Nietzsche]]'s directive to imagine life\u2014metaphorically or literally\u2014as an [[Eternal recurrence#Friedrich Nietzsche|endless repetition of events]]. \"How would this shape your actions?\" asks Goldberg.  \"What would you choose to live out for all eternity?\"<ref name=\"natrev\"/>\n\n===Time loop duration speculations===\nIn relationship to the spiritual interpretations of the film, many have tried to estimate how long Phil supposedly remains trapped in the loop, in real time, with a wide variance in estimated values. During filming, Ramis observed that according to Buddhist doctrine, it takes 10,000 years for a soul to evolve to its next level.  Therefore, he said, in a spiritual sense, the entire arc of ''Groundhog Day'' spans 10,000 years.<ref name=\"ned-ryerson\">{{cite news | first = Jan | last = Jekelek | title = In Depth With 'Groundhog Day's' Ned Ryerson, Actor Stephen Tobolowsky | date = February 11, 2010 | url = https://www.theepochtimes.com/stephen-tobolowsky-interview_1517660.html | work = Epoch Times | accessdate = March 23, 2013}}</ref> Deezen noted that the second draft of the screenplay called for Phil to be cursed to live the time loop for 10,000 years.<ref name=\"deezen\"/> In the DVD commentary, Ramis estimated a real-time duration of ten years.  Later, Ramis told a reporter, \"I think the 10-year estimate is too short. It takes at least 10 years to get good at anything, and allotting for the down time and misguided years he spent, it had to be more like 30 or 40 years.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.heebmagazine.com/blog/view/2075 | title=Harold Ramis's Response to the Groundhog Day Timeline Study | work=[[Heeb]] | archivedate=April 3, 2010 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100403063830/http://www.heebmagazine.com/blog/view/2075 | access-date=January 31, 2012 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Rubin said, \"Ultimately it became this weird political issue because if you asked the studio, 'How long was the repetition?', they'd say, 'Two weeks'.  But the point of the movie to me was that you had to feel you were enduring something that was going on for a long time ... For me it had to be\u2014I don't know. A hundred years. A lifetime.\"<ref>Gilbey, R. ''Groundhog Day (BFI Modern Classics)''. British Film Institute (2005), pp. 44\u20135. {{ISBN|1844570320}}</ref>  In 2014, the website WhatCulture combined various time duration assumptions and estimated that Phil spent a total of 12,395 days\u2014just under 34 years\u2014reliving Groundhog Day.<ref name=sim>[http://whatculture.com/film/just-how-many-days-does-bill-murray-really-spend-stuck-reliving-groundhog-day \"Just How Many Days Does Bill Murray REALLY Spend Stuck Reliving \u2018Groundhog Day\u2019?\"] by Simon Gallagher, WhatCulture.com</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HYAx9RX1OmY&t=4m47s How Many Days Does Bill Murray Spend Stuck In Groundhog Day?] (uploaded to YouTube by WhatCulture on May 20, 2014, with 491,624 views as of 10/20/17)</ref>\n\n==Release==\n===Critical reception===\nThe film was released to generally favorable reviews. Janet Maslin of ''[[The New York Times]]'' called it \"a particularly witty and resonant comedy\"<ref>{{cite news | url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9F0CEED6123EF931A25751C0A965958260 | title=New York Times Movie Review: Groundhog Day|accessdate=November 29, 2012 | work= [[New York Times]] | first= Janet | last= Maslin |author-link= Janet Maslin | date=February 12, 1993 }}</ref> and Hal Hinson of ''The Washington Post'' called it \"the best American comedy since 'Tootsie'\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/videos/groundhogdaypghinson_a0a7e9.htm|title=Washington Post: \"Groundhog Day\"|accessdate=November 29, 2012 | work=The Washington Post|date=February 12, 1993}}</ref> [[Owen Gleiberman]] of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave it a \"B-\",<ref>{{cite news | date=February 12, 1993 |author= Owen Gleiberman | author-link= Owen Gleiberman |title= Entertainment Weekly Movie Reviews: Groundhog Day |url= https://ew.com/article/1993/02/12/groundhog-day-3/ |accessdate= April 4, 2020 }}</ref> and [[Desson Howe]] of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' noted that even though the film is a good Bill Murray vehicle, \"'Groundhog' will never be designated a national film treasure by the Library of Congress\".<ref>{{cite news |author= Desson Howe | author-link= Desson Howe |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/videos/groundhogdaypghowe_a0af6c.htm|title=Washington Post: \"Groundhog Day\"|accessdate=November 29, 2012 | work=The Washington Post|date=February 12, 1993}}</ref> In 2006, the film was selected by the [[National Film Preservation Board]] for preservation in the [[Library of Congress]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000468/2006|title=National Film Preservation Board, December 27, 2006|accessdate=November 29, 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[Roger Ebert]] gave the film 3 out of 4 stars in his original review.<ref>{{cite web |date= January 30, 2005 |last1= Ebert |first1= Roger |author-link= Roger Ebert |title= Groundhog Day movie review & film summary (1993) |url= https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/great-movie-groundhog-day-1993 |publisher= [[Chicago Sun-Times]] }}</ref> In his \"Great Movies\" essay, Ebert acknowledged that, like many viewers, he had initially underestimated the film's many virtues and only came to truly appreciate it through repeated viewings, and gave it 4 out of 4 stars.<ref>{{cite web |date= February 12, 1993 |last1= Ebert |first1= Roger |author-link= Roger Ebert |title= Groundhog Day movie review & film summary (1993) |url= https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/great-movie-groundhog-day-1993 |publisher= [[Chicago Sun-Times]] }}</ref>\n\nThe film is number 32 on [[Bravo (US TV channel)|Bravo]]'s \"100 Funniest Movies\".{{cn|date=April 2020}} In ''[[Total Film]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s 1990s special issue, ''Groundhog Day'' was deemed the best film of 1993 (the year that saw the release of ''[[Schindler's List]]'', ''[[The Piano]]'', ''[[A Perfect World]]'' and ''[[The Fugitive (1993 film)|The Fugitive]]'').{{cn|date=April 2020}} In 2000, readers of ''Total Film'' voted it the seventh greatest comedy film of all time.{{cn|date=April 2020}} The [[Writers Guild of America]] ranked the [[screenplay]] #27 on their list of 101 Greatest Screenplays ever written.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wga.org/subpage_newsevents.aspx?id=1807 |title=The 101 Greatest Screenplays |accessdate=March 13, 2007 |publisher=Writers Guild of America |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060813151310/http://www.wga.org/subpage_newsevents.aspx?id=1807 |archive-date=August 13, 2006 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wga.org/subpage_newsevents.aspx?id=1807 |last= Savage |first= Sophia |date=February 27, 2013 |title=WGA Lists Greatest Screenplays, From 'Casablanca' and 'Godfather' to 'Memento' and 'Notorious' |accessdate=February 28, 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20060813151310/http://www.wga.org/subpage_newsevents.aspx?id=1807 |archive-date= August 13, 2006 }}</ref> In 2009, American literary theorist [[Stanley Fish]] named the film as among the ten best American films ever, writing that \"as the movie becomes more serious, it becomes funnier. The comedy and the philosophy (how shall one live?) do not sit side by side, but inhabit each other in a unity that is incredibly satisfying.\"<ref>{{cite news | author= [[Stanley Fish]] | title=The 10 Best American Movies | url=http://fish.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/01/04/the-10-best-american-movies | website=The New York Times | date=January 4, 2009 | accessdate=January 6, 2009}}</ref> In 2011, ''[[Time Out (company)|Time Out London]]'' named it the 5th-greatest comedy film of all time.<ref>{{cite web |title = 100 Best Comedy Movies |url = http://www.timeout.com/london/film/100-best-comedy-movies-the-full-list |publisher=Time Out London |accessdate=September 17, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn terms of retrospective reviews, ''Groundhog Day'' holds a 96% \"Certified Fresh\" rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] from 79 critics. The site's consensus reads \"Smart, sweet, and inventive, ''Groundhog Day'' highlights Murray's dramatic gifts while still leaving plenty of room for laughs\".<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/groundhog_day/ | title=Groundhog Day|website=Rotten Tomatoes | accessdate=October 17, 2012}}</ref> The film is regarded as a contemporary classic. It has a score of 72 out of 100 at Metacritic, indicating \"Generally favorable reviews.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/groundhog-day/critic-reviews|title=Groundhog Day \u2013 Metacritic|accessdate=November 29, 2012}}</ref> Audiences surveyed by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film a grade B+ on scale of A to F.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |title= GROUNDHOG DAY (1993) B+ |work= [[CinemaScore]] |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181220122629/https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |archive-date= 2018-12-20 }}</ref>\n\n===Box office===\nThe film was a solid performer in its initial release, grossing $70.9 million in [[North America]] and ranking [[1993 in film|12th among films released in 1993]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?yr=1993&p=.htm | title=1993 Domestic Grosses}}</ref> It was nominated for the [[Hugo Award for Best Dramatic Presentation]], but lost to ''[[Jurassic Park (film)|Jurassic Park]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/1994-hugo-awards/ |title=1994 Hugo Awards |publisher=World Science Fiction Society |accessdate=October 17, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110507072941/http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/1994-hugo-awards/ |archive-date=May 7, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n* [[BAFTA Award for Best Original Screenplay]] 1994\n* [[British Comedy Awards]] 1993 (Comedy Film)\n* [[Saturn Award for Best Actress (Film)]] (Andie MacDowell)\n\nIn June 2008, AFI revealed its \"Ten Top Ten\"\u2014the best ten films in ten \"classic\" American film genres\u2014after polling over 1,500 people from the creative community. ''Groundhog Day'' was acknowledged as the eighth best film in the fantasy genre.<ref>{{cite news | author = [[American Film Institute]] | title = AFI Crowns Top 10 Films in 10 Classic Genres | work = ComingSoon.net | date = June 17, 2008 | url = http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=46072 | accessdate= June 18, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title= Top 10 Fantasy | url = http://www.afi.com/10top10/fantasy.html | publisher= [[American Film Institute]] |accessdate= June 18, 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe film is recognized by [[American Film Institute]] in these lists:\n* [[AFI's 100 Years ... 100 Laughs]] \u2013 #34<ref>{{cite web|last= |first= |title=AFI's 100 Years ... 100 Laughs |url=http://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/laughs100.pdf |publisher=[[American Film Institute]] |date= |accessdate=August 6, 2016}}</ref>\n* 2008: [[AFI's 10 Top 10]]: #8 Fantasy Film<ref>{{cite web|last= |first= |title=AFI's 10 Top 10: Top 10 Fantasy |url=http://www.afi.com/10top10/category.aspx?cat=6 |publisher=[[American Film Institute]] |date= |accessdate=August 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Home media ===\n''Groundhog Day'' was released on DVD on January 29, 2008, it was released on Blu-Ray on January 27, 2009.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dvdsreleasedates.com/movies/1018/Groundhog-Day-(1993).html|title=Groundhog Day DVD Release Date|website=DVDs Release Dates|language=en-US|access-date=June 14, 2018}}</ref>{{notinsource|date=February 2020}} ''Groundhog Day'' was also released on [[Ultra HD Blu-ray]] on January 23, 2018.<ref>{{Citation|title=Groundhog Day 4K Blu-ray|url=http://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Groundhog-Day-4K-Blu-ray/178887/|accessdate=June 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nThe narrative of a protagonist trapped in a time loop, where escape is possible only after accumulating knowledge through multiple passes, is a popular [[trope (literary)|trope]] in fictional works.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://io9.gizmodo.com/5206173/lets-do-the-time-loop-again-and-again | title = Let's Do The Time Loop Again. And Again ...| first=  Charlie Jane | last = Anders | date = April 10, 2009 | accessdate = February 24, 2017 | work = [[io9]] }}</ref> Rubin noted that with his script, he \"stumbled upon a story with all the makings of a classic, so simple and true that it could be retold many different ways by many different storytellers.\"<ref name=\"telegraph interview\" /> The concept of a time loop in fiction did not originate with ''Groundhog Day''; one earlier identified example is the 1973 [[short story]] \"[[12:01 PM]]\" by [[Richard A. Lupoff]], published in ''[[The Magazine of Fantasy and Science Fiction]]'' predates the film, as well as two adaptions,  [[12:01 PM (1990 film)|a 1990 short film]], and [[12:01 (1993 film)|a 1993 television movie]].<ref name=\"npost 2018\">{{Cite web | url = https://nationalpost.com/entertainment/movies/from-groundhog-day-to-looper-a-brief-history-of-cinematic-time-loops | title = From Groundhog Day to Looper, a brief history of cinematic time loops | first=  Chris | last = Knight | date = February 2, 2018 | accessdate = July 5, 2018 | work = [[The National Post]] }}</ref> The writers and producers of \"12:01 P.M.\" believed that their work was stolen by ''Groundhog Day'' but abandoned [[12:01 (1993 film)#Legal action|legal action]] against the film makers.<ref name=\"npost 2018\" /><ref name=\"timebinders\">{{cite web   |url=http://www.fanac.org/timebinders/lupoff.html  |title=SF Recollections by Richard Lupoff   |work=Timebinders |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140728235202/http://fanac.org/timebinders/lupoff.html  |archive-date=July 28, 2014  |url-status=live  |accessdate=September 16, 2014  }}</ref> The film's time loop concept is also predated by [[Mamoru Oshii]]'s 1984 [[anime]] film ''[[Urusei Yatsura 2: Beautiful Dreamer]]'', where a high-school class relives the same day over and over again.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hartl|first1=John|title=Disney will Distribute Animated Japanese Movie|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19980903&slug=2769906|accessdate=May 15, 2017|date=September 3, 1998}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Off the Shelf \u2013 Urusei Yatsura 2: Beautiful Dreamer |url=https://www.highdefdigest.com/blog/off-the-shelf-urusei-yatsura-2-bluray/ |work=High-Def Digest |date=September 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Camp |first1=Brian |last2=Davis |first2=Julie |title=Anime Classics Zettai!: 100 Must-See Japanese Animation Masterpieces |date=2011 |publisher=[[Stone Bridge Press]] |isbn=9781611725193 |page=10 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PLc22hQhZGwC&pg=PT10}}</ref>\n\nThough not the earliest example, the time loop trope in fiction has been named after ''Groundhog Day'' by the website ''[[TV Tropes]]'' and other sources because the film established the trope in popular culture.<ref>[http://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/GroundhogDayLoop ''Groundhog Day Loop''] on TVTropes.com, retrieved February 24, 2017.</ref>  Such films as ''[[Edge of Tomorrow]]'' and ''[[ARQ (film)|ARQ]]'' have used it,<ref name=\"npost 2018\" /> as have television shows; one of the more recognized examples is ''[[The X-Files]]'' episode \"[[Monday (The X-Files)|Monday]]\".  Other genres, including sit-coms and dramas, have employed it as well. Pilot Viruet, in the magazine ''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]'', wrote, \"Because of the inherent reset button the trope provides, an episode of TV can explore different scenarios, plots, character interactions, and outcomes\u2014and if any of them don't quite feel right, the writers can start over (often with the ringing of a shrill alarm clock).\"<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/the-pop-culture-legacy-of-groundhog-day | title = The Pop Culture Legacy of 'Groundhog Day' | first = Pilot | last = Viruet | work = [[Vice (magazine)|Vice]] | date = February 2, 2017 | accessdate = February 2, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nThe phrase \"Groundhog Day\" has entered common usage as a reference to an unpleasant situation that continually repeats.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/opinion/2004-09-26-hurricane-fatigue_x.htm |title=Hurricane Fatigue |work=[[USA Today]] |date=September 26, 2004 |accessdate=October 10, 2009}}</ref> Goldberg paraphrased the common meaning as \"same stuff, different day\".<ref name=\"natrev\">{{cite web | url = http://www.nationalreview.com/article/228088/movie-all-time-jonah-goldberg | title = A Movie for All Time | first = Jonah | last = Goldberg | date = February 2, 2016 | accessdate = February 2, 2016 | work = [[National Review]] }}</ref>  In the [[military]], referring to unpleasant, unchanging, repetitive situations as \"Groundhog Day\" became widespread soon after the movie's release in February 1993. A magazine article about the aircraft carrier {{USS|America|CV-66|6}} mentions its use by sailors in September 1993.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/usnews/news/articles/940228/archive_012486_4.htm |title=Diplomacy's Gunboat |work=[[U.S. News & World Report]] |date=February 22, 1994 |accessdate=May 10, 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090416201009/http://www.usnews.com/usnews/news/articles/940228/archive_012486_4.htm |archive-date=April 16, 2009 }}</ref> The film was a favorite among the Rangers deployed for [[Operation Gothic Serpent]] in [[Somalia]] in 1993, because they saw the film as a metaphor of their own situation, waiting monotonous long days between raids.<ref>Bowden, [[Black Hawk Down (book)|Black Hawk Down]], Corgi edition, 2000 p.534.</ref> In February 1994, crew members  of the aircraft carrier {{USS|Saratoga|CV-60|6}} referred to their deployment in the Adriatic Sea, in support of [[Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnia]] operations, as Groundhog Station. A speech by [[Bill Clinton|President Clinton]] in January 1996 specifically referred to the movie and the use of the phrase by military personnel in Bosnia.<ref>Remarks to American Troops at Tuzla Airfield, Bosnia-Herzegovina, January 13, 1996.</ref> Fourteen years after the movie's release, \"Groundhog Day\" was noted as common American [[military slang]] for any day of a tour of duty in Iraq, often as a successor to the [[World War II]]-era slang term \"[[wikt:SNAFU|SNAFU]]\" (\"Situation Normal: All Fucked Up\").<ref name=\"natrev\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=7458809|title='Embrace the Suck' and More Military Speak|accessdate=November 26, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn his Iraq War memoir ''Victory Denied'', Maj. Roger Aeschliman describes guarding assorted visiting dignitaries as his \"Groundhog Day\":\n\n{{quote|The dignitary changes but everything else is exactly the same. The same airplanes drop them off at the same places. The same helicopters take us to the same meetings with the same presenters covering the same topics using the same slides. We visit the same troops at the same mess halls and send them away from the same airport pads to find our own way home late at night. Over and over and over and over and over and over and over and over and over until we are redeemed and allowed to go home to Kansas. Amen.<ref>{{cite book | title = Victory Denied: Everything You Know about Iraq is Wrong! | first = Roger T. | last = Aeschliman | isbn = 1434348954 | pages = 306 | publisher = [[Authorhouse]] | year = 2007 }}</ref>}}\n\nIn the 2015 memoir, ''Guant\u00e1namo Diary'', [[Mohamedou Ould Slahi]] refers to the film twice to describe his ongoing confinement in [[Guantanamo, Cuba]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Slahi|first=Mohamedou Ould|authorlink=Mohamedou Ould Slahi|title=[[Mohamedou Ould Slahi#Guant\u00e1namo Diary|Guant\u00e1namo Diary]]|pages=237, 311|publisher=[[Little, Brown and Company]]|year=2015|ISBN=978-0-316-32860-9}}</ref>\n\n[[Member of Parliament]] [[Dennis Skinner]] compared [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|British Prime Minister]] [[Tony Blair]]'s treatment following the 2004 [[Hutton Inquiry]] to the film. \"[The affair] was, he said, like ''Groundhog Day,'' with the prime minister's critics demanding one inquiry, then another inquiry, then another inquiry.\" Blair responded, \"I could not have put it better myself. Indeed I ''did'' not put it better myself.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/3458431.stm|title=Politics: Prime Minister's Questions|date=February 4, 2004|accessdate=May 22, 2008|work=BBC News|author=Nick Assinder}}</ref>\n\nMurray, Doyle-Murray, and Tobolowsky reprised their roles for a ''Groundhog Day''-themed [[Jeep]] commercial aired during [[Super Bowl LIV]] on February 2, 2020, promoting the [[Jeep Gladiator (JT)|Jeep Gladiator]]. The ad was filmed in and around Woodstock, Illinois.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adweek.com/brand-marketing/jeep-teases-groundhog-day-themed-super-bowl-ad/|title=Jeep Teases Groundhog Day-Themed Super Bowl Ad|last=Barwick|first=Ryan|date=January 31, 2020|work=[[Ad Week]]|accessdate=February 2, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.freep.com/story/money/cars/chrysler/2020/02/02/bill-murray-groundhog-day-super-bowl-ad/4638852002/|title=Watch Bill Murray take a groundhog for a spin in a Jeep Gladiator|last=Lawrence|first=Eric|date=February 2, 2020|work=[[Detroit Free Press]]|accessdate=February 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Events===\nThe town of Punxsutawney has seen much larger crowds at the annual Groundhog Day event since the film's release.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://time.com/4655181/groundhog-day-2017-punxsutawney-phil-documentary-animal-planet/ | title = The Surprising Way Groundhog Day Changed the Town of Punxsutawney | first = Olivia | last=  Waxman | date = February 1, 2017 | accessdate = February 1, 2017 | work = [[Time (magazine)|Time]] }}</ref>\n\nSince 1992 the town of Woodstock, Illinois where the film was mostly shot has staged an annual Groundhog Day festival, featuring a dinner dance, free screenings of the movie, and a walking tour of the opera house, bowling alley, movie theater, [[Loyal Order of Moose|Moose Lodge]] (site of the dinner dance scene), the piano teacher's house, Cherry Street Inn, and other locations from the film.<ref name=\"location\" />\n\nOn February 2, 2016, fans of the film in [[Liverpool]] experienced their own \"Groundhog Day\" by [[binge-watching]] the film 12 times in 24 hours.<ref>{{cite web | title= Groundhog Day for 'hardcore' film fans in Liverpool |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-merseyside-35473935| author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|date= February 2, 2016 | website= [[BBC News Online]] | accessdate= February 2, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==Related media==\n=== Stage adaptation ===\n{{Main|Groundhog Day (musical)}}\nAlthough [[Stephen Sondheim]] expressed interest in creating a musical adaption of the film in 2003,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/sondheim-talks-about-bounce-revisions-in-works-114941 | title=Sondheim Talks About Bounce; Revisions in Works | publisher=[[Playbill]] | work=playbill.com | date=August 26, 2003 | accessdate=May 16, 2015}}</ref> he eventually concluded that \"... to make a musical of ''Groundhog Day'' would be to gild the lily. It cannot be improved.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roundaboutchat.com/chat/chat_transcript.html |title=Roundabout Live Chat |accessdate=May 19, 2015 |date=May 5, 2008 |publisher=Roundabout Theatre |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426070311/http://www.roundaboutchat.com/chat/chat_transcript.html |archivedate=April 26, 2012 }}</ref> Nevertheless, Ramis announced in 2009 that Rubin was working on an adaptation.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://moviesblog.mtv.com/2009/03/31/exclusive-groundhog-day-musical-in-the-works-says-harold-ramis/ | title='Groundhog Day' Musical In The Works, Says Harold Ramis | publisher=[[MTV News]] | work=moviesblog.mtv.com | date=March 31, 2009 | accessdate=May 17, 2015}}</ref>  At a 2014 concert in [[Hyde Park, London|Hyde Park]], the Australian comedian and lyricist [[Tim Minchin]] performed a song he had written for the show, \"Seeing You\".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/tim-minchins-groundhog-day-musical-gets-off-the-ground-watch-song-performed-324642 | title=Tim Minchin's Groundhog Day Musical Gets Off the Ground; Watch Song Performed in London (Video) | publisher=[[Playbill]] | work=playbill.com | date=July 17, 2014 | accessdate=May 17, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe musical was officially confirmed in April 2015, with a book by Rubin based on his and Ramis's original screenplay,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/04/02/itll-be-groundhog-day-on-broadway-for-matilda-team/? | title=It'll Be 'Groundhog Day' on Broadway for 'Matilda' Team | publisher=[[The New York Times]] | work=artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com | date=April 2, 2015 | accessdate=May 17, 2015}}</ref> directed by [[Matthew Warchus]],<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/arts/stage/article4417434.ece | title=Nothing will ever be the same again: now it's Groundhog Day the musical | publisher=[[The Times]] | work= TheTimes.co.uk | date=April 21, 2015 | accessdate=May 17, 2015}}</ref> choreography by [[Peter Darling]],<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2015/apr/03/tim-minchin-groundhog-day-musical-broadway-2017 | title=Tim Minchin's Groundhog Day musical confirmed for 2017 | publisher=[[The Guardian]] | work=theguardian.com | date=April 3, 2015 | accessdate=May 17, 2015}}</ref> design by [[Rob Howell]],<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/theatre/theatre-news/11514063/Encore-Groundhog-Day-to-open-on-Broadway.html | title=Encore! Groundhog Day to open on Broadway | publisher=[[Telegraph Media Group|The Telegraph]] | work=telegraph.co.uk | date=April 3, 2015 | accessdate=May 17, 2015}}</ref> and an original score and lyrics by Minchin.<ref>{{cite web | date=January 15, 2014 |author= Ryan Reed | url= https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/tim-minchin-writing-groundhog-day-stage-musical-20140115 | title=Tim Minchin Writing 'Groundhog Day' Stage Musical | publisher=[[Rolling Stone]] | work= RollingStone.com | accessdate= May 17, 2015 }}</ref> The production reunites most of the creative team behind the 2010 musical ''[[Matilda the Musical|Matilda]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/theatre-dance/news/groundhog-day-musical-tim-minchin-to-write-lyrics-with-matilda-collaborators-also-attached-10158116.html | title=Groundhog Day musical: Tim Minchin to write lyrics with Matilda collaborators also attached | publisher=[[The Independent]] | work= Independent.co.uk | date=April 6, 2015 | accessdate=May 16, 2015}}</ref>  It premiered in 2016 at [[The Old Vic]] theatre in London<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/warchus-announces-first-season-at-old-vic-including-pre-broadway-groundhog-day-347259 | title=Warchus Announces First Season at Old Vic, Including Pre-Broadway Groundhog Day | publisher=[[Playbill]] | work=playbill.com | date=April 21, 2015 | accessdate=May 17, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/theatre-dance/news/kevin-spaceys-successor-at-the-old-vic-promises-a-more-lowkey-approach-10191051.html | title=Groundhog Day musical to premiere at Old Vic from Matilda theatre director | publisher=[[The Independent]] | work=independent.co.uk | date=April 20, 2015 | accessdate=May 17, 2015}}</ref> as part of Warchus's debut season as artistic director there.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/wires/ap/article-3047961/Groundhog-Day-musical-premiere-Londons-Old-Vic.html | title='Groundhog Day' musical to premiere at London's Old Vic | publisher=[[Daily Mail]] | work= Dailymail.co.uk | date=April 21, 2015 | accessdate=May 17, 2015}}</ref>  [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] performances began in March 2017.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Photo-Flash-Welcome-to-Smalltown-USA-First-Look-at-GROUNDHOG-DAY-on-Broadway-20170328 | title=Photo Flash: Welcome to Smalltown, USA! First Look at GROUNDHOG DAY on Broadway | publisher=[[Broadway World]] | work=brodawayworld.com | date=March 28, 2017 | accessdate=March 29, 2015}}</ref> The musical was well-received, with both the London and Broadway shows receiving a number of nominations and awards, including the [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best New Musical]] for the London production.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2017/mar/06/olivier-awards-2017-full-list-of-nominations|title=Olivier Awards 2017 Full List|work=The Guardian|date=March 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Video game sequel ===\n[[Sony Pictures]]' [[virtual reality]] division, along with game developer [[Tequila Works]], developed a sequel to the film via way of a virtual reality video game, ''Groundhog Day: Like Father Like Son'' which was released on September 17, 2019 on the [[PlayStation VR]], [[Oculus Rift]], and [[HTC Vive]] headsets. The game has the player take the role of Phil's son, Phil Connors, Jr., who similarly becomes trapped in a time loop while in Punxsutawney and requires the player to figure out how to escape it.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://kotaku.com/groundhog-day-like-father-like-son-is-a-psvr-game-and-1832290309  |title = Groundhog Day: Like Father Like Son Is A PSVR Game And A Sequel To The Bill Murray Film | first = Zack | last = Zweiden |date = February 2, 2019 | accessdate = February 2, 2019 | work = [[Kotaku]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2019/02/26-years-later-groundhog-day-gets-revived-as-a-vr-game/ | title=  26 years later, Groundhog Day gets revived as\u2026 a VR game? | first = Kyle | last= Orland | date = February 2, 2019 | accessdate = February 2, 2019 | work = [[Ars Technica]] }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of films featuring time loops]]\n\n== References == \n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book|last=Gilbey|first=Ryan|title=Groundhog Day|url=https://archive.org/details/groundhogday0000gilb|url-access=registration|location=London|publisher=British Film Institute|year=2004 |isbn=1-84457-032-0}}\n* {{cite book|last=Rubin|first=Danny|title=How to Write \"Groundhog Day\"|location=Boston|publisher=Triad Publishing|year=2012|asin= B0072PEV6U}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Groundhog Day (film)|Groundhog Day}}\n{{Wikiquote|Groundhog Day (film)|Groundhog Day}}\n{{Wiktionary|Groundhog Day}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=0107048|title=Groundhog Day}}\n* {{tcmdb title|id=21023|title=Groundhog Day}}\n* {{AllMovie title|20982|Groundhog Day}}\n* {{AFI film|id=59539|title=Groundhog Day}}\n* {{mojo title|groundhogday|Groundhog Day}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|id=groundhog_day|title=Groundhog Day}}\n\n{{Harold Ramis}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1993 films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:1990s comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:1990s fantasy-comedy films]]\n[[Category:American comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:American fantasy-comedy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:BAFTA winners (films)]]\n[[Category:Columbia Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by George Fenton]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Harold Ramis]]\n[[Category:Films set in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Films set in Pittsburgh]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Films whose writer won the Best Original Screenplay BAFTA Award]]\n[[Category:Holiday-themed films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Harold Ramis]]\n[[Category:Time loop films]]\n[[Category:United States National Film Registry films]]\n[[Category:Woodstock, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Films adapted into plays]]\n[[Category:Films involved in plagiarism controversies]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Danny Rubin]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Harold Ramis]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Groundhog Day\n| image          = Groundhog Day (movie poster).jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Harold Ramis]]\n| producer       = {{ubl|Trevor Albert|Harold Ramis}}\n| screenplay     = {{ubl|[[Danny Rubin]]|Harold Ramis}}\n| story          = Danny Rubin\n| starring       = {{Plain list|\n* [[Bill Murray]]\n* [[Andie MacDowell]]\n* [[Chris Elliott]]\n}}\n| music          = [[George Fenton]]\n| cinematography = [[John Bailey (cinematographer)|John Bailey]]\n| editing        = [[Pembroke J. Herring]]\n| distributor    = [[Columbia Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1993|2|12}}\n| runtime        = 101 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $14.6 million<ref name=\"Numbers\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Groundhog-Day#tab=summary |title=Groundhog Day \u2013 Box Office Data, DVD and Blu-ray Sales, Movie News, Cast and Crew Information |website=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] |access-date=November 30, 2014}}</ref>\n| gross          = $70.9 million {{No wrap|(North America)}}<ref name=\"Mojo\">{{Cite web |url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=groundhogday.htm |title=Groundhog Day (1993) |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |access-date=May 5, 2010}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Groundhog Day''''' is a 1993 American <!-- DON'T CHANGE GENRES WITHOUT DISCUSSION --> [[fantasy comedy]] film directed by [[Harold Ramis]] and written by Ramis and [[Danny Rubin]]. It stars [[Bill Murray]] as Phil Connors, a TV weatherman who, during an assignment covering the annual [[Groundhog Day]] event, is caught in a [[time loop]], repeatedly reliving the same day. [[Andie MacDowell]] and [[Chris Elliott]] co-star.\n\n''Groundhog Day'' was a modest success on release and garnered generally positive reviews. It later attracted critical acclaim and is often included in lists of the best comedy films. The term \"groundhog day\" is now commonly used in the English language to describe a recurring situation. In 2006, the film was added to the United States [[National Film Registry]] as being deemed \"culturally, historically, or aesthetically significant\".<ref>{{Cite press release |title=Films Added to National Film Registry for 2006 |date=December 27, 2006 |publisher=[[Library of Congress]] |url=https://www.loc.gov/today/pr/2006/06-234.html |access-date=May 5, 2010}}</ref> [[Groundhog Day (musical)|A stage musical adaptation]] premiered in 2016.\n\n==Plot==\nOn February 1st, weatherman Phil Connors reassures [[Pittsburgh]] viewers that an approaching blizzard will miss [[Western Pennsylvania]]. He goes with news producer Rita Hanson and cameraman Larry to [[Punxsutawney, Pennsylvania]], to cover the [[Groundhog Day]] festivities, which he has done for several years. Phil makes no secret of his contempt for the assignment, the small town, and the \"hicks\" who live there.\n\nThe next day, February 2nd, Phil awakens at his Punxsutawney [[bed and breakfast]] to [[Sonny & Cher]]'s \"[[I Got You Babe]]\" on the clock radio. He tapes a half-hearted report on [[Punxsutawney Phil]] and the town's festivities. Rita wants to stay and cover other events, but Phil wants to return to Pittsburgh. The blizzard blankets the region in snow, stranding them in Punxsutawney. Phil shuns the celebrations and retires to bed early.\n\nPhil wakes to \"I Got You Babe\" and the same DJ banter on the radio, and discovers the day's events repeating exactly. Phil relives the day and returns to bed, assuming it was a dream, but it is again February 2nd when he wakes : he is trapped in a [[time loop]] that no one else is aware of. Realizing there are no consequences for his actions, he spends the first several loops indulging in binge eating and drinking, one-night stands, robbery, and reckless driving. After spending several loops trying and failing to court Rita, he becomes depressed and desperate for a solution to end the loop. He tries numerous times to commit suicide, including going so far as to kidnap Punxsutawney Phil and drive off a cliff with him, but he continuously wakes up to \"I Got You Babe\" on the radio.\n\nPhil tries to explain his situation to Rita, for whom he has feelings, by accurately predicting the day's events. Rita sympathizes, and they spend the entirety of one loop together, but Phil wakes up alone as usual. He decides to use his knowledge of the day's events to better himself and the lives of others; he learns how to play the piano, sculpt ice, and speak French, but is unable to save a homeless man, who dies regardless of his actions.\n\nDuring one loop, Phil enthusiastically reports the Groundhog Day festivities, amazing Rita. They spend the rest of the day together, and Phil impresses her with his apparent overnight transformation and charitable deeds. She successfully bids for Phil at a charity bachelor auction. Phil makes an ice sculpture of Rita's face, and tells her that no matter what happens, even if he is doomed to continue awakening alone each morning forever, he wants her to know that he is finally happy, because he loves her. They retire together to Phil's lodgings. Phil wakes to \"I Got You Babe\" again, but finds Rita is still in bed with him and the radio banter is different; it is now February 3rd, he has escaped the time loop. He tells Rita he wants to live together with her in Punxsutawney.\n\n== Cast ==\n[[File:Andiegroundhog.png|thumb|Andie MacDowell with a groundhog, 2008]]\n{{Cast listing|\n* [[Bill Murray]] as Phil Connors\n* [[Andie MacDowell]] as Rita Hanson\n* [[Chris Elliott]] as Larry the cameraman\n* [[Stephen Tobolowsky]] as Ned Ryerson\n* [[Brian Doyle-Murray]] as Buster Green\n* [[Angela Paton]] as Mrs. Lancaster\n* [[Rick Ducommun]] as Gus\n* [[Rick Overton]] as Ralph\n* [[Robin Duke]] as Doris the waitress\n* [[Marita Geraghty]] as Nancy Taylor\n* [[Harold Ramis]] as Neurologist\n* [[Richard Henzel]] as D.J. #1\n* Rob Riley as D.J. #2\n* [[David Pasquesi]] as Psychiatrist\n* [[Hynden Walch]] as Debbie the bride\n* [[Michael Shannon]] as Fred the groom\n* Rod Sell as Groundhog official\n* [[Ken Hudson Campbell]] as Man in the hallway\n}}\n\n== Production ==\n===Concept===\nDanny Rubin had completed and sold his script for ''[[Hear No Evil (1993 film)|Hear No Evil]]'' and moved from Chicago to Los Angeles to become a professional screenwriter around 1990.<ref name=\"telegraph interview\">{{cite web | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/2016/08/07/how-i-wrote-the-script-for-groundhog-day-in-less-than-a-week/ | title = How I wrote the script for Groundhog Day in less than a week | first = Danny | last = Rubin | date = August 7, 2016 | accessdate = February 27, 2017 | work = [[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] }}</ref> His agent suggested that he prepare a \"calling-card\" script that he could use to gain meetings with various producers.<ref name=\"telegraph interview\"/> He came up with the core idea of the script which would become ''Groundhog Day'' while sitting in a movie theater.<ref name=\"telegraph interview\"/> He asked himself the question \"If a person could live forever, if a person was immortal, how would they change over time?\"<ref name=\"bigthink rubin\">{{Cite web | url = http://bigthink.com/videos/big-think-interview-with-danny-rubin | title = Big Think Interview With Danny Rubin | first=  Paul | last = Hoffman | date = May 10, 2010 | accessdate = February 24, 2017 | work = [[Big Think]] }}</ref> Having this character be immortal and having the world change around them would have been too cumbersome for filming. Instead he came back to a concept he had written down about two years earlier about a man living the same day over and over. With the idea of a person changing over time, this repeating day motif found its \"deeper purpose\" within the new script.<ref name=\"telegraph interview\"/> The two ideas, combined, answered his proverbial question as well as opened up several possibilities of drama and comedy with that framework.<ref name=\"bigthink rubin\"/>\n\nRubin first conceived of the dating aspect for the film, \"being able to use your superior knowledge to pick up women\", which led to the film leaning more to the comedy side.<ref name=\"bigthink rubin\"/> He knew he needed some calendar date to use for the day, and his earlier concept had the character reliving a late January day over and over; when he looked at his calendar, he saw Groundhog Day, February 2, as a date with great potential as a recognized holiday but one with little fanfare, and a date on which the film could be played annually, similar to Christmas or Halloween specials. Groundhog Day also presented Rubin with the idea of being able to take his character out of his home town into the unfamiliar territory and relative isolation of Punxsutawney, and cementing the character being named Phil in honor of Punxsutawney Phil, as well as making him a weatherman.<ref name=\"telegraph interview\"/><ref name=\"bigthink rubin\"/> Rubin took about seven weeks to fix the basic concepts and \"rules\" for the time loop in the film, and then completed the first draft of the screenplay within three to four days.<ref name=\"bigthink rubin\"/>\n\nRubin started to shop the screenplay to around 50 producers. While many studios expressed interest, they told him they would not be able to film it, though Rubin was able to secure additional work through these meetings. After his own agent left the industry, Rubin hired a [[Spec script|spec agent]] to help sell the script more. The script got to the hands of Richard Lovett in the [[Creative Artists Agency]], who was able to get it to Harold Ramis around 1991, leading to Ramis offering to produce the film.<ref name=\"bigthink rubin\"/><ref name=\"new yorker\"/>\n\n===Writing and casting===\nIn the first draft of the script, Rubin had not wanted to have to explain to the audience how Phil got in the loop, and so had the movie start ''[[in medias res]]'', with Phil already in the midst of the looping; the audience would have followed one of his days after waking up to \"I Got You Babe\" where he is already aware of what will be happening, and thus provoking the audience's curiosity; the film would then have used voice-over narration by Phil to provide some of the backstory.<ref name=\"bigthink rubin\"/> Rita would also confess to being trapped in a time loop of her own.<ref name=\"Mentalfloss\">{{cite web|last1=Cormier|first1=Roger|title=16 Repeatable Facts About 'Groundhog Day'|url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/70147/16-repeatable-facts-about-groundhog-day|website=Mental Floss|accessdate=March 26, 2016}}</ref> Rubin considered this draft to be more in line with the black comedy ''[[Kind Hearts and Coronets]]'', particularly with regards to how Phil's suicides were presented.<ref name=\"telegraph interview\"/>\n\nWhile Ramis wanted to keep this approach, the studio applied pressure to use a more standard narrative structure, forcing Rubin to rewrite the script under Ramis's direction.<ref name=\"bigthink rubin\"/> A major change was to restructure the film as a standard three-act piece.<ref name=\"uproxx rift\">{{cite web | url = http://uproxx.com/movies/the-story-behind-bill-murray-and-harold-ramis-21-year-rift/ | title = The Story Behind Bill Murray And Harold Ramis's 21 Year Rift | first = Dariel | last = Figueroa | date = September 21, 2014 | accessdate = February 25, 2017 | work = [[Uproxx]] }}</ref> This second draft of the screenplay established the reason for Phil being put in a time loop, according to actor [[Eddie Deezen]]. In that version, Phil unceremoniously dumps his current girlfriend Stephanie during the introductory scenes of the film at the studio. While Phil is at Punxsutawney, a scorned Stephanie devises a way to cast a spell to trap Phil within the loop for 10,000 years.<ref name=\"deezen\">{{cite web | url = http://www.neatorama.com/2012/02/01/why-did-bill-murray-keep-going-back-in-groundhog-day/ | title = Why Did Bill Murray Keep Going Back in Groundhog Day? | author = Miss Cellonia | date = February 1, 2012 | accessdate = February 21, 2017 | work = [[Neatorama]] }}</ref> According to Rubin, he felt that he had taken a defensive position in writing these new scenes, feeling that it would \"take away everything that was innovative and interesting and turn it into an easily-dismissed Hollywood comedy\", and acknowledges that Ramis interceded on his behalf to remove these explanatory scenes while keeping the three-act format.<ref name=\"telegraph interview\"/>\n\nAnother change in the second draft was to change Phil's attitude from having come to accept the nature of the time loop, to one that was more optimistic about being able to end the loop, making the role more suited to Murray's comedy talents.<ref name=\"new yorker\"/> Ramis had known Murray since their days in [[The Second City]] improv troupe and had used him in several successful films prior to ''Groundhog Day'', so he knew how to play on his strengths to convince Murray to take the role. Prior to Murray's casting, [[Tom Hanks]]<ref name=\"Hollywoodreporterhanks\">{{cite web|title=Happy 'Groundhog Day': Here's 5 Things You Didn't Know About the Movie|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/happy-groundhog-day-heres-5-769137|website=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=March 26, 2016}}</ref> and [[Michael Keaton]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Acuna|first1=Kristen|title=Why Michael Keaton Turned Down The Chance To Star In 'Groundhog Day' And 'Lost'|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/michael-keaton-turned-down-caddyshack-lost-2014-10|website=Business Insider|accessdate=March 26, 2016}}</ref> turned down the lead role.\n\n===Filming===\n[[File:Groundhog day tip top bistro.jpg|thumb|left|Tip Top Bistro, established at the site of the fictional Tip Top Cafe in Woodstock]]\nPrior to filming, and to gain a better understanding of the event, Rubin and Murray attended the 1992 Groundhog Day festival in Punxsutawney.  They remained discreet and did not reveal the intent of their visit.<ref>{{cite web | url =  http://www.philly.com/news/groundhog-billmuray-punxsutawney-pittsburgh-holiday-weird-eagles-20190202.html | title=  Groundhog Day, the improbable holiday that brings a shot in the arm to a former coal town | first = Jason | last = Nark | date = February 2, 2019 | accessdate =February 3, 2019 | work = [[The Philadelphia Inquirer]] }}</ref> The film was shot in [[Woodstock, Illinois]], {{convert|60|miles|abbr=off}} northwest of [[Chicago]] near the [[Wisconsin]] border, because Punxsutawney \"didn't have a town center that looked good on camera\", according to Ramis,<ref name=\"Mentalfloss\"/> and because Punxsutawney's remote location (located two hours from Pittsburgh and not near any major highways or airports) magnified the logistical problems and expense of filming there.<ref>[http://pittsburgh.about.com/cs/punxsutawney/a/groundhog_day.htm What the Heck is Groundhog Day Anyway?] pittsburgh.about.com, retrieved August 9, 2016.</ref><ref name=\"morning call\"/> Woodstock was a suitable replacement for Pennsylvania in the winter months; further, Ramis knew the area as a [[List of people from Chicago|Chicago native]] and recognized it would be easy to obtain licenses to film there and operate the film's production during the winter months.<ref name=\"morning call\"/> Punxsutawney officials, miffed that their town had been passed over, refused to allow the real Punxsutawney Phil to appear in the movie,<ref name=\"Mentalfloss\"/> but sent representatives to Woodstock to make sure the ceremony was being depicted accurately;<ref>[http://www.midniteticket.com/blog/15-behind-the-scenes-factoids-from-the-harold-ramis-groundhog-day-commentary ''Groundhog Day''.] MidniteTicket.com, retrieved August 9, 2016.</ref> according to producer Trevor Albert, the Punxsutawney officials \"were actually very pleased\" with their recreation of Gobbler's Knob, the site near Punxsutawney used for the Groundhog Day ceremonies.<ref name=\"morning call\"/> Filming began on March 16, 1992, and continued through May. Much of the filming was done in colder-than-normal weather, with Murray saying that temperatures were often under {{convert|20|F|C}}, and had snowfall that lasted through May.<ref name=\"morning call\">{{Cite web | url = http://articles.mcall.com/1993-02-12/features/2902959_1_groundhog-day-punxsutawney-phil-harold-ramis | title = Groundhog Sinks Teeth Into Film Role Bill Murray Calls Co-star `Cranky' | first = Paul | last=  Willistein | date = February 12, 1993 | accessdate = February 24, 2017 | work = [[The Morning Call]] }}</ref>\n[[File:Groundhog day movie 1992 location 2007-03-18 IMG 4313.JPG|thumb|right|The \"Cherry Street Inn\", which was a private home at the time of filming, is on Fremont Street]]\nPunxsutawney Phil was played by a series of groundhogs collectively known as Scooter. \"[The animals] hated my guts from day one,\" said Murray, who was bitten twice during shooting, including during the filming of the scene where he drives himself and Phil into a ravine. The bites were severe enough that he was forced to undergo precautionary [[Rabies vaccine|rabies immunization]] afterward.<ref name=\"morning call\"/><ref>[http://articles.philly.com/1993-02-07/entertainment/25955852_1_groundhog-s-day-phil-connors-punxsutawney-phil Bill Murray And The Beast Filming \"Groundhog Day\" Turned Out To Be A Nightmare For The Actor. His Furry Co-star Had A Hankering For His Blood.] ''The Philadelphia Inquirer'', February 7, 1993, retrieved August 9, 2016.</ref>\n\nThe Tip Top Cafe, where many indoor scenes took place, was a set created for the film, but it became an actual restaurant, the Tip Top Bistro, following the movie's success. Later, it became a coffee and Italian ice cream shop,<ref name=\"location\">[http://www.locationshub.com/blog/2013/10/26/about-those-famous-groundhog-days-filming-locations ''Groundhog Day'' filming locations].locationshub.com, retrieved August 9, 2016.</ref> and now is a [[Taco stand|taqueria]].<ref name=\"roadsideamerica.com\">{{cite web | url=http://sightseeker.blogspot.com/2014/07/groundhogday.html | title=Groundhogday Puddle scene location after 20 years. | accessdate=January 4, 2015}}</ref> The Cherry Street Inn, the [[Queen Anne style architecture in the United States|Queen Anne]]-[[Victorian architecture|Victorian]] bed and breakfast where Murray's character stayed, was a private home at the time of filming. Today, it is an actual bed and breakfast.<ref name=\"location\"/>\n\nDuring filming, Murray was in the midst of marital problems and several members of the crew reported his attitude as being erratic. Murray had wanted to make the film more contemplative and less of a comedy, contrary to Ramis's view. Rather than have to handle Murray's constant phone calls, Ramis had Murray work with Rubin in New York City directly to adjust the script to satisfy Murray's requests.<ref name=\"new yorker\">{{cite web |url = http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2004/04/19/comedy-first?currentPage=all | title = Comedy First | first= Tad | last = Friend | date = April 19, 2004 | accessdate = February 25, 2017 | work = [[The New Yorker]] }}</ref> Actor [[Stephen Tobolowsky]] described the script changes: \"When I got the part, it was still kind of a mediocre Bill Murray movie,\" he said. \"You know, Bill Murray, with no consequences, in comic situations ... It wasn't until we got into the shooting that everything turned on its head. And it became not only a good movie, not only a great movie, but a classic.\"<ref name=\"ned-ryerson\"/>\n\nDuring the time he was working with Rubin, Murray refused to talk to Ramis, according to Rubin. When Murray returned to Woodstock to complete filming, Ramis described his behavior as \"just really irrationally mean\", and difficult to work with.<ref name=\"new yorker\"/> Following the filming, Ramis and Murray's longtime collaboration and friendship ended abruptly, without public explanation. Except for a few words at a wake, and later at a bar mitzvah, the two men did not speak for over 20 years after the film's release.<ref name=\"new yorker\"/><ref>{{cite news | last=Heisler | first=Steve | url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/harold-ramis,29410/ | title=Harold Ramis &#124; Film | newspaper=A.V. Club | accessdate=August 31, 2009}}</ref> Murray finally initiated a reconciliation\u2014at the suggestion of [[Brian Doyle Murray]]\u2014only after Ramis entered the final stages of his terminal illness.<ref>{{cite web | last=Wakeman | first=Gregory | title=How Groundhog Day Ruined Bill Murray And Harold Ramis' Partnership|url=http://www.cinemablend.com/new/How-Groundhog-Day-Ruined-Bill-Murray-Harold-Ramis-Partnership-67345.html | work = Cinema Blend  |accessdate=May 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Music==\nSongs featured in the film include:\n\n*\"Weatherman\" by [[Delbert McClinton]]\n*\"[[I Got You Babe]]\" by [[Sonny & Cher]]\n*\"[[Pennsylvania Polka]]\" by [[Frank Yankovic]]\n*\"[[You Don't Know Me]]\" by [[Ray Charles]]\n*\"[[Rhapsody on a Theme of Paganini]]\"\n*\"[[Almost Like Being in Love]]\" by [[Nat King Cole]]\n\n==Interpretations and analysis==\nThe film is often considered an allegory of [[self-help|self-improvement]], emphasizing that happiness comes from placing the needs of others above one's own selfish desires. As the released film offers no explanation why the time loop occurs\u2014or why it ends\u2014viewers are left to draw their own conclusions. Rubin has said that while he and Ramis discussed several of the philosophical and spiritual aspects of the film, they \"never intended [it] to be anything more than a good, heartfelt, entertaining story\".<ref name=\"telegraph interview\"/>\n\n\"Groundhog Day\", as an expression, has become shorthand for the concept of [[Transcendence (philosophy)|spiritual transcendence]].<ref>\"The spiritual power of repetitive form: Steps toward transcendence in Groundhog Day\". Suzanne Daughton, ''Critical Studies in Mass Communication.'' Annandale: Jun 1996. Vol. 13, Iss. 2; pg. 138, 17 pgs.</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=Groundhog Almighty | first=Alex | last=Kuczynski | url=http://www.times.com | newspaper=[[The New York Times]] | date=December 7, 2003 | accessdate=October 10, 2009 | quote=Angela Zito, a co-director of the Center for Religion and Media at New York University, screens the film for students in her Buddhism class. She said that ''Groundhog Day'' perfectly illustrates the Buddhist notion of samsara, the continuing cycle of rebirth that Buddhists regard as suffering that humans must try to escape (a belief, Dr. Zito noted, that was missed by executives at Guerlain, who, searching for an exotic name, introduced a perfume called Samsara in the 1980s, overlooking the negative connotations). ''Groundhog Day,'' Dr. Zito said, is a cinematic version of the teachings in Mahayana Buddhism, known as \"the greater vehicle.\" \"In Mahayana,\" she said, \"nobody ever imagines they are going to escape samsara until everybody else does. That is why you have bodhisattvas, who reach the brink of nirvana, and stop and come back and save the rest of us. Bill Murray is the bodhisattva. He is not going to abandon the world. On the contrary, he is released back into the world to save it.\" |archive-url=http://www2.kenyon.edu/Depts/Religion/Fac/Adler/Misc/GroundhogDay.htm |archive-date=December 7, 2003}}</ref> As such, the film has become a favorite of some [[Buddhism|Buddhists]],<ref>{{cite web | title=Groundhog Day The Movie, Buddhism and Me | last=Schindler|first=Paul | url=http://www.schindler.org/psacot/20010813_ghd.shtml | publisher=schindler.org | date= | accessdate=January 25, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last=Garfinkel|first=Perry|publisher=[[Lion's Roar (magazine)|Lion's Roar]] | url=http://www.lionsroar.com/harold-ramis-profile-by-perry-garfinkel/ | title=And If He Sees His Shadow ...|date=February 2, 2014|accessdate=April 5, 2015}}</ref> who see its themes of selflessness and rebirth as reflections of their own spiritual messages. In the Roman Catholic tradition, it has been seen as a representation of [[purgatory]]. \"Connors goes to his own version of hell, but since he's not evil it turns out to be purgatory, from which he is released by shedding his selfishness and committing to acts of love,\" wrote [[Jonah Goldberg]]. \"Meanwhile, Hindus and Buddhists see versions of reincarnation here, and Jews find great significance in the fact that Connors is saved only after he performs ''[[mitzvah]]s'' (good deeds) and is returned to earth, not heaven, to perform more.\" It has even been described by some religious leaders as the \"most spiritual film of our time\".<ref>{{cite news | title=Is this the greatest story ever told? | author=Andrew Buncombe | work=The Independent | url=http://isgodimaginary.com/forum/index.php?topic=31369.0 | publisher=isgodimaginary.com | date=February 2, 2004 | accessdate=January 30, 2013 | location=London}}</ref> \"The curse is lifted when Bill Murray blesses the day he has just lived,\" wrote the critic Rick Brookhiser. \"And his reward is that the day is taken from him. Loving life includes loving the fact that it goes.\"<ref name=\"natrev\"/> Albert said that after the film was released, he was contacted by a Buddhist leader praising him for making a film that captures the ideologies of regeneration, and later from a Jewish group that commenended him for depicting the ideas of ''[[mitzvah]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.thewrap.com/groundhog-day-bill-murray-accidental-classic/ | title = \u2018Groundhog Day': How Bill Murray Rom-Com Became an Accidental Classic | first = Brian | last = Welk | date = February 2, 2020 | accessdate = February 2, 2020 | work = [[The Wrap]] }}</ref>\n\nTheologian Michael P. Foley, writing for ''[[Touchstone Magazine]]'', commented on the difficulty of determining a single religious or philosophical interpretation of the film, given Ramis's \"ambiguous religious beliefs\" as \"an agnostic raised Jewish and married to a Buddhist\", and suggested that when not viewed through a \"single hermeneutical lens\", the film could be seen as \"a stunning allegory of moral, intellectual, and even religious excellence in the face of postmodern decay, a sort of Christian-Aristotelian ''[[The Pilgrim's Progress|Pilgrim's Progress]]'' for those lost in the contemporary cosmos.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Foley|first1=Michael P.|title=Phil's Shadow|magazine=Touchstone|date=April 2004|volume=17|issue=3|url=http://www.touchstonemag.com/archives/article.php?id=17-03-012-v|accessdate=August 19, 2014}}</ref> Others see an interpretation of [[Nietzsche]]'s directive to imagine life\u2014metaphorically or literally\u2014as an [[Eternal recurrence#Friedrich Nietzsche|endless repetition of events]]. \"How would this shape your actions?\" asks Goldberg.  \"What would you choose to live out for all eternity?\"<ref name=\"natrev\"/>\n\n===Time loop duration speculations===\nIn relationship to the spiritual interpretations of the film, many have tried to estimate how long Phil supposedly remains trapped in the loop, in real time, with a wide variance in estimated values. During filming, Ramis observed that according to Buddhist doctrine, it takes 10,000 years for a soul to evolve to its next level.  Therefore, he said, in a spiritual sense, the entire arc of ''Groundhog Day'' spans 10,000 years.<ref name=\"ned-ryerson\">{{cite news | first = Jan | last = Jekelek | title = In Depth With 'Groundhog Day's' Ned Ryerson, Actor Stephen Tobolowsky | date = February 11, 2010 | url = https://www.theepochtimes.com/stephen-tobolowsky-interview_1517660.html | work = Epoch Times | accessdate = March 23, 2013}}</ref> Deezen noted that the second draft of the screenplay called for Phil to be cursed to live the time loop for 10,000 years.<ref name=\"deezen\"/> In the DVD commentary, Ramis estimated a real-time duration of ten years.  Later, Ramis told a reporter, \"I think the 10-year estimate is too short. It takes at least 10 years to get good at anything, and allotting for the down time and misguided years he spent, it had to be more like 30 or 40 years.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.heebmagazine.com/blog/view/2075 | title=Harold Ramis's Response to the Groundhog Day Timeline Study | work=[[Heeb]] | archivedate=April 3, 2010 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100403063830/http://www.heebmagazine.com/blog/view/2075 | access-date=January 31, 2012 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Rubin said, \"Ultimately it became this weird political issue because if you asked the studio, 'How long was the repetition?', they'd say, 'Two weeks'.  But the point of the movie to me was that you had to feel you were enduring something that was going on for a long time ... For me it had to be\u2014I don't know. A hundred years. A lifetime.\"<ref>Gilbey, R. ''Groundhog Day (BFI Modern Classics)''. British Film Institute (2005), pp. 44\u20135. {{ISBN|1844570320}}</ref>  In 2014, the website WhatCulture combined various time duration assumptions and estimated that Phil spent a total of 12,395 days\u2014just under 34 years\u2014reliving Groundhog Day.<ref name=sim>[http://whatculture.com/film/just-how-many-days-does-bill-murray-really-spend-stuck-reliving-groundhog-day \"Just How Many Days Does Bill Murray REALLY Spend Stuck Reliving \u2018Groundhog Day\u2019?\"] by Simon Gallagher, WhatCulture.com</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HYAx9RX1OmY&t=4m47s How Many Days Does Bill Murray Spend Stuck In Groundhog Day?] (uploaded to YouTube by WhatCulture on May 20, 2014, with 491,624 views as of 10/20/17)</ref>\n\n==Release==\n===Critical reception===\nThe film was released to generally favorable reviews. Janet Maslin of ''[[The New York Times]]'' called it \"a particularly witty and resonant comedy\"<ref>{{cite news | url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9F0CEED6123EF931A25751C0A965958260 | title=New York Times Movie Review: Groundhog Day|accessdate=November 29, 2012 | work= [[New York Times]] | first= Janet | last= Maslin |author-link= Janet Maslin | date=February 12, 1993 }}</ref> and Hal Hinson of ''The Washington Post'' called it \"the best American comedy since 'Tootsie'\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/videos/groundhogdaypghinson_a0a7e9.htm|title=Washington Post: \"Groundhog Day\"|accessdate=November 29, 2012 | work=The Washington Post|date=February 12, 1993}}</ref> [[Owen Gleiberman]] of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave it a \"B-\",<ref>{{cite news | date=February 12, 1993 |author= Owen Gleiberman | author-link= Owen Gleiberman |title= Entertainment Weekly Movie Reviews: Groundhog Day |url= https://ew.com/article/1993/02/12/groundhog-day-3/ |accessdate= April 4, 2020 }}</ref> and [[Desson Howe]] of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' noted that even though the film is a good Bill Murray vehicle, \"'Groundhog' will never be designated a national film treasure by the Library of Congress\".<ref>{{cite news |author= Desson Howe | author-link= Desson Howe |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/videos/groundhogdaypghowe_a0af6c.htm|title=Washington Post: \"Groundhog Day\"|accessdate=November 29, 2012 | work=The Washington Post|date=February 12, 1993}}</ref> In 2006, the film was selected by the [[National Film Preservation Board]] for preservation in the [[Library of Congress]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000468/2006|title=National Film Preservation Board, December 27, 2006|accessdate=November 29, 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[Roger Ebert]] gave the film 3 out of 4 stars in his original review.<ref>{{cite web |date= January 30, 2005 |last1= Ebert |first1= Roger |author-link= Roger Ebert |title= Groundhog Day movie review & film summary (1993) |url= https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/great-movie-groundhog-day-1993 |publisher= [[Chicago Sun-Times]] }}</ref> In his \"Great Movies\" essay, Ebert acknowledged that, like many viewers, he had initially underestimated the film's many virtues and only came to truly appreciate it through repeated viewings, and gave it 4 out of 4 stars.<ref>{{cite web |date= February 12, 1993 |last1= Ebert |first1= Roger |author-link= Roger Ebert |title= Groundhog Day movie review & film summary (1993) |url= https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/great-movie-groundhog-day-1993 |publisher= [[Chicago Sun-Times]] }}</ref>\n\nThe film is number 32 on [[Bravo (US TV channel)|Bravo]]'s \"100 Funniest Movies\".{{cn|date=April 2020}} In ''[[Total Film]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s 1990s special issue, ''Groundhog Day'' was deemed the best film of 1993 (the year that saw the release of ''[[Schindler's List]]'', ''[[The Piano]]'', ''[[A Perfect World]]'' and ''[[The Fugitive (1993 film)|The Fugitive]]'').{{cn|date=April 2020}} In 2000, readers of ''Total Film'' voted it the seventh greatest comedy film of all time.{{cn|date=April 2020}} The [[Writers Guild of America]] ranked the [[screenplay]] #27 on their list of 101 Greatest Screenplays ever written.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wga.org/subpage_newsevents.aspx?id=1807 |title=The 101 Greatest Screenplays |accessdate=March 13, 2007 |publisher=Writers Guild of America |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060813151310/http://www.wga.org/subpage_newsevents.aspx?id=1807 |archive-date=August 13, 2006 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wga.org/subpage_newsevents.aspx?id=1807 |last= Savage |first= Sophia |date=February 27, 2013 |title=WGA Lists Greatest Screenplays, From 'Casablanca' and 'Godfather' to 'Memento' and 'Notorious' |accessdate=February 28, 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20060813151310/http://www.wga.org/subpage_newsevents.aspx?id=1807 |archive-date= August 13, 2006 }}</ref> In 2009, American literary theorist [[Stanley Fish]] named the film as among the ten best American films ever, writing that \"as the movie becomes more serious, it becomes funnier. The comedy and the philosophy (how shall one live?) do not sit side by side, but inhabit each other in a unity that is incredibly satisfying.\"<ref>{{cite news | author= [[Stanley Fish]] | title=The 10 Best American Movies | url=http://fish.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/01/04/the-10-best-american-movies | website=The New York Times | date=January 4, 2009 | accessdate=January 6, 2009}}</ref> In 2011, ''[[Time Out (company)|Time Out London]]'' named it the 5th-greatest comedy film of all time.<ref>{{cite web |title = 100 Best Comedy Movies |url = http://www.timeout.com/london/film/100-best-comedy-movies-the-full-list |publisher=Time Out London |accessdate=September 17, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn terms of retrospective reviews, ''Groundhog Day'' holds a 96% \"Certified Fresh\" rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] from 79 critics. The site's consensus reads \"Smart, sweet, and inventive, ''Groundhog Day'' highlights Murray's dramatic gifts while still leaving plenty of room for laughs\".<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/groundhog_day/ | title=Groundhog Day|website=Rotten Tomatoes | accessdate=October 17, 2012}}</ref> The film is regarded as a contemporary classic. It has a score of 72 out of 100 at Metacritic, indicating \"Generally favorable reviews.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/groundhog-day/critic-reviews|title=Groundhog Day \u2013 Metacritic|accessdate=November 29, 2012}}</ref> Audiences surveyed by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film a grade B+ on scale of A to F.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |title= GROUNDHOG DAY (1993) B+ |work= [[CinemaScore]] |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181220122629/https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |archive-date= 2018-12-20 }}</ref>\n\n===Box office===\nThe film was a solid performer in its initial release, grossing $70.9 million in [[North America]] and ranking [[1993 in film|12th among films released in 1993]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?yr=1993&p=.htm | title=1993 Domestic Grosses}}</ref> It was nominated for the [[Hugo Award for Best Dramatic Presentation]], but lost to ''[[Jurassic Park (film)|Jurassic Park]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/1994-hugo-awards/ |title=1994 Hugo Awards |publisher=World Science Fiction Society |accessdate=October 17, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110507072941/http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/1994-hugo-awards/ |archive-date=May 7, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n* [[BAFTA Award for Best Original Screenplay]] 1994\n* [[British Comedy Awards]] 1993 (Comedy Film)\n* [[Saturn Award for Best Actress (Film)]] (Andie MacDowell)\n\nIn June 2008, AFI revealed its \"Ten Top Ten\"\u2014the best ten films in ten \"classic\" American film genres\u2014after polling over 1,500 people from the creative community. ''Groundhog Day'' was acknowledged as the eighth best film in the fantasy genre.<ref>{{cite news | author = [[American Film Institute]] | title = AFI Crowns Top 10 Films in 10 Classic Genres | work = ComingSoon.net | date = June 17, 2008 | url = http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=46072 | accessdate= June 18, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title= Top 10 Fantasy | url = http://www.afi.com/10top10/fantasy.html | publisher= [[American Film Institute]] |accessdate= June 18, 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe film is recognized by [[American Film Institute]] in these lists:\n* [[AFI's 100 Years ... 100 Laughs]] \u2013 #34<ref>{{cite web|last= |first= |title=AFI's 100 Years ... 100 Laughs |url=http://www.afi.com/Docs/100Years/laughs100.pdf |publisher=[[American Film Institute]] |date= |accessdate=August 6, 2016}}</ref>\n* 2008: [[AFI's 10 Top 10]]: #8 Fantasy Film<ref>{{cite web|last= |first= |title=AFI's 10 Top 10: Top 10 Fantasy |url=http://www.afi.com/10top10/category.aspx?cat=6 |publisher=[[American Film Institute]] |date= |accessdate=August 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Home media ===\n''Groundhog Day'' was released on DVD on January 29, 2008, it was released on Blu-Ray on January 27, 2009.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dvdsreleasedates.com/movies/1018/Groundhog-Day-(1993).html|title=Groundhog Day DVD Release Date|website=DVDs Release Dates|language=en-US|access-date=June 14, 2018}}</ref>{{notinsource|date=February 2020}} ''Groundhog Day'' was also released on [[Ultra HD Blu-ray]] on January 23, 2018.<ref>{{Citation|title=Groundhog Day 4K Blu-ray|url=http://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Groundhog-Day-4K-Blu-ray/178887/|accessdate=June 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nThe narrative of a protagonist trapped in a time loop, where escape is possible only after accumulating knowledge through multiple passes, is a popular [[trope (literary)|trope]] in fictional works.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://io9.gizmodo.com/5206173/lets-do-the-time-loop-again-and-again | title = Let's Do The Time Loop Again. And Again ...| first=  Charlie Jane | last = Anders | date = April 10, 2009 | accessdate = February 24, 2017 | work = [[io9]] }}</ref> Rubin noted that with his script, he \"stumbled upon a story with all the makings of a classic, so simple and true that it could be retold many different ways by many different storytellers.\"<ref name=\"telegraph interview\" /> The concept of a time loop in fiction did not originate with ''Groundhog Day''; one earlier identified example is the 1973 [[short story]] \"[[12:01 PM]]\" by [[Richard A. Lupoff]], published in ''[[The Magazine of Fantasy and Science Fiction]]'' predates the film, as well as two adaptions,  [[12:01 PM (1990 film)|a 1990 short film]], and [[12:01 (1993 film)|a 1993 television movie]].<ref name=\"npost 2018\">{{Cite web | url = https://nationalpost.com/entertainment/movies/from-groundhog-day-to-looper-a-brief-history-of-cinematic-time-loops | title = From Groundhog Day to Looper, a brief history of cinematic time loops | first=  Chris | last = Knight | date = February 2, 2018 | accessdate = July 5, 2018 | work = [[The National Post]] }}</ref> The writers and producers of \"12:01 P.M.\" believed that their work was stolen by ''Groundhog Day'' but abandoned [[12:01 (1993 film)#Legal action|legal action]] against the film makers.<ref name=\"npost 2018\" /><ref name=\"timebinders\">{{cite web   |url=http://www.fanac.org/timebinders/lupoff.html  |title=SF Recollections by Richard Lupoff   |work=Timebinders |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140728235202/http://fanac.org/timebinders/lupoff.html  |archive-date=July 28, 2014  |url-status=live  |accessdate=September 16, 2014  }}</ref> The film's time loop concept is also predated by [[Mamoru Oshii]]'s 1984 [[anime]] film ''[[Urusei Yatsura 2: Beautiful Dreamer]]'', where a high-school class relives the same day over and over again.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hartl|first1=John|title=Disney will Distribute Animated Japanese Movie|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19980903&slug=2769906|accessdate=May 15, 2017|date=September 3, 1998}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Off the Shelf \u2013 Urusei Yatsura 2: Beautiful Dreamer |url=https://www.highdefdigest.com/blog/off-the-shelf-urusei-yatsura-2-bluray/ |work=High-Def Digest |date=September 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Camp |first1=Brian |last2=Davis |first2=Julie |title=Anime Classics Zettai!: 100 Must-See Japanese Animation Masterpieces |date=2011 |publisher=[[Stone Bridge Press]] |isbn=9781611725193 |page=10 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PLc22hQhZGwC&pg=PT10}}</ref>\n\nThough not the earliest example, the time loop trope in fiction has been named after ''Groundhog Day'' by the website ''[[TV Tropes]]'' and other sources because the film established the trope in popular culture.<ref>[http://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/GroundhogDayLoop ''Groundhog Day Loop''] on TVTropes.com, retrieved February 24, 2017.</ref>  Such films as ''[[Edge of Tomorrow]]'' and ''[[ARQ (film)|ARQ]]'' have used it,<ref name=\"npost 2018\" /> as have television shows; one of the more recognized examples is ''[[The X-Files]]'' episode \"[[Monday (The X-Files)|Monday]]\".  Other genres, including sit-coms and dramas, have employed it as well. Pilot Viruet, in the magazine ''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]'', wrote, \"Because of the inherent reset button the trope provides, an episode of TV can explore different scenarios, plots, character interactions, and outcomes\u2014and if any of them don't quite feel right, the writers can start over (often with the ringing of a shrill alarm clock).\"<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/the-pop-culture-legacy-of-groundhog-day | title = The Pop Culture Legacy of 'Groundhog Day' | first = Pilot | last = Viruet | work = [[Vice (magazine)|Vice]] | date = February 2, 2017 | accessdate = February 2, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nThe phrase \"Groundhog Day\" has entered common usage as a reference to an unpleasant situation that continually repeats.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/opinion/2004-09-26-hurricane-fatigue_x.htm |title=Hurricane Fatigue |work=[[USA Today]] |date=September 26, 2004 |accessdate=October 10, 2009}}</ref> Goldberg paraphrased the common meaning as \"same stuff, different day\".<ref name=\"natrev\">{{cite web | url = http://www.nationalreview.com/article/228088/movie-all-time-jonah-goldberg | title = A Movie for All Time | first = Jonah | last = Goldberg | date = February 2, 2016 | accessdate = February 2, 2016 | work = [[National Review]] }}</ref>  In the [[military]], referring to unpleasant, unchanging, repetitive situations as \"Groundhog Day\" became widespread soon after the movie's release in February 1993. A magazine article about the aircraft carrier {{USS|America|CV-66|6}} mentions its use by sailors in September 1993.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/usnews/news/articles/940228/archive_012486_4.htm |title=Diplomacy's Gunboat |work=[[U.S. News & World Report]] |date=February 22, 1994 |accessdate=May 10, 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090416201009/http://www.usnews.com/usnews/news/articles/940228/archive_012486_4.htm |archive-date=April 16, 2009 }}</ref> The film was a favorite among the Rangers deployed for [[Operation Gothic Serpent]] in [[Somalia]] in 1993, because they saw the film as a metaphor of their own situation, waiting monotonous long days between raids.<ref>Bowden, [[Black Hawk Down (book)|Black Hawk Down]], Corgi edition, 2000 p.534.</ref> In February 1994, crew members  of the aircraft carrier {{USS|Saratoga|CV-60|6}} referred to their deployment in the Adriatic Sea, in support of [[Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnia]] operations, as Groundhog Station. A speech by [[Bill Clinton|President Clinton]] in January 1996 specifically referred to the movie and the use of the phrase by military personnel in Bosnia.<ref>Remarks to American Troops at Tuzla Airfield, Bosnia-Herzegovina, January 13, 1996.</ref> Fourteen years after the movie's release, \"Groundhog Day\" was noted as common American [[military slang]] for any day of a tour of duty in Iraq, often as a successor to the [[World War II]]-era slang term \"[[wikt:SNAFU|SNAFU]]\" (\"Situation Normal: All Fucked Up\").<ref name=\"natrev\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=7458809|title='Embrace the Suck' and More Military Speak|accessdate=November 26, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn his Iraq War memoir ''Victory Denied'', Maj. Roger Aeschliman describes guarding assorted visiting dignitaries as his \"Groundhog Day\":\n\n{{quote|The dignitary changes but everything else is exactly the same. The same airplanes drop them off at the same places. The same helicopters take us to the same meetings with the same presenters covering the same topics using the same slides. We visit the same troops at the same mess halls and send them away from the same airport pads to find our own way home late at night. Over and over and over and over and over and over and over and over and over until we are redeemed and allowed to go home to Kansas. Amen.<ref>{{cite book | title = Victory Denied: Everything You Know about Iraq is Wrong! | first = Roger T. | last = Aeschliman | isbn = 1434348954 | pages = 306 | publisher = [[Authorhouse]] | year = 2007 }}</ref>}}\n\nIn the 2015 memoir, ''Guant\u00e1namo Diary'', [[Mohamedou Ould Slahi]] refers to the film twice to describe his ongoing confinement in [[Guantanamo, Cuba]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Slahi|first=Mohamedou Ould|authorlink=Mohamedou Ould Slahi|title=[[Mohamedou Ould Slahi#Guant\u00e1namo Diary|Guant\u00e1namo Diary]]|pages=237, 311|publisher=[[Little, Brown and Company]]|year=2015|ISBN=978-0-316-32860-9}}</ref>\n\n[[Member of Parliament]] [[Dennis Skinner]] compared [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|British Prime Minister]] [[Tony Blair]]'s treatment following the 2004 [[Hutton Inquiry]] to the film. \"[The affair] was, he said, like ''Groundhog Day,'' with the prime minister's critics demanding one inquiry, then another inquiry, then another inquiry.\" Blair responded, \"I could not have put it better myself. Indeed I ''did'' not put it better myself.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/3458431.stm|title=Politics: Prime Minister's Questions|date=February 4, 2004|accessdate=May 22, 2008|work=BBC News|author=Nick Assinder}}</ref>\n\nMurray, Doyle-Murray, and Tobolowsky reprised their roles for a ''Groundhog Day''-themed [[Jeep]] commercial aired during [[Super Bowl LIV]] on February 2, 2020, promoting the [[Jeep Gladiator (JT)|Jeep Gladiator]]. The ad was filmed in and around Woodstock, Illinois.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adweek.com/brand-marketing/jeep-teases-groundhog-day-themed-super-bowl-ad/|title=Jeep Teases Groundhog Day-Themed Super Bowl Ad|last=Barwick|first=Ryan|date=January 31, 2020|work=[[Ad Week]]|accessdate=February 2, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.freep.com/story/money/cars/chrysler/2020/02/02/bill-murray-groundhog-day-super-bowl-ad/4638852002/|title=Watch Bill Murray take a groundhog for a spin in a Jeep Gladiator|last=Lawrence|first=Eric|date=February 2, 2020|work=[[Detroit Free Press]]|accessdate=February 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Events===\nThe town of Punxsutawney has seen much larger crowds at the annual Groundhog Day event since the film's release.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://time.com/4655181/groundhog-day-2017-punxsutawney-phil-documentary-animal-planet/ | title = The Surprising Way Groundhog Day Changed the Town of Punxsutawney | first = Olivia | last=  Waxman | date = February 1, 2017 | accessdate = February 1, 2017 | work = [[Time (magazine)|Time]] }}</ref>\n\nSince 1992 the town of Woodstock, Illinois where the film was mostly shot has staged an annual Groundhog Day festival, featuring a dinner dance, free screenings of the movie, and a walking tour of the opera house, bowling alley, movie theater, [[Loyal Order of Moose|Moose Lodge]] (site of the dinner dance scene), the piano teacher's house, Cherry Street Inn, and other locations from the film.<ref name=\"location\" />\n\nOn February 2, 2016, fans of the film in [[Liverpool]] experienced their own \"Groundhog Day\" by [[binge-watching]] the film 12 times in 24 hours.<ref>{{cite web | title= Groundhog Day for 'hardcore' film fans in Liverpool |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-merseyside-35473935| author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|date= February 2, 2016 | website= [[BBC News Online]] | accessdate= February 2, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==Related media==\n=== Stage adaptation ===\n{{Main|Groundhog Day (musical)}}\nAlthough [[Stephen Sondheim]] expressed interest in creating a musical adaption of the film in 2003,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/sondheim-talks-about-bounce-revisions-in-works-114941 | title=Sondheim Talks About Bounce; Revisions in Works | publisher=[[Playbill]] | work=playbill.com | date=August 26, 2003 | accessdate=May 16, 2015}}</ref> he eventually concluded that \"... to make a musical of ''Groundhog Day'' would be to gild the lily. It cannot be improved.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roundaboutchat.com/chat/chat_transcript.html |title=Roundabout Live Chat |accessdate=May 19, 2015 |date=May 5, 2008 |publisher=Roundabout Theatre |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426070311/http://www.roundaboutchat.com/chat/chat_transcript.html |archivedate=April 26, 2012 }}</ref> Nevertheless, Ramis announced in 2009 that Rubin was working on an adaptation.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://moviesblog.mtv.com/2009/03/31/exclusive-groundhog-day-musical-in-the-works-says-harold-ramis/ | title='Groundhog Day' Musical In The Works, Says Harold Ramis | publisher=[[MTV News]] | work=moviesblog.mtv.com | date=March 31, 2009 | accessdate=May 17, 2015}}</ref>  At a 2014 concert in [[Hyde Park, London|Hyde Park]], the Australian comedian and lyricist [[Tim Minchin]] performed a song he had written for the show, \"Seeing You\".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/tim-minchins-groundhog-day-musical-gets-off-the-ground-watch-song-performed-324642 | title=Tim Minchin's Groundhog Day Musical Gets Off the Ground; Watch Song Performed in London (Video) | publisher=[[Playbill]] | work=playbill.com | date=July 17, 2014 | accessdate=May 17, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe musical was officially confirmed in April 2015, with a book by Rubin based on his and Ramis's original screenplay,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/04/02/itll-be-groundhog-day-on-broadway-for-matilda-team/? | title=It'll Be 'Groundhog Day' on Broadway for 'Matilda' Team | publisher=[[The New York Times]] | work=artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com | date=April 2, 2015 | accessdate=May 17, 2015}}</ref> directed by [[Matthew Warchus]],<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/arts/stage/article4417434.ece | title=Nothing will ever be the same again: now it's Groundhog Day the musical | publisher=[[The Times]] | work= TheTimes.co.uk | date=April 21, 2015 | accessdate=May 17, 2015}}</ref> choreography by [[Peter Darling]],<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2015/apr/03/tim-minchin-groundhog-day-musical-broadway-2017 | title=Tim Minchin's Groundhog Day musical confirmed for 2017 | publisher=[[The Guardian]] | work=theguardian.com | date=April 3, 2015 | accessdate=May 17, 2015}}</ref> design by [[Rob Howell]],<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/theatre/theatre-news/11514063/Encore-Groundhog-Day-to-open-on-Broadway.html | title=Encore! Groundhog Day to open on Broadway | publisher=[[Telegraph Media Group|The Telegraph]] | work=telegraph.co.uk | date=April 3, 2015 | accessdate=May 17, 2015}}</ref> and an original score and lyrics by Minchin.<ref>{{cite web | date=January 15, 2014 |author= Ryan Reed | url= https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/tim-minchin-writing-groundhog-day-stage-musical-20140115 | title=Tim Minchin Writing 'Groundhog Day' Stage Musical | publisher=[[Rolling Stone]] | work= RollingStone.com | accessdate= May 17, 2015 }}</ref> The production reunites most of the creative team behind the 2010 musical ''[[Matilda the Musical|Matilda]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/theatre-dance/news/groundhog-day-musical-tim-minchin-to-write-lyrics-with-matilda-collaborators-also-attached-10158116.html | title=Groundhog Day musical: Tim Minchin to write lyrics with Matilda collaborators also attached | publisher=[[The Independent]] | work= Independent.co.uk | date=April 6, 2015 | accessdate=May 16, 2015}}</ref>  It premiered in 2016 at [[The Old Vic]] theatre in London<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/warchus-announces-first-season-at-old-vic-including-pre-broadway-groundhog-day-347259 | title=Warchus Announces First Season at Old Vic, Including Pre-Broadway Groundhog Day | publisher=[[Playbill]] | work=playbill.com | date=April 21, 2015 | accessdate=May 17, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/theatre-dance/news/kevin-spaceys-successor-at-the-old-vic-promises-a-more-lowkey-approach-10191051.html | title=Groundhog Day musical to premiere at Old Vic from Matilda theatre director | publisher=[[The Independent]] | work=independent.co.uk | date=April 20, 2015 | accessdate=May 17, 2015}}</ref> as part of Warchus's debut season as artistic director there.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/wires/ap/article-3047961/Groundhog-Day-musical-premiere-Londons-Old-Vic.html | title='Groundhog Day' musical to premiere at London's Old Vic | publisher=[[Daily Mail]] | work= Dailymail.co.uk | date=April 21, 2015 | accessdate=May 17, 2015}}</ref>  [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] performances began in March 2017.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Photo-Flash-Welcome-to-Smalltown-USA-First-Look-at-GROUNDHOG-DAY-on-Broadway-20170328 | title=Photo Flash: Welcome to Smalltown, USA! First Look at GROUNDHOG DAY on Broadway | publisher=[[Broadway World]] | work=brodawayworld.com | date=March 28, 2017 | accessdate=March 29, 2015}}</ref> The musical was well-received, with both the London and Broadway shows receiving a number of nominations and awards, including the [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best New Musical]] for the London production.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2017/mar/06/olivier-awards-2017-full-list-of-nominations|title=Olivier Awards 2017 Full List|work=The Guardian|date=March 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Video game sequel ===\n[[Sony Pictures]]' [[virtual reality]] division, along with game developer [[Tequila Works]], developed a sequel to the film via way of a virtual reality video game, ''Groundhog Day: Like Father Like Son'' which was released on September 17, 2019 on the [[PlayStation VR]], [[Oculus Rift]], and [[HTC Vive]] headsets. The game has the player take the role of Phil's son, Phil Connors, Jr., who similarly becomes trapped in a time loop while in Punxsutawney and requires the player to figure out how to escape it.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://kotaku.com/groundhog-day-like-father-like-son-is-a-psvr-game-and-1832290309  |title = Groundhog Day: Like Father Like Son Is A PSVR Game And A Sequel To The Bill Murray Film | first = Zack | last = Zweiden |date = February 2, 2019 | accessdate = February 2, 2019 | work = [[Kotaku]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2019/02/26-years-later-groundhog-day-gets-revived-as-a-vr-game/ | title=  26 years later, Groundhog Day gets revived as\u2026 a VR game? | first = Kyle | last= Orland | date = February 2, 2019 | accessdate = February 2, 2019 | work = [[Ars Technica]] }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of films featuring time loops]]\n\n== References == \n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book|last=Gilbey|first=Ryan|title=Groundhog Day|url=https://archive.org/details/groundhogday0000gilb|url-access=registration|location=London|publisher=British Film Institute|year=2004 |isbn=1-84457-032-0}}\n* {{cite book|last=Rubin|first=Danny|title=How to Write \"Groundhog Day\"|locatio